Public Prosecutor v John Sun (previously known as Sng Wee Hock)
[2023] SGDC 77

Case Number:DAC 922412 of 2018 and Others
Decision Date:27 April 2023
Tribunal/Court:District Court
Coram: Christopher Tan
Counsel Name(s): Deputy Public Prosecutors Suhas Malhotra and Gerald Tan (Attorney-General's Chambers) for the Prosecution; Roderick Martin SC and Marshall Lim (Martin & Partners) (instructed) and Daniel Atticus Xu (Exodus Law Corporation) for the Accused.
Parties: Public Prosecutor — John Sun (previously known as Sng Wee Hock)

Criminal Law – Statutory offences – Cheating

Criminal Law – Statutory offences – Forgery

27 April 2023

Judgment reserved

District Judge Christopher Tan:

1       The Accused is a 49-year-old male. He claimed trial to a total of 24 charges, comprising:

(a)     13 charges under s 420 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) (“Penal Code”), for cheating and thereby dishonestly inducing the delivery of property (“cheating charges”); and

(b)     11 charges under s 468 of the Penal Code, for forgery for the purpose of cheating (“forgery charges”).

2       At the end of the trial, I find the Accused guilty and convict him of:

(a)     seven of the cheating charges, one of which (DAC 922412/2018) was amended by me prior to conviction; and

(b)     seven of the forgery charges.

I also acquit the Accused of the remaining six cheating charges and four forgery charges.

3       This trial took over three years to complete, in large part because of the COVID pandemic. Apart from necessitating the vacation of trial dates in the second quarter of 2020, the pandemic also engendered travel restrictions that prevented one of the Defence experts, Dr Alfred Lau Sze Lok (“Dr Alfred Lau”), from flying down to complete his evidence-in-chief. As will be seen, the key physical exhibits in this case included radiographs, some of which had distinct scratches and indentations on their surface that were central to the Prosecution’s case on the forgery charges. The Defence wanted Dr Alfred Lau to physically handle the radiograph films while answering questions on the stand. By November 2020, the Defence had completed adducing the evidence of all its witnesses, save for Dr Alfred Lau. Those aspects of Dr Alfred Lau’s evidence-in-chief which could be given remotely were completed via videoconferencing, leaving only those portions of his testimony which required him to handle the radiograph films while on the stand. Thereafter, the Defence made multiple attempts to fly Dr Alfred Lau from Hong Kong to complete his examination-in-chief, but these were repeatedly frustrated by the evolving restrictions on cross-border travel. After a year of trying, the Defence gave up and agreed to let Dr Alfred Lau complete the rest of his testimony remotely. In early March 2022, the Defence picked up on Dr Alfred Lau’s evidence in-chief, from where it left off some 15 months earlier. Dr Alfred Lau’s entire testimony (including cross-examination) was thus concluded over videoconferencing, without him physically handling the radiograph films while on the stand.

4       Upon conclusion of Dr Alfred Lau’s testimony in March 2022, the Defence was supposed to have closed its case. However, the Defence argued that the Accused had been prejudiced by Dr Alfred Lau’s inability to physically handle the radiograph films while on the witness stand. The Defence thus sought to call an additional expert (also from overseas) −this led to a further delay of about five months. When the Defence’s additional expert, Dr Firdaus Hariri (“Dr Firdaus”) finally took the stand, it was already August 2022.

Outline of this case

5       The Accused essentially faces two categories of charges: the cheating charges and the forgery charges. Both categories are factually related.

6       The Accused filed 13 Medisave claims with the Central Provident Fund (“CPF”) Board for clinical procedures purportedly performed by him on nine patients. The cheating charges alleged that the claims were false, on account of the procedures never having been performed.

7       The allegedly false Medisave claims related to three types of procedures:

(a)      Mandible or Maxilla Alveolar Defect/Deformity, Complex Alveoloplasty: This is a procedure where granules of bone or bone substitutes are grafted onto the patient’s jaw to buttress the bone line, typically to ensure that there is sufficient foundation for a dental implant to be inserted later. The specific type of bone graft at issue in this case is the Autogenous Bone Graft, referred to as “ABG” for short. The word “autogenous” connotes that the graft material comprises bone harvested from a donor site within the patient’s body (as opposed to bone from extraneous sources).

(b)      Mouth, Foreign Body (superficial), Removal: This is a procedure where a foreign body trapped in the patient’s gum is removed. This procedure for foreign body removal is referred to as “FBR” for short.

(c)      Insertion of Endosseous Implant: This is a procedure where an implant is inserted into the patient’s jawbone and is referred to as “implant” for short.

After the Accused made the allegedly false Medisave claims, the Ministry of Health (“MoH”) conducted an audit requiring him to submit documents showing that the procedures (for which the Medisave claims were made) had in fact been performed. The Accused duly submitted the documents, which included photographs of radiograph that had purportedly been taken of the patients’ mouths, both before and after the procedures.

8       The forgery charges allege that 11 of these photographs, which related to four of the nine patients above, were forged. The Prosecution’s case is that the Accused took photographs of actual radiographs, before altering the captured images so that the photographs that were printed out gave the impression that the procedures had been performed.

The charges

9       The nine patients to whom the cheating charges related were called as Prosecution witnesses:

(a)      Chia Ching Choo, Catherine (PW3) (“Catherine Chia”);

The forgery charges centred on photographs of the first four patients listed above (in bold), submitted by the Accused to MoH for the audit.

Some technical conventions and terminology

12     Before delving into the evidence in this case, it is necessary for me to first explain some conventions and terminology adopted in the practice of dentistry, as this will help with understanding the issues in dispute.

ABG and FBR

13     All but one of the 13 cheating charges in this case relate to the ABG and/or FBR procedures. To understand the Accused’s defences to the cheating charges, it is necessary to elaborate on what each of these procedures entail.

14     I first explain the ABG procedure.

(a)     There are (broadly) two types of bone grafts that dentists perform:[note: 1]

(i)       In simple bone grafts,[note: 2] the graft material comes from external sources such as minerals (ie, synthetic bone), animals or even human cadavers – these external sources are sometimes referred to collectively, as “bottled bone”.

(ii)       In ABG,[note: 3] which is what the Accused claimed to have performed, the graft material is harvested from a donor site within the patient’s body.

MoH sets limits on the Medisave claims which can be made for the different dental procedures. In respect of bone grafts, the claim limit for ABG is higher than for simple bone grafts, given the increased complexity of the former.[note: 4]

(b)     The Defence claims that when the Accused performed ABG, the donor site from which he commonly harvested bone was the ramus. This is the part of the jawbone situated just behind the wisdom tooth:

(c)     The Defence also claims that when the Accused harvested bone for an ABG, he would use a trephine drill.[note: 5] This is a drill which has a bit that looks like a cylinder with a burred circular edge:

According to the Defence, the Accused would apply the trephine drill to the exposed jawbone to harvest small discs of bone, which he would then crush to create the graft material that was used to augment the graft site.

15     Next, I explain the FBR procedure.

(a)     This involves surgical removal of foreign bodies trapped in the patient’s gum. The foreign body typically gets embedded in the patient’s gum via a portal of entry,[note: 6] such as an open wound.[note: 7] Foreign bodies may thus get embedded through trauma injuries, eg, where bits of glass enter the gum in a traffic accident or a fall.[note: 8] Another common example of foreign body embedment is the amalgam, where bits of the metal filling (used for teeth restoration) enter the gum through an opening and get lodged.[note: 9]

(b)     During the trial, parties also discussed how food particles (eg, kernels, seeds and shellfish shards) may get trapped in the gum pocket surrounding the tooth root (ie, the portion targeted by flossing). While such food particles may loosely be termed as “foreign bodies”, their removal by non-surgical means (eg, by fishing the particle from the gum pocket) will technically not qualify as FBR for which a Medisave claim may be made.[note: 10] The FBR procedures that were the subject of the cheating charges, which the Defence claims were performed (and which the Prosecution alleges were not performed), involve surgical removal of foreign bodies (ie, making an incision in the gum to access the foreign body and remove it).

Anatomical references

16     In this judgment, the teeth at issue have been identified using the following naming convention, which divides the teeth into four quadrants:

(a)     Quadrant 1: the upper teeth to the patient’s right;

(b)     Quadrant 2: the upper teeth to the patient’s left;

(c)     Quadrant 3: the lower teeth to the patient’s left; and

(d)     Quadrant 4: the lower teeth to the patient’s right.

Within each quadrant, the tooth’s position is identified by a number, with the tooth at the front numbered as ‘1’ and the wisdom tooth numbered as ‘8’. The teeth in all four quadrants are assigned a unique two-digit number: the first digit being the quadrant number and the second being the tooth’s position within that quadrant. From the perspective of a dentist peering down the throat of a patient with his mouth opened wide, the teeth would be numbered as follows:

17     This judgment will use the tooth number to refer not only to the tooth itself but also to the specific site on the jawbone. For example, the tooth number may be used to refer to an edentulous site on the jawbone, notwithstanding that the tooth is no longer at that site.

18     This judgment will also employ technical directional references. The surface of the tooth facing the outside is called the buccal side (ie, facing the cheek). The surface facing the inside may, in the case of the upper teeth, be called the palatal side (ie, facing the palate) or, in the case of the lower teeth, the lingual side (ie, facing the tongue). The surface of the tooth facing the front is called the mesial side, while the surface facing the back (ie, where the wisdom tooth is) is called the distal side.

The experts

19     Much of the evidence centred on the opinions of the expert witnesses. These were dentists whom the parties had called. The experts testified on the steps for performing the relevant procedures, as well as gave their views on physical exhibits such as radiographs of the patient’s teeth and photographs of these radiographs.

20     The Prosecution called two dental experts:

(a)     Dr Andrew Tay Ban Guan (PW9) (“Dr Andrew Tay”), the Head and Senior Consultant of the Department of Oral & Maxillofacial Surgery at the Singapore National Dental Centre.

(b)     Dr Loh Chee Fun (PW10) (“Dr Loh”), Adjunct Associate Professor at the National University of Singapore Dental School and practising dental surgeon at Gleneagles Hospital.

21     The Defence called three dental experts:

(a)     Dr Leo Wai Fung (DW2) (“Dr Leo Fung”), a dentist employed by the Accused.

(b)     Dr Alfred Lau (DW3), the director of the Dental Implant and Maxillofacial Centre in Hong Kong.

(c)     Dr Firdaus (DW5), a Consultant Oral & Maxillofacial Surgeon in the Department of Oral and Maxillofacial Clinical Sciences at the Universiti Malaya’s Faculty of Dentistry.

The Cheating Charges

22     The dispute in the cheating charges centred primarily on whether the procedures, which were declared in the Medisave claims as having been performed by the Accused, were indeed performed. The Prosecution claims that they were not, meaning that the Medisave claims were false and constituted deception practised on the CPF Board. The Accused’s defence is that the procedures were performed, meaning that there was no deception to speak of.

Were the procedures in the cheating charges performed?

23     In contending that the procedures in the cheating charges were not performed, the Prosecution relies on the following evidence.

(a)     Firstly, many of the patients did not recall discussing the procedures with the Accused, whether prior to or during the time that the procedures were supposedly performed. The Prosecution contends that if the procedures had indeed been performed, such discussions must have taken place, for the following reasons:

(i)       Ethically, the dentist has to inform the patient before embarking on any surgical procedure.[note: 11] The Prosecution experts explained that given the invasive nature of surgery, a patient has the right to decide whether to proceed with a procedure.[note: 12] This is all the more essential for a major procedure like ABG, where harvesting of bone causes bleeding, swelling and pain at the donor site, as well as carries the risk of damage (and numbness) to the mandibular nerve running through the lower jaw.[note: 13] Even the Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau testified that it is his practice to get the patient’s consent before performing a bone harvest.[note: 14]

(ii)       For FBG, it is also unlikely that no discussions took place with the Accused if there had indeed been a foreign body in the patient’s gum. The Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau testified that the gum is a sensitive area, and the patient would usually be aware of any foreign body trapped there.[note: 15]

(iii)       Finally, given that the surgical procedures must be paid for by the patient (albeit from his Medisave account), the patient has a right to know what he is paying for.[note: 16]

The absence of any such discussions, argue the Prosecution, suggests that the procedures were never performed.

(b)     Secondly, most of the patients explicitly testified that the procedures were not performed, or at least that they did not recall the procedure being performed.

(c)     Thirdly, the patients also did not witness any post-operative wounds or stitches at the sites where the procedures were supposedly performed.[note: 17]

24     The Defence contends that the procedures were performed, but the patients were simply not able to recall them. The quality of the patients’ recollection, suggests the Defence, would have been impacted by the following:

(a)     The patients were under anaesthesia, meaning that they would not have been able to perceive the procedures being performed.

(b)     The procedures were performed between March and September 2014. The long passage of time from then till trial would have diluted the ability of the patients to recall the procedures.[note: 18]

25     Furthermore, the Defence highlights that by the time the police report was filed against the Accused on 13 February 2015, only a few months had elapsed from when the procedures were purportedly performed. The Defence contends that MoH should have used that small window of time to check the patients’ mouths for traces of whether the procedures had indeed been performed. However, MoH failed to do so and instead allowed the post-operative wounds to heal. This, argues the Defence, prejudiced the Accused, as objective and potentially exculpatory evidence was allowed to dissipate.[note: 19]

26     Having considered the evidence and arguments on both sides, I arrive at the following conclusions in respect of the 13 cheating charges:

27     I elaborate on each of these conclusions below.

Catherine Chia: Were the procedures performed on her?

28     Catherine Chia visited the Accused on 7 April 2014 for a consultation on whether she should insert an implant[note: 20] at the tooth #36 site[note: 21] (her tooth #36 had been extracted by the Accused’s clinic on a previous visit some months back[note: 22]). During this visit, no surgical procedures were performed.[note: 23]

29     A week after, on 14 April 2014,[note: 24] Catherine Chia visited the Accused’s clinic again −this time, the implant procedure at tooth #36 was performed. The Defence’s case is that during that visit, the Accused performed:[note: 25]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #36 site (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #33 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

30     The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Catherine Chia on 14 April 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false. The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922412/2018) in respect of Catherina Chia. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Catherine Chia, when they were not.

(1)    Was ABG performed on Catherine Chia?

31     After hearing the evidence, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as regards his claim that ABG was performed on Catherine Chia on 14 April 2014, as declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922412/2018.

32     As regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 14 April 2014, Catherine Chia testified that the Accused did not discuss with her about harvesting bone from her left ramus to augment the implant site.[note: 26] She also testified that the Accused did not mention anything about doing a bone graft to augment the implant site.[note: 27]

33     However, as regards what was performed during the procedure on 14 April 2014, I find Catherine Chia’s evidence on whether ABG was performed to be somewhat uncertain. She initially testified that no cuts were made to the purported donor site at the left ramus.[note: 28] However, under cross-examination, it was suggested to her that the cut to the implant site (at the tooth #36 region) could have extended all the way back to the left ramus (ie, behind tooth #38), this being the purported donor site for the ABG which the Accused claimed to have performed. She was not able to refute this, and instead replied “I wouldn’t know”.[note: 29] When the Defence asked if she knew whether a drill had been applied to the purported donor site at the left ramus (to harvest bone), she gave a noncommittal reply: “I don’t know … Because the---as you say, the part of the gum is numb. I do not know what is done.”[note: 30] The ambiguity in Catherine Chia’s evidence as to what was performed during the operation was likely a function of the fact that the site where the implant was performed (at tooth #36) was relatively close to the purported donor site (at the left ramus). Any anaesthetic applied to the implant site would likely have numbed Catherine Chia’s sensation at the donor site as well.

34     Even when focusing on Catherine Chia’s evidence as regards her post-operative state, when the anaesthetic had already worn off, her testimony on signs of ABG having been done was equally equivocal. She testified that the purported donor site at the left ramus had no pain,[note: 31] thereby suggesting that no procedures were performed there. When asked if there were stitches at the left ramus, she said that she could not remember whether there were.[note: 32]

35     Given the equivocal nature of Catherine Chia’s testimony on this point, I am unable to rule out that ABG may have been performed, with bone harvested from the left ramus for grafting onto the tooth #36 implant site. I thus give the Accused the benefit of the doubt, as regards his claim that ABG was performed.

(2)    FBR not performed on Catherine Chia

36     Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Catherine Chia on 14 April 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922412/2018.

37     Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 14 April 2014, Catherine Chia testified that the Accused did not mention about a foreign body in her gum, nor allude to surgery to remove a foreign body.[note: 33] On the consultation that took place a week before that (ie, on 7 April 2014),[note: 34] the issue of a foreign body in her gum was similarly not raised by her to the Accused, nor by the Accused to her.[note: 35] Catherine Chia’s testimony was clear that she was not aware of any foreign body in her gum.[note: 36] I find this noteworthy, given that even the Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau opined that as the gum is a sensitive part of the mouth, a patient would usually be aware if a foreign body was embedded there (see paragraph 23(a)(ii) above).

38     The next aspect of Catherine Chia’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 14 April 2014. I find this aspect of Catherine Chia’s testimony to be compelling. Only local anaesthesia was applied,[note: 37] meaning that she remained conscious. Catherine Chia testified that she did not recall FBR having been done at the tooth #33 area.[note: 38] She testified, repeatedly, that the Accused did not apply numbing cream at the site where the FBR was supposed to have occurred[note: 39] and, despite this, felt no pain at the tooth #33 area when the FBR purportedly took place.[note: 40] She also confirmed that no cuts were made to the tooth #33 area[note: 41] and that she did not recall any foreign body being removed from there.[note: 42] The Defence pursued this in cross-examination, asking her if she recalled any cut being made at that part of her mouth, to which she confirmed that she could not.[note: 43]

39     The Defence argues that Catherine Chia “backtracked” on her testimony that no cut was made at the purported FBR site, [note: 44] citing the following portion of her cross-examination:[note: 45]

Q

… I’m instructed [the Accused] then used a scalpel to cut a very small cut, about half centimetre, at your tooth 33 area. … Can you recall that?

A

No. I cannot recall that.

Q

Okay. Now, what say you if I were to put it to you that you couldn’t feel that cut because of 2 factors, that area in 33 has already been numbed by the local anaesthesia and that’s why you couldn’t feel the cut being made?

A

But you could feel after the procedure.

Q:

Okay. We will come to that in a moment. But as the cut was being made under local anaesthesia, would you agree with me that you couldn’t feel it? It was painless.

DPP:

Your Honour, the assumption in that question seems to be that the cut was made. … If that’s --- the --- assumption, it should be expressly put to --- the witness.

DC:

It is a put, Your Honour.

Q:

Let me clarify, Witness, what is a put. Because sometimes throughout Cross-Examination, I have to present to you, what you saw we call a put in this line, where I have to present to you my client’s case. It’s for you to agree, disagree, and in any event, you may explain, and if you don’t know, we are happy for you to say “I don’t know.” … Okay?

…

A:

Okay.

Court:

So … Maybe just to respond to the objection … the question is assuming the cut was made at 33 under local anaesthesia, you would not have been able to feel it anyway because everything was numb. Is that the question?

Foo:

Yes. Stand guided, Your Honour. Yah.

A

For this question, yes, I agree.

Q

Okay. Thank you. And then--- I’m instructed that the cut was for the purpose of enabling [the Accused] to remove a foreign body from the position of 33 … . This was my instruction. What say you to that?

A

I don’t know.

Q

You don’t know, okay, that’s fine. Okay. Now, following that, okay, I’m instructed that Dr. Sng then stitched up the small cut at the area of 33.

A

I don’t know.

[emphasis added]



The Defence highlights Catherine Chia’s replies, ie, “yes, I agree” and “I don’t know”, to argue that she conceded that she did not know if an incision had been made at the tooth #33 area.

40     The Defence’s interpretation of the above extract from Catherine Chia’s cross-examination is highly skewed. A plain reading of the passage above shows that Defence Counsel explicitly circumscribed Catherine Chia’s response with the assumption that the tooth #33 area was cut. After having confined Catherine Chia to within the parameters of that assumption, Defence Counsel proceeded to put it to her that she would not be able to feel that cut, or any stitches to close that cut, because the area had been numbed. It was only then that Catherine Chia replied: “I don’t know”. However, the very factual basis for this assumption was something that Catherine Chia had already refuted, via her testimony that no cut was made, and no numbing cream was applied, to the tooth #33 area. In response to what was (for all intents and purposes) a hypothetical question, her response “I don’t know” was not unexpected.

41     Catherine Chia also reinforced her position further by testifying unequivocally that in her post-operative state, that there were no stitches at the purported FBR site at the tooth #33 area.[note: 46]

42     Given Catherine Chia’s evidence that the issue of FBR was not raised in her discussions with the Accused, her confirmation that no surgery was performed on the purported FBR site and her clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches at that site, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on her on 14 April 2014.

(3)    Conclusion on Catherine Chia

43     As regards the ABG and FBR declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922412/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Catherine Chia on 14 April 2014, I conclude that:

(a)     the FBR was not performed; and

(b)     the benefit of the doubt should be given to the Accused as to whether the ABG was performed.

44     In light of this, I amend the charge in DAC 922412/2018, by deleting the reference to ABG (so that only the reference to FBR remains) and reducing the sum alleged to have been paid by the CPF Board (from $1,900 to $350 −the latter figure being what was paid for FBR only[note: 47]).

Chong Moh Chin: Were the procedures performed on her?

45     Chong Moh Chin first visited the Accused on 9 April 2014,[note: 48] for the purpose of inserting an implant at the tooth #36 site.[note: 49] The Defence’s case is that during that visit, the Accused performed:[note: 50]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #36 site (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #16 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

46     The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Chong Moh Chin on 9 April 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false. The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922413/2018) in respect of Chong Moh Chin. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Chong Moh Chin, when they were not.

(1)    ABG not performed on Chong Moh Chin

47     After hearing the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform ABG on Chong Moh Chin on 9 April 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922413/2018.

48     Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 9 April 2014, the Accused appears to have told Chong Moh Chin that bone powder had to be grafted onto her implant site to augment the bone line, so as to support the implant.[note: 51] However, as explained at paragraph 14(a) above, a bone graft can be performed using purely bottled bone or, in the case of an ABG, with autogenous bone harvested from a doner site in the patient’s body (the autogenous bone can then either be grafted by itself or mixed with bottled bone, prior to grafting). A graft using purely bottled bone would not constitute an ABG, as there would be no harvesting of bone from a donor site within the patient’s body. The question thus arises as to what “bone powder” the Accused was referring to, when he was discussing the bone graft with Chong Moh Chin. The Defence’s case is that the graft was an ABG because the Accused harvested bone from Chong Moh Chin’s left ramus, crushed the bone material and then applied this to the implant site. However, the evidence of Chong Moh Chin ran counter to this, as she testified that the Accused did not tell her that he would be harvesting bone from another site within her mouth to graft onto the implant site.[note: 52] She also testified that the Accused did not tell her that he would grafting crushed bone onto the implant site.[note: 53]

49     The next aspect of Chong Moh Chin’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 9 April 2014. As only local anaesthesia was applied,[note: 54] she remained conscious. Her evidence on what happened can be summarised under two main points:

(a)     She testified that the Accused did not make any incision at the ramus where the purported donor site was,[note: 55] notwithstanding her ability to recall that the Accused did cut her gum at tooth #36 (where the implant was performed).[note: 56]

(b)     She recalled a drill being applied, although this was not (as contended by the Defence) applied to her left ramus.[note: 57] She surmised that the drill may have been applied to the tooth #36 implant site, to facilitate insertion of the implant.[note: 58]

50     The Defence places some reliance on Chong Moh Chin’s testimony that she heard a drill, arguing that there was no reason for the Accused to have drilled the tooth #36 implant site.[note: 59] The Defence contends that the implant could only have been inserted at the implant site (at tooth #36) on a later date, after the grafting had settled, meaning that any drilling to facilitate insertion of the implant must similarly have been on a later date and not on 9 April 2014 (when the implant site was just being augmented with graft material). Given that the tooth #36 implant site is very close to the purported donor site at the left ramus, the Defence invites the court to infer that Chong Moh Chin must have been mistaken, and that she must have heard the drill being applied to the left ramus (rather than the tooth #36 implant site). This, says the Defence, supports the Accused’s claim that ABG was performed, with bone being autogenously harvested from the left ramus with the drill which Chong Moh Chin heard.

51     I am of the view that the Defence’s arguments are premised on postulations which have not been established. In effect, the Defence asserts that there is never a need for a drill (or any other instrument sounding like a drill) to be applied to an implant site when it is being augmented with bone graft. This is a rather sweeping proposition for which the Defence failed to provide supporting evidence. When Chong Moh Chin testified that the drill had been applied to the tooth #36 site on 9 April 2014 to facilitate fitting of the implant screw,58 the Defence did not challenge this by suggesting to her that there was no occasion to apply the drill to the #36 site. Furthermore, the Defence has not pointed me to any statement by the experts which categorically affirms that a drill can never be applied at the implant site when it is being augmented with bone graft. The experts were certainly not invited to opine on this. That makes it difficult for me, without more, to simply reject Chong Moh Chin’s claim that the drill was applied to the tooth #36 site and replace her clear testimony with an inference that the drill must have been applied to the ramus instead. The fact that she heard what sounded like a drill is neither here nor there and certainly does not validate the Defence’s claim that the drill was applied to the ramus.

52     Having said that, it is still my view that as regards what was performed during the procedure on 9 April 2014, Chong Moh Chin’s recollection may have been somewhat ambivalent, because of the effect of the anaesthetic. Given that the implant site (at tooth #36) was quite close to the left ramus (being the purported ABG’s donor site), any anaesthetic applied to the implant site would likely also have numbed Chong Moh Chin’s sensation at the ramus. Thus, when she was asked in cross-examination if she agreed that a drill was applied to the ramus and a tool was then used to harvest bone therefrom, she candidly conceded: “I would not know about that because it was under anaesthesia.”[note: 60] I am thus unable to derive much assistance from this part of Chong Moh Chin’s evidence.

53     The aspect of Chong Moh Chin’s testimony that is far more unequivocal pertains to her post-operative state, when the effects of the anaesthesia had worn off. I find her evidence in this respect to be compelling. She testified that post-operation, there was no pain at the left ramus, which was the purported ABG donor site.[note: 61] She testified that there was no wound there.[note: 62] She testified, repeatedly, that there were no stitches at the left ramus.[note: 63] She also affirmed confidently that if there had been stitches there, she would know.[note: 64]

54     Given Chong Moh Chin’s clear recollection of the absence of any post-operative pain, wounds, or stiches at the purported donor site on the left ramus, as well as her evidence that the issue of harvesting bone from her ramus had not been raised in discussions with the Accused (notwithstanding this being a significant surgery), I am satisfied that ABG was not performed on her on 9 April 2014.

(2)    FBR not performed on Chong Moh Chin

55     Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Chong Moh Chin on 9 April 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922413/2018.

56     Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 9 April 2014, there appears to be some ambiguity in Chong Moh Chin’s evidence as to whether the Accused raised the issue of FBR. Chong Moh Chin testified that she did not tell the Accused that she had a foreign body stuck in her mouth.[note: 65] However, she conceded that she had “some discomfort” on the upper right corner of her mouth,[note: 66] this being the quadrant where tooth #16 (where the FBR purportedly took place) is located. When it was put to her in cross-examination that this discomfort may have been due to a foreign body, she candidly conceded that this was possible.[note: 67] When it was suggested to her in cross-examination that the Accused might have told her that she had a foreign body in her mouth but she could have failed to recall this, she candidly agreed.[note: 68] Chong Moh Chin’s poor recollection about whether she discussed FBR with the Accused thus does not assist the Prosecution’s case.

57     However, I find Chong Moh Chin’s evidence as to what was performed during the procedure on 9 April 2014 to be far more unequivocal. As alluded to above, only local anaesthesia was applied,54 so Chong Moh Chin remained conscious. In this respect, she testified that the procedure on 9 April 2014 pertained only to the fitting of an implant at the tooth #36 site, with no surgery being performed at the upper right side of her mouth (where the FBR was purportedly performed).[note: 69] When she was asked if she could remember any cut being made to the tooth #16 area, she replied that she could not.[note: 70] Her testimony on this was significant, given that Chong Moh Chin also testified that she did not remember the Accused applying numbing cream at the tooth #16 area[note: 71] and she was certain that the Accused did not inject anaesthesia at this area.[note: 72] As such, I infer that if FBR had indeed been performed at the tooth #16 procedure, she would have felt it.

58     The Defence contends that Chong Moh Chin could not remember whether the Accused had performed FBR at the tooth #16 area[note: 73] −the connotation of the word “whether” being that the Accused may or may not have performed the FBR. In support of this, the Defence cites the following exchange in her cross-examination:[note: 74]

Q:    … Then what say you if I further put it to you that Dr. Sng then removed the foreign body he saw at 16, and thereafter---and thereafter, took another X-ray. Can you recall that?

A:     For 16, I don’t remember. [emphasis added]

With respect, this is a mischaracterisation of Chong Moh Chin’s testimony. Chong Moh Chin was saying that she did not remember the Accused removing a foreign body from the tooth #16 area. That is very different from her saying, as was implicit in the Defence submission, that Chong Moh Chin could not remember whether the Accused performed FBR at the tooth #16 area. The latter suggests Chong Moh Chin’s acceptance of the possibility that the Accused did remove a foreign body from the tooth #16 area, which she clearly did not. The exchange which followed immediately from the extract above, which is not cited in the Defence submissions, makes this clear:[note: 75]

Q:    Okay, that’s fair. Yah. Then after that, Dr. Sng then stitched the small cut on your gum at location 16, stitched up. That means he used thread to close.

A:     I disagree.

Towards the end of cross-examination, it was put to Chong Moh Chin that FBR was performed at the tooth #16 area. She reaffirmed her position by flatly disagreeing.[note: 76]

59     That no FBR was performed at tooth #16 is reinforced by Chong Moh Chin’s evidence on her post-operative state, which I find to be compelling. She testified that after the procedure, she did not have any wound on the upper right side of her mouth (where the FBR was purportedly performed)[note: 77] and there were no stitches there.[note: 78] She asserted that if there had been stitches there, she would have known[note: 79] and (more importantly) would have remembered.[note: 80]

60     Given Chong Moh Chin’s confirmation that no surgery was performed at the purported FBR site, as well as her clear recollection that there were no post-operative stitches there, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on her on 9 April 2014.

(3)    Conclusion on Chong Moh Chin

61     I thus conclude that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922413/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Chong Moh Chin on 9 April 2014, were not performed.

Neo Kheng Yew: Were the procedures performed on him?

62     Neo Kheng Yew is the husband of Chong Moh Chin. He testified that he visited the Accused’s clinic on 9 April 2014[note: 81] (with his wife) to address a decay at his tooth #46.[note: 82] Neo Kheng Yew testified this tooth was extracted on this visit,[note: 83] following which he sought to fit an implant at the extraction site.[note: 84] The Defence’s case is that apart from extracting tooth #46, the Accused performed the following two procedures on Neo Kheng Yew at this visit:[note: 85]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #46 site (using bone harvested from the region of the right ramus); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #17 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

63     The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Neo Kheng Yew on 9 April 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false. The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922414/2018) in respect of Neo Kheng Yew. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Neo Kheng Yew, when they were not.

(1)    ABG not performed on Neo Kheng Yew

64     Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform ABG on Neo Kheng Yew on 9 April 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922413/2018.

65     Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 9 April 2014, Neo Kheng Yew testified that the Accused did not raise the issue of augmenting the extraction site with a bone graft, nor discuss harvesting bone from the ramus for such a graft.[note: 86] Neo Kheng could not recall whether, during the procedure itself, the Accused told him that he would be doing a bone graft to strengthen the extraction site[note: 87] but testified that the Accused did not tell him that he would be making an incision at the purported donor site.[note: 88] Still, I note that there is some ambiguity in Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence as regards whether ABG was discussed with the Accused, as Neo Kheng Yew stated rather candidly (in re-examination) that given the lapse of five years, he was unable to definitely say that the Accused did not discuss bone grafting with him.[note: 89] Even then, Neo Kheng Yew testified that to the best of his knowledge, he had never heard of the bone graft procedure.[note: 90] Given the ambiguity, I am of the view that this aspect of Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence does not assist the Prosecution’s case.

66     The next aspect of Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 9 April 2014. I find this part of his evidence to be much more definitive. As only local anaesthesia was applied,[note: 91] he remained conscious. Neo Kheng Yew testified that the Accused did not make an incision at his ramus, nor remove any bone with a drill.[note: 92] Neo Kheng Yew further elaborated that he could not remember:

(a)     any incision being made;[note: 93]

(b)     any drill being applied;[note: 94] or

(c)     any bone being harvested with a chisel,[note: 95]

at the purported donor site at the right ramus.

67     The Defence nevertheless suggests that Neo Kheng Yew did hear a drill being applied to the tooth #46 site, where the tooth had just been extracted and an implant was to be affixed. To support this suggestion, the Defence highlights the following portion of Neo Kheng Yew’s cross examination:[note: 96]

As I remember, uh, beside the 4-6, uh, no other place was--- have any kind of in---uh, drill or anything down on the other side---… beside the---the 4-6.

[emphasis added in Defence submissions]

The Defence suggests that Neo Kheng Yew was say that he did not hear a drill being applied anywhere else other than the tooth #46 site and, building upon that, argues[note: 97] (as with the case of Chong Moh Chin, at paragraph 50 above), that as there was no reason for a drill to be applied to the implant site at tooth #46, the drill must have been applied to the purported donor site at the right ramus. This, argues the Defence, buttresses the inference that a bone harvest was indeed done at the right ramus.

68     With respect, this submission blithely imputes to Neo Kheng Yew words that he never said. I extract the relevant exchange in cross-examination:[note: 98]

Q:    So, [the Accused] then proceeded to use a dental drill to drill the ramus and this caused considerable vibration and a loud whining sound, a dental drill sound. Can you recall that?

A    No. … I--- A cannot recall that Dr. Sng drilled on the 4 over that side instead of 4-6. … I can only remember that 4-6 was done. … Only on that---on that location.

Q    Yes. What say you, Mr. Neo, if I were just suggest to you that this drilling on your right ramus was actually carried out but you---as you sit there now, you can no longer recall because after all, 5 years has passed between the procedure and today. You cannot recall because the---of the passing of 5 years between the procedure and today. Yes?

A    As I remember, uh, beside the 4-6, uh, no other place was--- have any kind of in---uh, drill or anything down on the other side--- … beside the 4-6.

[emphasis added]

It is thus clear that the point about a drill having been used for the procedure was raised by Defence Counsel, not by Neo Kheng Yew. Neo Kheng Yew was simply responding to counsel’s question by explaining that apart from the procedure to the extraction site at tooth #46, there was no “drill or anything” applied to the ramus. This is very, very different from him saying that a drill was applied to the extraction site at tooth #46. In fact, Neo Kheng Yew had repeatedly testified that he was not aware of a drill being used.[note: 99]

69     As regards Neo Kheng Yew’s post-operative state, he testified that there was pain at the bottom right portion of his mouth.[note: 100] This was the quadrant where right ramus was located, where the bone harvest was purportedly performed. However, the existence of pain here does not advance the Defence’s case that surgery was performed at the right ramus, as this is also the quadrant where the extraction (at tooth #46) was performed.[note: 101] In fact, Neo Kheng Yew averred on multiple occasion that he had no stitches at the purported donor site on the right ramus.[note: 102] He only had stitches at the extraction site[note: 103] and nowhere else.[note: 104] This strongly contradicts the Defence claim that a bone harvest was ever performed at the right ramus.

70     Given Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence that the issue of harvesting bone to augment the extraction site was not raised in discussions with the Accused, his confirmation that no surgery was performed at the purported ABG done site at the right ramus and his clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches at that ramus, I am satisfied that ABG was not performed on him on 9 April 2014.

(2)    FBR not performed on Neo Kheng Yew

71     Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Neo Kheng Yew on 9 April 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922414/2018.

72     As regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 9 April 2014, there appears to be some ambiguity in Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence about whether FBR was raised. Neo Kheng Yew testified that during the consultation, the Accused did not highlight the issue of a foreign body in his mouth.[note: 105] Subsequently, during the implant procedure, the Accused also did not mention anything about a foreign body at the tooth #17 area which needed removal.[note: 106] However, during cross-examination, the Defence suggested to Neo Kheng Yew that after the lapse of 5 years, it was possible that he might have forgotten that the issue of FBR had in fact been discussed with the Accused, to which Neo Kheng Yew candidly replied: “It’s possible”.[note: 107] Given this ambiguity, I do not think this aspect of Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence assists the Prosecution’s case.

73     However, I found Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence as regards what was performed during the procedure on 9 April 2014 to be much more unequivocal. As mentioned above, only local anaesthetic was applied,91 meaning that Neo Kheng Yew remained conscious. He testified that no incision was made at tooth #17, where the FBR procedure was allegedly performed, nor was anything removed from that area.[note: 108] As such, he could not understand why the clinical notes mentioned that FBR was performed at tooth #17.[note: 109] Under rigorous cross-examination, Neo Kheng Yew held firm and maintained that the Accused did not make an incision at the tooth #17 area.[note: 110]

74     At one point in cross-examination, Defence Counsel suggested to Neo Kheng Yew that if the entire right side of his face had grown numb from the anaesthetic injection, it was possible that he would not be able to feel the Accused making an incision at the tooth #17 area. To this, Neo Kheng Yew candidly agreed that this was “possible”.[note: 111] However, he also maintained that once the effects of the anaesthesia wore off, he would be able to detect the cut.[note: 112] On this, I find Neo Kheng Yew’s evidence as to his post-operative state to be compelling. He testified that he did not experience any post-operative pain at the purported FBR site – the only pain being at the bottom right of his jaw, where the extraction had taken place.[note: 113] Neo Kheng Yew testified that there were no stiches at the tooth #17 area, where the FBR was allegedly performed.[note: 114] In fact, there were also no stitches anywhere apart from the extraction site.[note: 115] Under cross-examination, Defence Counsel suggested to him that the tooth #17 area might have been stitched up but he forgot due to the lapse of time. To this, Neo Kheng Yew held his ground and maintained that there was no surgery other than the extraction and implant procedure.[note: 116]

75     Given Neo Kheng Yew’s confirmation that no surgery was performed on the purported FBR site and his clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches there, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on him on 9 April 2014.

(3)    Conclusion on Neo Kheng Yew

76     I thus conclude that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922414/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Neo Kheng Yew on 9 April 2014, were not performed.

Juliann Rick: Were the procedures performed on her?

77     Juliann Rick visited the Accused’s clinic on 12 March 2014, for the purpose of fitting an implant at the tooth #36 site.[note: 117] The Defence’s case is that during that visit, the Accused performed:[note: 118]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #36 site (using bone harvested from the region of the right ramus); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #26 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

78     The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Juliann Rick on 12 March 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false. The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922415/2018) in respect of Juliann Rick. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Juliann Rick, when they were not.

(1)    ABG not performed on Juliann Rick

79     After hearing the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform ABG on Juliann Rick on 12 March 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922415/2018.

80     According to the evidence adduced at trial, Juliann Rick’s bone at the tooth #36 implant site was augmented during her visit to the Accused’s clinic on 12 March 2014. However, the implant was not inserted on this visit but on subsequent visits.[note: 119] Specifically, the implant’s foundation (ie, the titanium screw) appears to have been inserted at the next visit, on 4 June 2014,[note: 120] while the implant’s crown may have been inserted after that, on 26 June 2015.[note: 121] The question is thus whether augmentation of Juliann Rick’s jawbone on 12 March 2014 (in preparation for the subsequent implant) was with autogenous bone or bottled bone. The Accused’s defence is that the implant site was augmented with bone harvested from the right ramus, meaning that ABG was performed on 12 March 2014 (as declared in the Medisave claim). Conversely, the Prosecution’s case is that the implant site was augmented on 12 March 2014, but not with autogenous bone.[note: 122]

81     As regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 12 March 2014, Juliann Rick’s evidence was somewhat tentative. Some parts of her testimony suggested that the Accused did not raise ABG to her. For example, Juliann Rick testified that she remembered the Accused mentioning about augmenting the implant site with plastic bone and that she did not remember him mention taking bone from her right ramus.[note: 123] However, at other points of her testimony, Juliann Rick appeared somewhat unsure in her stance. For example, when asked on various occasions if the Accused told her that bone would be removed from her ramus, she said “I don’t remember”[note: 124] and also said that she “cannot recall” the Accused telling her about removing bone from her right ramus.[note: 125] This aspect of Juliann Rick’s evidence thus does not assist the Prosecution’s case.

82     The next aspect of Juliann Rick’s testimony pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 12 March 2014. As a preliminary point, it is necessary to first deal with the Defence’s contention that Juliann Rick may have been too anaesthetised to realise what was going on. The Prosecution’s position is that only local anaesthesia was applied, meaning that Juliann Rick remained conscious. I accept the Prosecution’s position, as it accords with Juliann Rick’s testimony that only local anaesthesia was administered.[note: 126] During the trial, the Defence attempted to suggest that Juliann Rick had asked for anaesthesia to “knock her out”, but she replied that she did not remember this.[note: 127] In their submissions, the Defence appear to pursue this point, contending that Juliann Rick was willing to be placed under general anaesthesia to avoid any pain.[note: 128] In raising this, the Defence refers[note: 129] to a portion of the transcripts where Juliann Rick alluded to general anaesthesia being applied:

Court:

… So, you’ve heard Mr. Foo go through the dates with you, there’s the first date which is 12th of March. They were talking about the procedures and I think you have explained that you don’t recall having a bone extracted from your ramus--- … you don’t recall a foreign body being removed from the [#26], you say that you do recall some mention of a plastic bone. … And then after that, … you can’t remember the date but I think counsel has mentioned sometime in April, right, where they actually performed the---the preparation for the bone graft where they put---where it’s supposed to be more painful, you remember that? That’s the visit after that, where it’s supposed to be more painful and counsel suggested that you’d asked for GA.

Witness:

The---yah, the GA was supposed to be---because they---they we---they were telling me that it’s going to be a bit more painful procedure than the previous.

…

Court:

Okay. So that second procedure was when they were inserting something into your jaw bone for the implant, is that it or---or was it something else?

Witness:

Uh, I don’t remember the procedure, I just remember about the GA,---

[emphasis added in Defence submissions]



Viewing Juliann Rick’s testimony in context, she was clearly not saying that she was under general anaesthesia at the time of the purported ABG on 12 March 2014. As explained at paragraph 80 above, while the implant site was augmented during the first visit on 12 April 2014, the insertion of the implant was done only at the next visit. Juliann Rick had agreed that general anaesthesia was applied at that next visit, when the implant was being inserted, because insertion of the titanium screw would have been painful.[note: 130] At no time did Juliann Rick agree that she was under general anaesthesia during the prior visit on 12 March 2014, ie, when the implant site was being augmented and when the Accused claimed to have performed the ABG. In fact, her evidence was that local anaesthesia had been applied and she was aware of what was going on.126

83     Juliann Rick was thus in a perfectly good position to testify as to what transpired during the procedure on 12 March 2014. In this respect, I find her testimony to be clear − ABG was not performed on 12 March 2014. She confirmed, twice, that if bone had indeed been harvested from her right ramus, she would have remembered as this would have been a major procedure.[note: 131] Against this backdrop, she testified time and again that she could not remember any of the key aspects of the ABG procedure being performed:

(a)     She did not remember an incision being made at her right ramus.[note: 132]

(b)     She did not remember bone being harvested from her right ramus with a trephine drill.[note: 133]

(c)     While she remembered anaesthesia being applied to the left side her mouth (being the site of the implant), she did not remember the right side of her mouth (where the purported donor site at the right ramus was located) being numbed.[note: 134] During cross-examination, it was suggested to her that her ramus was numbed but she had forgotten given the passage of time. To this, she candidly conceded that this was a possibility, but re-iterated that she did not recall any procedure being done to the right side of her mouth.[note: 135]

84     Juliann Rick’s position that she did not recall ABG being performed during her visit on 12 March 2014 is reinforced by her evidence on her post-operative state. She testified that after the procedure, she felt pain at the tooth #36 implant site[note: 136] but did not remember pain at other parts of her mouth.[note: 137] When asked if she remembered if her lower right ramus had stitches, she said no.[note: 138]

85     I thus regard Juliann Rick’s evidence as effectively confirming that no bone harvest had been performed at the purported donor site at the right ramus. This, coupled with her inability to recollect pain or post-operative stitches at that site, satisfies me that ABG was not performed on her on 12 March 2014.

(2)    FBR not performed on Juliann Rick

86     Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Juliann Rick on 12 March 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922415/2018.

87     Firstly, as regards what was discussed with the Accused, and whether this included the issue of a foreign body, I found Juliann Rick’s testimony (as with her evidence on whether ABG was discussed) rather tentative. She testified that she had no problems with her tooth #26,[note: 139] where the FBR purportedly occurred. However, she stopped short of expressly averring that the issue of a foreign body was never discussed with the Accused. Instead, she testified that she did not remember if the Accused informed her about a foreign body stuck at tooth #26.[note: 140] During cross-examination, it was suggested to her that the Accused did tell her, after viewing the X-ray, that there was a foreign body which had to be taken out. To this, Juliann Rick replied that she did not remember the Accused mentioning this.[note: 141] Given that the tenor of this aspect of Juliann Rick’s evidence was not particularly definitive, I was not able to derive much assistance from it.

88     However, as regards what was performed during the procedure on 12 March 2014, I find Juliann Rick’s testimony to be clear: FBR had not been performed. As explained above, Juliann Rick was under local anaesthesia,126 so she remained conscious. In this respect, Juliann Rick confirmed in cross-examination that nothing was removed from the tooth #26 area.[note: 142] It was then suggested to her that the Accused made a small incision at the tooth #26 area, removed a foreign body, and stitched the wound. However, Juliann Rick rebutted this, saying “I don’t think so”.[note: 143]

89     Juliann Rick also testified that she experienced numbness on the left side of her mouth during the procedure.[note: 144] I do not find this surprising, given that implant augmentation was performed at tooth #36, which is situated on the lower left side of the mouth. The numbness did not necessarily suggest that any procedures took place on the upper left side of the mouth, where the FBR purportedly occurred (at the tooth #26 area). In any case, Juliann Rick testified that she did not remember numbing cream being applied at the purported FBR site.[note: 145]

90     That no FBR was performed at the tooth #26 area is also reinforced by Juliann Rick’s testimony as to her post-operative state. As explained above, she testified that after the procedure, she felt pain at the tooth #36 implant site136 but did not remember pain at other parts of her mouth.137 When asked if she remembered any stitches at the tooth #26 area, she said ‘no’.[note: 146] She also explained that if there had been stitches at the tooth #26 area, she could have seen them in the mirror.[note: 147]

91     The Defence argues that Juliann Rick made “concessions” that the Accused could have stitched up the purported FBR site at tooth #26 and the purported ABG donor site at the right ramus.[note: 148] However, the section of Juliann Rick’s testimony cited by the Defence in the footnote to this submission does not support the contention. I extract the section below:[note: 149]

Q    And thereafter, whilst your mouth is still numb from the effect of the anaesthetic injected by syringe, I’m instructed that [the Accused] then close up the incisions at 2-6, 3-6, and 4-8. Do you agree with this?

A     I believe it’s only at 36.

Q    Okay.

A     I don’t remember the rest of the area.

Q    Now, would it be possible to say that you could not feel the stitching at the locations of 2-6 and 4-8 because those locations were likewise numbed by anaesthetic?

A    It’s possible but I don’t feel any stitches at the other areas after that.

[emphasis added]

A plain reading of this extract shows that Juliann Rick was not, as suggested by the Defence submission, conceding that stitching could have been done at the purported FBR and ABG donor sites. Her answer was based on the Defence’s premise that those sites were numbed: if those sites were numbed, it is possible that she would not feel the stitching being performed. However, this was a premise that did not reflect Juliann Rick’s position in the first place. She stated quite clearly that she did not recall numbing cream being applied to the purported FBR site.145 In any case, as seen from the extract above, Juliann Rick also qualified that she did not feel stitches at areas other than the tooth #36 site. Meaning that she did not feel stitches at the purported FBR site.

92     Given Juliann Rick’s evidence that no foreign body had been removed from the purported FBR site at the tooth #26 area and her confirmation that she did not recall seeing stitches at that site, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on her on 14 April 2014.

(3)     Conclusion on Juliann Rick

93     I thus conclude that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922415/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Juliann Rick on 12 March 2014, were not performed.

Sum Marn Peng: Were the procedures performed on her?

94     Sum Marn Peng visited the Accused’s clinic on 18 March 2014, for the purpose of fitting an implant at the tooth #45 site.[note: 150] The Defence’s case is that during that visit, the Accused performed:[note: 151]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #45 site (using bone harvested from the region of the right ramus); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #26 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

95     The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Sum Marn Peng on 18 March 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false. The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922416/2018) in respect of Sum Marn Peng. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Sum Marn Peng, when they were not.

(1)    ABG not performed on Sum Marn Peng

96     After hearing the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform ABG on Sum Marn Peng on 18 March 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922416/2018.

97     Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 18 March 2014, Sum Marn Peng testified that the Accused did not raise the issue of ABG to her. While the Accused did tell her that the bone wall at tooth #45 was defective and in need of a bone graft,[note: 152] Sum Marn Peng confirmed that he did not discuss with her about harvesting graft material from a donor site within her mouth.[note: 153] This suggested that the bone graft was not an ABG. She also did not remember anyone telling her during the procedure that bone was going to be harvested from another part of her mouth to augment the implant site.[note: 154] In this respect, she was firm in her testimony that the Accused did not tell her that he was harvesting bone from her jaw for a bone graft.[note: 155]

98     The next aspect of Sum Marn Peng’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 18 March 2014. As only local anaesthesia was applied,[note: 156] Sum Marn Peng remained conscious. I find Sum Marn Peng’s evidence to be clear in this regard. She testified that while the tooth #45 site had been augmented with graft material in preparation for the implant,[note: 157] harvesting of bone from the purported donor site at her lower right ramus was not done, as she would have felt the pain if it had been done.[note: 158]

99     During cross-examination, the Defence suggested to Sum Marn Peng that as the implant sit (at tooth #45) was close to the purported donor site at the right ramus, the Accused had performed a single long cut stretching from tooth #45 to the right ramus, at tooth #48. This would explain why she did not detect a separate cut at the right ramus. However, Sum Marn Peng astutely observed that such a cut would have been very long, and she would have remembered such a long cut.[note: 159] At that juncture, the cross-examination questions from the Defence grew somewhat muddled. Counsel clarified that the cut stretched from tooth #45 to tooth #47 and not tooth #48, and then asserted that such a cut would not be that long after all, reaching to only some 1 to 1.5cm in length.[note: 160] I queried counsel as to how a cut stretching across three molars could possibly span only 1 to 1.5cm?[note: 161] Counsel then reframed his question to state that the cut stretched from tooth #45 to #47, before traversing diagonally downwards to tooth #48 to reach the right ramus.[note: 162] In response to this, Sum Marn Peng re-iterated that this was an “extremely long cut” and, while she was unable to see what the Accused was doing in her mouth, she did not recall such a long wound.[note: 163]

100    Given that the implant procedure was being performed at tooth #45, I am mindful that the anaesthesia applied could possibly have numbed the right ramus as well. This possibility was in fact supported by Sum Marn Peng’s evidence that the right side of her face was numb.[note: 164] However, any such numbness would have worn off after the procedure. In that respect, I find Sum Marn Peng’s testimony as to her post-operative state to be compelling. She testified that after the procedure, there was pain only at the implant site, and not anywhere else.[note: 165] She was also aware that the tooth #45 implant site was stitched up[note: 166] but she did not see the stitches stretching to the right ramus. She explained that if there had been such stitches, she would have felt them while brushing her teeth and she would have remembered them.[note: 167]

101    Given Sum Marn Peng’s evidence that harvesting of bone from her ramus was not raised in her discussions with the Accused, her confirmation that no incision was made at the purported donor site at the right ramus, as well as her clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches at that ramus, I am satisfied that ABG was not performed on her on 18 March 2014.

(2)    FBR not performed on Sum Marn Peng

102    Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Sum Marn Peng on 18 March 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922416/2018.

103    Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 18 March 2014, Sum Marn Peng testified that she did not think that she had highlighted any problems with tooth #26 to the Accused.[note: 168] She also did not recall the Accused telling her about a foreign body which needed removal.[note: 169] Further, she did not remember him telling her during the procedure that he had removed a foreign body from her upper left jaw[note: 170] In fact, she did not recall the Accused saying anything during the procedure about the tooth #26 area or her upper jaw.[note: 171] In cross-examination, it was suggested to Sum Marn Peng that the Accused may have informed her about a foreign body at tooth #26, to which she replied that she did not think so because the term “foreign body” had “never popped up” in her conversation with the Accused.[note: 172] This is significant, given that even the Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau opined that as the gum is a sensitive part of the mouth, a patient would usually be aware if a foreign body was indeed embedded there (see paragraph 23(a)(ii) above).

104    The next aspect of Sum Marn Peng’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 18 March 2014. As stated above, only local anaesthesia was applied,156 meaning that Sum Marn Peng remained conscious. In this respect, Sum Marn Peng confirmed that the Accused did not perform FBR at the tooth #26 area[note: 173] and that cuts were not made to the gum of her upper left jaw, where the FBR purportedly took place.[note: 174] During cross-examination, the Defence suggested to Sum Marn Peng that the Accused had made an incision at tooth #26 and removed a foreign body, but she responded plainly that the procedure was only at the lower jaw, with nothing done to the upper jaw, including the tooth #26 region.[note: 175] When the Defence press her that the Accused did carry out FBR at tooth #26, she asserted that she did not recall having a foreign body removed from her mouth, adding that she was sure of this.[note: 176]

105    At one point in cross-examination, the Defence pointed out that on 16 March 2014, ie, two days before the FBR was purportedly performed, Sum Marn Peng had visited the Accused’s clinic, during which tooth #26 was extracted by the Accused’s colleague, Dr Teo. The Defence suggested to Sum Marn Peng that Dr Teo could possibly have, in extracting her tooth, inadvertently left a foreign body embedded in her gum. The Defence suggested that when Sum Marn Peng visited the Accused’s clinic two days after that, on 18 March 2014, the Accused decided to remove that foreign body.[note: 177] I should point out at this juncture that this was the first time that the Defence raised the possibility of the Accused’s clinic being responsible for leaving a foreign body in Sum Marn Peng’s gum. Even then, the Defence did not see fit to call Dr Teo as a witness to support this conjecture. Notwithstanding, Sum Marn Peng responded stoically: “If that is the case, I would have recalled. No matter how fuzzy my recollection is.”[note: 178]

106    I find Sum Marn Peng’s testimony as to her post-operative state to be just as unequivocal. As explained above, the only post-operative pain which she felt was at the implant site, not anywhere else.165 She recalled that after the procedure, there was no wound[note: 179] and no stitches[note: 180] at the upper left side of her mouth where the FBR purportedly took place.

107    Given Sum Marn Peng’s evidence that the issue of FBR “never popped up” during her discussions with the Accused, her confirmation that no surgery was performed at the purported FBR site, as well as her clear recollection of there being no post-operative wounds or stitches at that site, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on her on 18 March 2014.

(3)    Conclusion on Sum Marn Peng

108    I thus conclude that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922416/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Sum Marn Peng on 18 March 2014, were not performed.

Russel Lee: Were the procedures performed on him?

109    Russel Lee first visited the Accused on 15 August 2014,[note: 181] during which it was discovered that his tooth #36 was shaky.[note: 182] Tooth #36 was consequently extracted by the Accused on this visit.[note: 183] It is the Defence’s case that apart from doing this, the Accused also performed the following two procedures during the visit:[note: 184]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #36 site (using bone harvested from the tooth #36 area); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #21 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

110    The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Russel Lee on 15 August 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false. The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922417/2018) in respect of Russel Lee. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Russel Lee, when they were not.

(1)    ABG not performed on Russel Lee

111    After hearing the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform ABG on Russel Lee on 15 August 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922417/2018.

112    Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 15 August 2014, Russel Lee testified that the Accused did not tell him that bone had to be grafted onto the tooth #36 site,[note: 185]nor did he tell Russel Lee that bone graft material was to be harvested from a donor site on his jaw.[note: 186]

113    The next aspect of Russel Lee’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 15 August 2014. Only local anaesthesia was applied,[note: 187] so he remained conscious. This aspect of Russel Lee’s testimony was also unequivocal. He testified that he did not recall any bone being removed from the purported donor site on his jaw.[note: 188] In fact, when asked if he ever had any bone removed from his jaw in any of his visits to the Accused, Russel Lee’s unequivocal answer was “no”.[note: 189] He also did not recall any bone being grafted onto the extraction site at tooth #36.[note: 190] During cross-examination, it was put to Russel Lee that ABG was performed on him on 15 August 2014, but he categorically disagreed.[note: 191] It was also suggested to Russel Lee in cross-examination that he would not be able to recall even if bone had been harvested from a donor site on his jaw. Russel Lee retorted that he could recall.[note: 192]

114    As regards Russel Lee’s post-operative state, he testified that stitches were present at the tooth #36 site.[note: 193] Although the tooth #36 area was the purported ABG donor site, the presence of stitches here is still only a neutral factor. This is because the tooth #36 site was also the site where the tooth had just been extracted and an implant was being performed, so some stitching was expected. The stitches here thus do not advance the Defence’s contention that bone was harvested from the tooth #36 area for an ABG.

115    I pause to observe that it is somewhat odd that the donor site, from which bone had been purportedly been harvested would be at the tooth #36 area.184 If the tooth #36 site had indeed been deficient in bone, such that bone at that site had to be augmented with bone graft, why would the dentist harvest bone graft material from that same (bone-deficient) area? Effectively, he would be harvesting bone from one area, to graft back onto that very area. This seemingly peculiar situation is also at odds with the Defence’s own stand during the trial, where the Defence had put to Russel Lee that a drill was applied to harvest bone from the lower left ramus, “behind the last teeth”[note: 194] (ie, behind tooth #38), and not at the tooth #36 area. Notwithstanding, even if the Defence were to run the alternative case that bone was harvested from the left ramus behind tooth #38 (instead of the tooth #36 area), this would still be contradicted by the evidence of Russel Lee that that there was no such harvest194 and no stitches at the right ramus behind tooth #38.[note: 195]

116    Given Russel Lee’s evidence that harvesting of bone from his ramus was not raised in his discussions with the Accused, his confirmation that no bone was harvested from his jaw and grafted at the extraction site, as well as his clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches behind tooth #38 at the right ramus, I am satisfied that ABG was not performed on him on 15 August 2014.

(2)    FBR not performed on Russel Lee

117    Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Russel Lee on 15 August 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922417/2018.

118    As regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 15 August 2014, Russel Lee testified that the Accused did not tell him that he had a foreign body embedded in his mouth which needed removal.[note: 196]

119    The next aspect of Russel Lee’s evidence pertains to what was performed during the procedure on 15 August 2014. As alluded to above, only local anaesthesia was applied,187 so he remained conscious. In this respect, Russel Lee testified that he did not recall any FBR being conducted at the tooth #21 area.[note: 197] In fact, when he was asked if he ever had any operation done at the tooth #21 area, his reply was a flat “no”.[note: 198] During cross-examination, the Defence put to Russel Lee that FBR was performed on him on 15 August 2014, but he categorically disagreed with this.[note: 199]

120    Russel Lee’s testimony as to his post-operative state was just as unequivocal. He testified that there was no wound at the site of tooth #21, where the FBR was purportedly conducted.[note: 200] He also affirmed, on multiple occasions, that there were no stitches at that site.[note: 201]

121    Given Russel Lee’s evidence that the issue of FBR was not raised during his discussions with the Accused, his confirmation that no procedure was performed at the site of tooth #21, as well as his clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches at that site, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on him on 15 August 2014.

(3)    Conclusion on Russel Lee

122    I thus conclude that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922417/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Russel Lee on 15 August 2014, were not performed.

Ng Pei Fen: Were the procedures performed on her?

123    Ng Pei Fen first visited the Accused on 13 September 2014.[note: 202] During that visit, the Accused had performed an implant procedure at the tooth #35 site.[note: 203] The Defence’s case is that apart from doing this, the Accused also performed the following two procedures during that visit:[note: 204]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #45 site (using bone harvested from the tooth #45 area); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #37 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

124    The Prosecution’s case is that ABG and FBR were not performed on Ng Pei Fen on 13 September 2014, meaning that the Medisave claim was false.
