The Prosecution thus preferred one cheating charge under s 420 of the Penal Code (DAC 922422/2018) in respect of Ng Pei Fen. The charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on Ng Pei Fen, when they were not.

(1)    ABG not performed on Ng Pei Fen

125    After hearing the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform ABG on Ng Pei Fen on 13 September 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922422/2018.

126    Firstly, as regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 13 September 2014, Ng Pei Fen’s evidence contained some ambiguity. In cross-examination, she was asked if she could recall the Accused telling her that the tooth #45 site had a defective wall that required grafting, to which she replied that she could not.[note: 205] However, when it was put to her that the Accused did tell her this, she said she was not sure.[note: 206] Given the rather open-ended nature of her evidence, I am unable to derive much assistance from Ng Pei Fen’s testimony as regards whether ABG was discussed with the Accused.

127    However, Ng Pei Fen’s testimony as to what was performed during the procedure on 13 September 2014 was couched in much stronger terms. Only local anaesthesia was applied,[note: 207] meaning that she remained conscious. To recapitulate, it was the Accused’s defence that bone graft material had been harvested from the tooth #45 area and grafted onto the tooth #45 site. However, Ng Pei Fen’s testimony plainly contradicted this:

(a)     Firstly, Ng Pei Fen was sure that no anaesthetic had been applied to the right side of her mouth, where tooth #45 is situated and where the bone harvest and bone augmentation purportedly occurred. Ng Pei Fen remembered numbness at the lower left area of her mouth (where the implant procedure at the tooth #35 site was being performed) and confirmed that the rest of her mouth was not numb.[note: 208] Thus, she could feel the right side of her face when she touched it.[note: 209] During cross-examination, she maintained that anaesthetic cream was applied only to the left side of her mouth and not the right.[note: 210] She stated, thrice, that despite the passage of time, this was something that she could recall.[note: 211] Given that no numbing cream was applied to the right side of her jaw, Ng Pei Fen was able to affirm that no anaesthetic injection was applied to the right side of her jaw.[note: 212] Without such an anaesthetic injection, the inference would be that a major surgery such as a bone harvest could not possibly have been performed at the tooth #45 area. The Defence tried to cast doubt on this, by reminding Ng Pei Fen that she had suffered some nerve damage affecting the lower right quadrant of her mouth.[note: 213] However, Ng Pei Fen explained that the nerve damage only impacted the sensation at her lower right lip −it neither affected her jaw[note: 214] nor her gums.[note: 215]

(b)     Secondly, Ng Pei Fen testified unequivocally that during her visit on 13 September 2014, no cuts were made at her lower right jaw[note: 216] and no bone was harvested from there.[note: 217] She also did not recall hearing a drill, which the Accused claimed had been used to harvest bone from the donor site.[note: 218] She went so far as to testify that nothing was done on the right side of her jaw on that visit.[note: 219] Under cross examination, the Defence suggested that an incision had been made to the tooth #45 area on 13 September 2014, but she held her ground and maintained that she did not recall anything being done on the right side of her mouth.[note: 220] She confirmed that no bone grafting had been performed at the tooth #45 site, clarifying that this was not just a case of her not remembering whether a bone graft was carried out, but her expressly disagreeing with the suggestion that a bone graft was carried out.[note: 221]

128    Ng Pei Fen’s testimony on her post operative state further reinforced her position that no ABG was performed at the lower right side of her mouth. She confirmed that her only wound was at the at the tooth #35 site, where the implant procedure was carried out.[note: 222] There were no wounds at her lower right jaw[note: 223] (where tooth #45 is sited), nor did she feel any post-operative pain there.[note: 224] Under cross-examination, Ng Pei Fen was steadfast in her testimony that there were no stitches at the tooth #45 area.[note: 225] When it was suggested to her that the passage of time may have caused her to forget about the stitches at the tooth #45 area, she maintained that this was not the case.[note: 226]

129    Again, I find it slightly peculiar that the donor site, from which bone had been harvested for the purported ABG, would be at the tooth #45 area −see the similar observations which I made in respect of Russel Lee, at paragraph 115 above. If the tooth #45 site had indeed been deficient in bone, it seems odd for a dentist to graft bone onto that site using bone harvested from the very same area. This also ran counter to the position put forward by the Defence to Ng Pei Fen at trial, ie, that the Accused harvested bone from the tooth #37 area (ie, where the FBR was purportedly done) and not the tooth #45 area.[note: 227] Be that as it may, even if the Defence runs the alternative claim that bone had been harvested from the tooth #37 area (rather than the tooth #45 area), this would still be contradicted by Ng Pei Fen’s evidence that there was no such harvest,227 and (as set out at paragraph 134 below) no stitches, at the tooth #37 area.

130    Given Ng Pei Fen’s confirmation that bone was neither harvested from nor grafted onto her jaw, as well as her clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches at the tooth #45 or tooth #37 areas, I am satisfied that ABG was not performed on her on 13 September 2014.

(2)    FBR not performed on Ng Pei Fen

131    Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that the Accused did not perform FBR on Ng Pei Fen on 13 September 2014, contrary to what was declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922422/2018.

132    As regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedure on 13 September 2014, Ng Pei Fen testified that she did not raise any issues with her tooth #37 to the Accused, nor did he highlight any issues with that tooth.[note: 228] The Accused did not tell her about any foreign body at the tooth #37 area that required removal.[note: 229] She testified that the Accused also did not inform her during the procedure that day about him removing a foreign body from the tooth #37 area.[note: 230] In cross-examination, she maintained that she could not recall the Accused telling her about a foreign body lodged in the gum at the tooth #37 area.[note: 231] I find this remarkable, given that even the Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau opined that as the gum is a sensitive part of the mouth, a patient would usually be aware if a foreign body was embedded there (see paragraph 23(a)(ii) above).

133    The next aspect of Ng Pei Fen’s evidence pertained to what was performed during the procedure on 13 September 2014. As mentioned above, only local anaesthesia was applied,207 meaning that Ng Pei Fen remained conscious. She confirmed that the Accused did not remove a foreign body from the tooth #37 area[note: 232] and did not even make a cut there.[note: 233] In cross-examination, she reaffirmed that the Accused did not cut her gum at the tooth #37 area.[note: 234]

134    I note that Ng Pei Fen had rather candidly agreed that with the local anaesthesia applied to the tooth #35 implant site (which was just two teeth away from tooth #37), she may not have been able to feel an incision to the tooth #37 area, if one had indeed been made.[note: 235] The Defence seeks to use this to argue that Ng Pei Fen’s evidence as to what transpired during the procedure is inconclusive.[note: 236] Even if I accept this, I still find that Ng Pei Fen’s evidence on her post-operative state, ie, after the anaesthetic had worn off, to be compelling. As explained above, Ng Pei Fen confirmed that her only wounds were at the tooth #35 site, where the implant procedures were carried out.222 She could clearly recall that she only had stitches at the tooth #35 implant site and there were no stitches at the tooth #37 area[note: 237] −she also clarified that this was something she could recall notwithstanding the passage of time.[note: 238] She even explained that she had looked in the mirror and saw the stitches at the tooth #35 implant site, but did not see stitches at the purported FBR site at the tooth #37 area.[note: 239] When the Defence suggested to her that she could be mistaken, given that tooth #35 and tooth #37 were relatively proximate, she repeatedly maintained that both areas were different and she was not mistaken.[note: 240]

135    Given Ng Pei Fen’s evidence that the issue of FBR had not been raised in her discussions with the Accused, as well as her clear recollection of there being no post-operative stitches at the purported FBR site at the tooth #37 area, I am satisfied that FBR was not performed on her on 13 September 2014.

(3)    Conclusion on Ng Pei Fen

136    I thus conclude that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in DAC 922422/2018 to have been performed by the Accused on Ng Pei Fen on 13 September 2014, were not performed.

James Lee: Were the procedures performed on him?

137    James Lee first visited the Accused on 27 January 2014[note: 241] as his tooth #27 was in pain.[note: 242] This tooth was extracted by the Accused on that visit.[note: 243] The Defence’s case is that apart from extracting tooth #27, the Accused also performed the following two procedures during that visit:[note: 244]

(a)      ABG at the tooth #27 site (using bone harvested from the lower left jaw); and

(b)      FBR at the tooth #37 area.

He thus made a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for both these procedures, for which his clinic was paid $1,900.

138    The Defence claims that during the visit on 27 January 2014, the Accused performed bone grafting not only at the tooth #27 site but at the tooth #37 site[note: 245] (ie, at where the FBR was purportedly performed) as well. Neo Kheng Yew had then returned at a later visit for implants to be fitted at both these (freshly grafted) sites, at teeth #27 and #37. It is the Defence’s case that after being fitted, both implants came loose, leading to James Lee having to visit the Accused on 25 September 2014 for them to be tightened. The Accused claims that at that visit, he unscrewed the implants at the teeth #27 and #37 sites, added bone graft powder into the apertures and reinserted both implants with a wrench.[note: 246] This formed the basis for him making a Medisave claim to the CPF Board for “implant surgery” (comprising the re-tightening of both these implants), for which his clinic was paid $2,200.

139    The Prosecution’s case is that (a) ABG and FBR were not performed on James Lee on 27 January 2014; and (b) the “implant surgery” was not performed on James Lee on 25 September 2014, meaning that both the Medisave claims above were false. The Prosecution thus preferred two cheating charges, both under s 420 of the Penal Code, against the Accused:

(a)     DAC 922420/2018 alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that ABG and FBR were performed on James Lee, when they were not.

(b)     DAC 922421/2018 alleged that the Accused dishonestly induced the CPF Board to disburse $2,200, by submitting the Medisave claim falsely declaring that implant surgery was performed, when it was not.

(1)    ABG and FBR on 27 January 2014

140    After hearing the evidence, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as regards his claim that ABG and FBR were performed on James Lee on 27 January 2014, as declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922420/2018.

141    James Lee’s account of what was discussed with the Accused in the lead up to the procedure did not support the Prosecution’s case:

(a)     As regards the ABG procedure, James Lee testified that during the visit on 27 January 2014, the Accused did tell him that the implant site might have to be grafted with bone taken from another site.[note: 247]

(b)     As regards the FBR procedure, James Lee initially testified that the Accused did not tell him anything about a foreign object at the tooth #37 area.[note: 248] However, during cross-examination, he conceded that the Accused could possibly have said this, but he forgot.[note: 249]

142    James Lee’s evidence of what was performed during the procedure on 27 January 2014 also appeared to leave open the prospect that ABG and FBR were performed:

(a)     As regards the ABG procedure, James Lee agreed that numbing cream had been applied to the purported donor site at the left ramus behind tooth #38.[note: 250] When asked if the Accused could have harvested bone with a drill at his left ramus, James Lee’s response was noncommittal, to the effect that all he did was to open his mouth and he was not sure what the Accused did.[note: 251]

(b)     As regards the FBR procedure, James Lee agreed that numbing cream was applied to the tooth #37 area,250 where the FBR purportedly took place. When asked if he could recall the Accused slicing his gum at that area and removing a foreign body, he was again noncommittal, replying that he could not see if the Accused did so or not.[note: 252]

143    Finally, James Lee’s evidence about his post-operative state also failed to preclude the possibility that the procedures were performed:

(a)     James Lee testified that the entire left side of his mouth was swollen[note: 253] – this quadrant would have encompassed both the purported ABG donor site (at the left ramus) and the purported FBR site (at the tooth #37 area).

(b)     Furthermore, James Lee testified that there were stitches in his mouth, but he could not remember where[note: 254] −thus leaving open the possibility that stitches were present at the purported ABG harvest site and FBR site.

There is hence nothing in James Lee’s evidence to satisfy me that the relevant sites were indeed free of pain and stitches.

144    Given the state of James Lee’s testimony on this charge, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as regards his claim that the ABG and FBR, which were the subject of the Medisave claim in DAC 922420/2018, had in fact been performed. This thus raises a reasonable doubt as to whether the Medisave claim was false and, consequently, whether deception was practised. Without that element of deception being established beyond reasonable doubt, the charge in DAC 922420/2018 is not made out.

145    Consequently, I acquit the Accused of the cheating charge in DAC 922420/2018.

(2)    Implant surgery on 25 September 2014

146    Having heard the evidence, I also give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as regards his claim that implant surgery was performed on James Lee on 25 September 2014, as declared in the Medisave claim in DAC 922421/2018.

147    James Lee was prepared to accept that by September 2014, the implants at both the tooth #27 and tooth #37 sites had already been inserted, although he could not recall the exact visit when the insertions were done.[note: 255] Initially James Lee testified that after the Accused inserted the implant screws for teeth #27 and #37, there were no subsequent visits where the implants had to be tightened.[note: 256] However, this statement was significantly watered down in cross-examination:

(a)     James Lee agreed that the purpose of the 25 September 2014 visit was for the Accused to check if the implants had been firmly embedded in the jawbone.[note: 257]

(b)     As regards the implant at tooth #27:

(i)       When James Lee was asked to confirm if the Accused had sliced his gum at the tooth #27 location and found the implant to be shaky, James Lee replied that he could not recall, given that six plus years had elapsed.[note: 258]

(ii)       When he was asked if the Accused had removed the implant at tooth #27, inserted bone graft powder into the aperture, and screwed the implant back into the aperture with a wrench, James Lee replied that he did not see this being done.[note: 259]Yet, James Lee recalled the Accused tightening the implant.[note: 260]

(c)     As regards the implant at tooth #37:

(i)       When James Lee was asked to confirm if the Accused had sliced his gum at the tooth #37 location and found the implant to be shaky, James Lee similarly replied that he could not recall.[note: 261]

(ii)       When he was asked if the Accused had removed the implant at tooth #27, inserted bone graft powder into the aperture, and screwed the implant back into the aperture with a wrench, James Lee replied that he did not see this being done but acknowledged that this was possible.[note: 262]

148    Clearly, James Lee was unable to affirmatively refute the Accused’s claim that he re-opened the implant sites on 25 September 2014, removed the implants, added further graft material and re-inserted the implants. Instead, James Lee’s acknowledgement that it was possible for the Accused to have performed these steps, as well as his testimony that he heard a wrench, corroborated that claim.

149    James Lee’s evidence on his post-operative state also did not advance the Prosecution’s case. When it was suggested to James Lee that the incision made to tooth #27 on 25 September 2014 was very small, so that no stitching was needed to close the wound, he agreed. [note: 263] It was also suggested to James Lee that the incision at #37 was also very small, so that no stitching was needed to close it, to which he replied that he did not know. [note: 264] In light of these responses by James Lee, even if post-operative stitches had been absent after 25 September 2014, this would not be at odds with the Accused’s version of events on how he performed re-tightening of the implants that day.

150    Given how James Lee’s testimony did not contradict (and at some points even corroborated) the Defence’s case on this charge, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as regards his claim that the implant surgery, which was the subject of the Medisave claim in DAC 922421/2018, was performed. If it was performed, the Medisave claim would not have been false. This would raise a reasonable doubt as to whether deception had indeed been practised on the CPF Board. Without that element of deception being established beyond reasonable doubt, the charge in DAC 922421/2018 is not made out.

151    I thus acquit the Accused of the cheating charge in DAC 922421/2018.

Tay Sai Gek: Were the procedures performed on her?

152    Tay Sai Gek first visited the Accused’s clinic on 13 July 2012. As at this visit, she already had a few missing teeth in her mouth, including teeth #46[note: 265], #27[note: 266] and #36. The tooth #36 site also had an implant foundation inserted by Tay Sai Gek’s previous dentist.[note: 267] The visit on 13 July 2012 was prompted by Tay Sai Gek’s suspicion that her previous dentist had, when inserting the implant foundation at tooth #36, cracked the neighbouring tooth #37.[note: 268] This led to the Accused extracting tooth #37 at the 13 July 2012 visit,[note: 269] thereby adding to the list of missing teeth in Tay Sai Gek’s mouth. There is also some suggestion that the Accused then performed ABG at the tooth #37 extraction site, using bone harvested from Tay Sai Gek’s left ramus. In the subsequent visits that followed, the Accused purportedly performed various procedures at the sites of the missing teeth −these formed the subject of the cheating charges relating to Tay Sai Gek.

153    In total, the Accused faces four cheating charges in respect of Tay Sai Gek, all under s 420 of the Penal Code:

(a)     DAC 922423/2018 charged the Accused with dishonestly inducing the CPF Board to disburse $3,400, by submitting a Medisave claim for the following procedures that had purportedly been performed on 5 January 2013:[note: 270]

(i)        Implant insertion at the tooth #36 site; and

(ii)        ABG at the tooth #46 site (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus).

(b)     DAC 922424/2018 charged the Accused with dishonestly inducing the CPF Board to disburse $3,400, by submitting a Medisave claim for purportedly performing ABG on 29 January 2013 at the tooth #44 site (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus).[note: 271]

(c)     DAC 922425/2018 charged the Accused with dishonestly inducing the CPF Board to disburse $3,400, by submitting a Medisave claim for purportedly performing ABG on 18 May 2013 at the tooth #27 site (using bone harvested from the region of the right ramus).[note: 272]

(d)     DAC 922426/2018 charged the Accused with dishonestly inducing the CPF Board to disburse $1,900, by submitting a Medisave claim for purportedly performing ABG on 3 August 2013 at the teeth #36 & #37 sites (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus).[note: 273]

The Prosecution’s case is that the above procedures were not performed on Tay Sai Gek, meaning that all four Medisave claims above were false.

154    After hearing the evidence, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as regards his claim that the procedures in the four charges above were performed on Tay Sai Gek, as declared in the Medisave claims in DACs 922423, 922424, 922425 and 922426 of 2018.

(1)    Tay Sai Gek’s testimony

155    Of all the patients, I find Tay Sai Gek’s recollection to be the murkiest.

156    As regards what was discussed prior to and during the procedures, Tay Sai Gek was asked if she could recall the Accused telling her that she needed to harvest bone from her jaw. Her response was “I have forgotten”.[note: 274]

157    As regards what was performed during the procedure, Tay Sai Gek’s evidence was similarly devoid of material. Despite only local anaesthesia being applied (meaning that she remained conscious),[note: 275] she was unable to recall any of the key aspects of the procedures. I set out her evidence below.

(a)     DAC 922423/2018 pertained to the Accused’s Medisave claim for the procedures purportedly performed on 5 January 2013, ie, (i) Implant insertion at the tooth #36 site; and (ii) ABG at the tooth #46 site (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus). Tay Sai Gek’s testimony on this charge is set out below:

(i)       As regards the purported implant insertion at the tooth #36 site, Tay Sai Gek’s evidence was that when she first visited the Accused, there was already an implant at that site, inserted by her previous dentist.267 When she was asked if the Accused did anything to that existing implant prior to performing the purported implant insertion at the tooth #36 site, she said “I really cannot recall all these things.”[note: 276] When she was asked if the Accused had operated on tooth #36, she said “I really cannot recall”.[note: 277] The haziness of her testimony was compounded by the fact that as at the point of trial, there did not appear to be any implant at the tooth #36 site.[note: 278] This was puzzling because, if the Accused had indeed done nothing to the tooth #36 site, the implant inserted by Tay Sai Gek’s previous dentist would presumably still have been there. I had asked Tay Sai Gek to clarify whether, by “cannot recall”, she meant that she could not recall the Accused performing the procedure (implying that the procedure was not done), or that she could not recall whether the procedure was done (which left open the prospect that the procedure might have been done). Her reply was “I really don’t know whether he did this or not.”[note: 279]

(ii)       As regards the purported ABG, she was asked if bone was harvested from her left ramus, to which she said “I really cannot recall”.[note: 280] When asked if she could recall bone being grafted to tooth # 46 on 5 January 2013, she replied that “I cannot recall any of this”[note: 281] and “this is already a long time ago, I cannot recall whether he did this or not”.[note: 282]

Clearly, Tay Sai Gek’s recollection was so poor that she was unwilling to take a stand on what the Accused did or did not do on 5 January 2013.

(b)     DAC 922424/2018 pertained to the Accused’s Medisave claim for the procedure purportedly performed on 29 January 2013, ie, ABG at the tooth #44 site (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus). When asked about this procedure, Tay Sai Gek replied that the Accused did perform an operation at the tooth #44 site and stitched it up, although she did not know what he did.[note: 283] As such, this was not at odds with the Accused’s claim that ABG was performed on tooth #44, on 29 January 2013.

(c)     DAC 922425/2018 pertained to the Accused’s Medisave claim for the procedure purportedly performed on 18 May 2013, ie, ABG at the tooth #27 site (using bone harvested from the region of the right ramus). When asked about this procedure, Tay Sai Gek’s response was “Really all this, I cannot remember”.[note: 284] Her testimony thus did not controvert the Accused’s claim that ABG was performed that day.

(d)     DAC 922426/2018 pertained to the Accused’s Medisave claim for the procedure purportedly performed on 3 August 2013, ie, ABG at the teeth #36 and #37 sites (using bone harvested from the region of the left ramus). When asked about this procedure, Tay Sai Gek’s response was “Honestly, regarding all these, I really don’t know”.[note: 285] Again, she was unable to commit as to what was done that day.

158    As regards her post-operative state, Tay Sai Gek was asked if there were stitches at her ramus, to which she replied that she “cannot recall”.[note: 286] She was also specifically asked if there were stitches at her left ramus, given that three of the four cheating charges involved bone purportedly being harvested from there. Her response was “I have forgotten”.[note: 287] When asked the same question, but in relation to the right ramus, her response was: “I can’t recall. I really have no recollection”. [note: 288]

159    One thus sees that Tay Sai Gek’s testimony on all aspects of the procedures, from the pre-operative discussions, to what was performed during the procedures, to whether post-operative wounds and stitches were seen, affords no support whatsoever for the four cheating charges.

(2)    The expert evidence

160    To establish the four cheating charges in respect of Tay Sai Gek, the Prosecution has yet another plank in its case. This is the expert evidence which the Prosecution says clearly shows that the bone harvests could not possibly have been carried out in the manner claimed by the Accused.

161    Firstly, the Prosecution contends that a dentist must do a Computed Tomography (“CT”) scan of the ramus prior to the harvest, to properly assess the location of the mandibular nerve running through the jawbone. Dr Loh testified that the position of this nerve is highly variable −both in terms of the nerve’s depth below the surface of the ramus, as well the nerve’s distance from the buccal and lingual wall of the jawbone.[note: 289] While an X-ray may show the nerve’s depth, it will not show how close the nerve is to the buccal or lingual wall.[note: 290] The surgeon thus needs to perform a cone beam three dimensional (“3D”) CT scan to pinpoint the nerve’s exact location, to avoid the risk of cutting the nerve when excavating the harvest site.[note: 291] Harvesting bone without first performing such a scan was tantamount to “driving blind”[note: 292] −this would be negligent and foolhardy.[note: 293]

162    The Prosecution points out that there was no evidence of the Accused ever having performed a 3D CT scan of the harvest sites of any of his patients, prior to the purported bone harvests.[note: 294] This, argues the Prosecution, lends support to the inference that the bone harvests were never done. In the case of Tay Sai Gek, where so many harvests were purportedly carried out at the same (ie, the left) ramus, the risk of hitting the mandibular nerve would have been compounded with each successive harvest. The absence of a 3D CT scan thus creates a strong inference that the bone harvests were never performed.

163    In my view, the Accused’s failure to do a 3D CT scan is not determinative. The parameters underlying Dr Loh’s opinion appear somewhat open-ended. It is possible that his opinion on the need for a 3D CT scan applies only when harvesting large amounts of bone. That would render Dr Loh’s opinion consistent with that of the Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau, who testified that while a CT scan might be recommended when harvesting large amounts of bone, there is little risk of striking the mandibular nerve when harvesting only a small amount of bone from the ramus.[note: 295] That appears to be the case here, where the Accused claims to have used a trephine drill to harvest only small discs of bone that were 5 mm in diameter[note: 296] and only 1-2 mm thick[note: 297]. I also note that even Dr Loh contemplated that a 3D CT scan is not always necessary, as he alluded to how highly experienced maxillofacial surgeons can ascertain the amount of bone to be harvested without risk of hitting the mandibular nerve, simply by looking at panoramic radiographs (rather than a CT scan).[note: 298]

164    As such, I consider that the Accused’s failure to perform a pre-procedure 3D CT scan at the ramus to be only a neutral factor.

165    Secondly, the Prosecution stresses how unusual it was for a dentist to perform so many bone harvests at the same ramus, all within the short span of slightly over a year. The Prosecution maps out the harvests purportedly performed by the Accused, in the following table:

Cheating Charge

ABG graft site*

Date

ABG harvest site

-

#37

13 Jul 2012

Left ramus

DAC 922423/2018

#36, #46

5 Jan 2013

DAC 922424/2018

#37, #44

29 Jan 2013

DAC 922425/2018

#27, #46

18 May 2013

Right ramus

DAC 922426/2018

#36, #37

3 Aug 2013

Left ramus



*Sites emphasised in bold are subjects of the four cheating charges; the others are not.

From this table, one sees that two of the harvests at the left ramus took place within 24 days of each other (in January 2013).

166    The Prosecution’s case is that it is not possible to take so many bone harvests from the same site, over such a short span of time. In support of this contention, the Prosecution relies on the evidence of its experts:

(a)     Dr Loh explained that when bone is harvested from the ramus, the surgeon does not have to dig very deep before he risks hitting the mandibular nerve or other vital structure.[note: 299] With each harvest, the amount of bone remaining on the ramus gets progressively thinner,[note: 300] meaning that each subsequent harvest gets progressively closer to the mandibular nerve.[note: 301] Surgeons thus generally avoid going back to the same surgical site when harvesting bone.[note: 302] Dr Loh also said that the bone structure might be less affected if the surgeon simply scrapes off just a bit of bone.[note: 303] But in this case, what the Accused claims to have done was to drill the ramus with a trephine drill and pull out multiple pieces of bone. Performing such bone harvests repeatedly at the same site would be “pushing the envelope really a bit too far”.[note: 304] The attendant risks are further magnified if the surgeon does not perform (as the Accused in this case similarly did not perform) a 3D CT scan of the jawbone to get a sensing of the mandibular bone’s location, before embarking on the harvest.

(b)     Dr. Andrew Tay shared Dr Loh’s concerns, highlighting that he did not know of any surgeon who would enter the same ramus four times, unless there was absolute necessity to do so.[note: 305] As with Dr Loh, Dr Andrew Tay opined that digging another hole in the same spot of the jawbone brings the surgeon increasingly close to the nerve, risking damage to it.[note: 306] Dr Andrew Tay also explained how repeated entries to the same site to harvest bone can have other negative effects, such as:

(i)       weakening the bone, giving rise to structural integrity issues and possibly even bone fracture;[note: 307] and

(ii)       other complications such as bleeding, infection, and neuropathic pain at the site.[note: 308]

Dr Andrew Tay thus opined that if repeated harvests are necessary, the Accused could simply have harvested bone from another site, eg, the chin, rather than returning to same ramus.[note: 309]

167    The Defence counters that the Prosecution experts had all erroneously assumed that the multiple harvests from Tay Sai Gek’s ramus were taken from the same site. However, the fact that the harvests were taken from the same side (ie, the left ramus) did not mean that they had to be taken from the same site on that side.[note: 310] The Defence maintains that it is possible to take harvests from different sites on the same side, even within a short span of time.

168    I am prepared to give the Defence the benefit of the doubt on this point. While the Prosecution experts touched extensively on the challenges of repeated harvests from the same ramus, they had not, in my view, sufficiently touched on the scenario where the surgeon merely takes repeated small harvests from different sites on the ramus (as in this case where the Accused claims to have taken very small discs of bone of only 5mm in diameter – see paragraph 163 above). That small pieces of bone could be successively harvested from different sites of the ramus finds support in Dr Alfred Lau’s expert evidence. Dr Alfred Lau pointed to the literature at exhibit D13(2), which exhibited the following schematic diagram of the ramus below, to illustrate how bone graft material could be harvested from different sites on the same ramus:[note: 311]

Dr Alfred Lau explained:[note: 312]

But of course, if you go back to the same ramus but you are not taking bone at the previous taken site, then you can do it anytime because-- - because it’s the same ramus but not the same site that you take out the bone from. So, uh, if you are not taking the same exact site, then I don’t think the time matters. [emphasis added]

This view appears to make sense. It was possible for the Accused to go back to the same ramus to perform repeated harvests, so long as he avoided the previous site from which he had harvested bone. This would in turn have been possible if the surface area of each harvest was small.

169    As for the Prosecution experts’ concerns that repeated harvests from the ramus would progressively increase the risk that each subsequent procedure would hit the mandibular nerve, I think this would (again) depend on the amount of bone harvested. Dr Alfred Lau explained that the cortical bone at the ramus area is 1-2 mm thick – positioning the drill so that it does not penetrate beyond the cortical bone averts the risk of hitting the mandibular nerve.[note: 313] In this respect, the Accused’s position was that the small discs of bone which he harvested were only 1−2 mm thick. With drilling to such a shallow depth, the risk of hitting the nerve would, according to Dr Alfred Lau’s view, be slim (so long as these discs were harvested from different sites on the ramus).

170    As such, looking at the totality of the expert evidence, the Prosecution has failed to prove beyond reasonable doubt that multiple harvests from the same ramus would necessarily be impossible.

(3)    Conclusion on Tay Sai Gek

171    Given the highly equivocal nature of Tay Sai Gek’s oral testimony, as well as the inconclusive state of the expert evidence on multiple harvests from the same ramus, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as to whether he had performed the implant insertion and ABG on 5 January 2013, as well as the ABG on 29 January, 18 May and 3 August 2013.

172    Consequently, I acquit the Accused of the four cheating charges in respect of Tay Sai Gek in DAC 922423, 922424, 922425 and 922426 of 2018.

Quality of the patients’ testimonies

173    I now canvass the more general criticisms levelled by the Defence against the patients’ testimonies. In essence, the Defence argues that the patients mistook the Accused for not having performed the procedures because:

(a)     Anaesthesia dulled their ability to perceive the procedures when they were being carried out; and

(b)     Lapse of time impacted on their ability to recall the procedures.

174    I find neither of these explanations to be valid, for the reasons below.

Effect of anaesthesia on ability to perceive the procedures

175    The Defence argues that the Accused did perform the relevant procedures but the patients were unaware of what was going on as the anaesthesia administered by the Accused numbed their ability to perceive the procedures being carried out.[note: 314]

176    I am not persuaded by this argument. The anaesthesia administered on all the patients at the time when the procedures were purportedly performed was local (and not general) anaesthesia. Anyone who has undergone surgery at the dentist knows that the local anaesthetic only numbs the pain emanating from the surgical site but does not remove the sensation that something is being done at that site. That sensation is called proprioception.

177    The Prosecution experts testified that anaesthesia would not remove a patient’s proprioception. Both Dr Andrew Tay and Dr Loh explained that even though the pain has been blocked, a patient can still feel the pulling or pushing when the incised gum is being lifted off the bone.[note: 315] Peeling the gum from the bone requires some force because the gum does not simply rest on the bone but is actually attached to it.[note: 316] Furthermore, the patient will feel the vibrations when the drill is applied to the jawbone during the bone harvest.[note: 317]

178    Even the Accused agreed that the patient’s sense of proprioception is retained, notwithstanding the effects of local anaesthetic.[note: 318] The Defence expert, Dr Leo Fung, suggested at one point that the sense of proprioception might be lost after administration of local anaesthetic.[note: 319] However, he subsequently conceded that the patient can still feel the tugging and pushing at the surgical site,[note: 320] as well as the vibrations from the drill.[note: 321]

179    In any case, where I have concluded that the relevant procedures declared in the Medisave claims were not performed, my findings have largely been bolstered by the patient’s evidence that post-operative wounds and stitches were absent at the sites where the procedures were purportedly performed. The patients’ ability to perceive the absence of stitches would not have been impacted by the anaesthesia, which would have long worn off.

Lapse of time impacting on patients’ recollection

180    The Defence also questions the reliability of the patients’ recollection, arguing that the lapse of time would have affected their ability to remember the procedures.[note: 322]

181    However, this submission ignores the plain thrust of the patients’ testimonies. In almost all those instances where I concluded that the relevant surgical procedures declared in the Medisave claims were not performed, it was not just a case of the patient being unable to recall whether the procedures had been done – the patients testified affirmatively that the procedures were not done. They would not be able to testify as such if their recollection had indeed been severely degraded, as suggested by the Defence.

182    The one patient whose testimony was somewhat more nuanced is Juliann Rick. The Defence highlights[note: 323] the following extract from her cross-examination where she testified about her visit on 12 March 2014 (where ABG and FBR had purportedly been performed by the Accused):

Court:

…So, you’ve heard [Defence Counsel] go through the dates with you, there’s the first date which is 12th of March. They were talking about the procedures and I think you have explained that you don’t recall having a bone extracted from your ramus--… you don’t recall a foreign body being removed from the [#26], you say that you do recall some mention of a plastic bone. … So, if at the first visit there was no foreign body removal, right, there was no extraction of a bone graft-- …from your jaw,---… then what was done at this first visit? Can you recall what was the purpose of this first visit? Was there any procedures done?

Witness:

I don’t really remember what was done on the first procedure, Your Honour .

Court:

Okay. So, the question is, is it---was there even procedure or was it just pure consultation?

Witness:

I really don’t remember but---

…

Court:

Okay. So, no recollection at all?

Witness:

Yes.

Court:

Okay. So, you don’t---you can’t recall what was done, you can only recall or rather you can only tell us that you don’t recall whether certain procedures were done?

Witness:

Yah, the---regarding my right, you know, yah.

[emphasis added]



The Defence contends that this aspect of Juliann Rick’s testimony constitutes “a shocking admission … that in reality, she could not recall any procedures on the visit on 12 March 2014 at all”.[note: 324] With respect, this submission omits the most critical qualifier in Juliann Rick’s evidence. As alluded to at paragraph 83 above, Juliann Rick had confirmed, twice, that if bone had indeed been harvested from her ramus, she would have remembered, given that this would have been a major procedure. Her statements that she could not remember must thus be viewed against that critical starting point. As for FBR, she had similarly confirmed in cross-examination that nothing was removed from the tooth #26 area.[note: 325] The Defence’s suggestion that she disavowed all recollection of what happened on the day of the procedure is thus unsubstantiated.

183    The Defence also seeks to cast doubts on the reliability of the patients’ memories by highlighting various details which the patients were unable to recall, which the Defence suggests was emblematic of poor recollection. The following are examples raised by the Defence.

(a)     As regards Neo Kheng Yew, the Defence contends that his recollection was “so severely degraded by the passage of time that it is entirely unsafe to convict the Accused based on his evidence”.[note: 326] To illustrate, the Defence cites how he was unable to recall the following particulars: [note: 327]

(i)       For his visit on 9 April 2014, he could not recall (A) what time he arrived at the Accused’s clinic; and (B) whether numbing cream had been applied to his gum.

(ii)       He was also unable to recall his subsequent appointments, where various treatments were administered, including: (A) removal of his stitches; (B) scaling and polishing; (C) further gum surgery at the implant site, (D) emplacement of the implant; and (v) attachment of the implant crown.

(b)     As regards Russel Lee, the Defence repeats the same claim −that his recollection was “so severely degraded by the passage of time that it is entirely unsafe to convict the Accused based on his evidence.[note: 328] The Defence cites the following instances of particulars that he could not recall:[note: 329]

(i)       For his visit on 15 August 2014, he was unable to recall: (A) the time when he attended at the Accused’s clinic; (B) the number of radiographs taken of his mouth; (C) the spot where the anaesthetic injunction was applied; (D) whether numbing cream and ice spray had been applied, prior to the anaesthetic injection; and (E) whether the Accused tested for the efficacy of the anaesthetic’s numbing effect prior to commencing the procedure.

(ii)       He was also unable to remember the fact that after his visit on 15 August 2014, he visited the Accused’s clinic another eight to ten times.

184    I reject these challenges to the reliability of the patients’ recollection. Firstly, the fact that a witness has some lapses in memory is no reason to throw his entire testimony out: see Ang Jwee Herng v Public Prosecutor [2001] 1 SLR(R) 720 (at [49]). More importantly, a scan of the laundry list of particulars highlighted by the Defence in the preceding paragraph, which Neo Kheng Yew and Russel Lee failed to recall, shows that these details are peripheral in nature. There is nothing surprising if relatively insignificant details fail to get committed to the patient’s memory.

185    In comparison, the experience of having a dentist drill out pieces of bone from one’s exposed ramus, or slice open one’s gums to search for and fish out an embedded foreign object, must surely create a far deeper impression. Yet, both Neo Kheng Yew and Russel Lee were unequivocal that these procedures were not done.

186    Furthermore, in those instances where I concluded that the relevant surgical procedures declared in the Medisave claims were not performed, the patients were able to affirm the absence of post-surgical wounds or stitches at the purported ABG and FBR sites. This is significant, given the expert opinion that it is difficult for a patient to be unaware of such wounds. Dr Andrew Tay testified that there will be pain, significant swelling and sometimes bruising at the harvest site.[note: 330] Similarly, Dr Loh testified that the harvest site will be quite painful, as the process of removing bone is “quite destructive”.[note: 331] There would be post operative bruising and swelling, which the Patient would not be able to overlook given the issues that this poses to the eating process.[note: 332]

187    There would also be “quite a bit of” stitching.[note: 333] It would have been unlikely for the patient to be unaware of post-operative stitches (if they were indeed there), given that the Accused claimed to have used black silk sutures,[note: 334] which would have been visible. Such sutures would not dissolve with time,[note: 335] but may grow elongated after exposure to moisture.[note: 336] They could also be felt with the tongue[note: 337] and brushing on them would cause soreness.[note: 338] The prospect of the patients failing to notice the stitches is rendered even more unlikely by the length of the purported incisions in this case. For the ABG harvest site, Dr Andrew Tay testified that the wound would be at least 2 ½ long.[note: 339] For FBR, Dr Andrew Tay testified that for a small foreign body, one would have to make an incision across two to three teeth, stretching for 1½ to 2 cm.[note: 340]

188    The Defence tries to cast doubt on the Prosecution’s expert evidence as regards the length of the incisions, by highlighting perceived contradictions. As regards the incision required for FBR, the Defence highlights that while Dr Andrew Tay testified that the length of the cut would be 1½ to 2 cm, Dr Loh contradicted this by opining that the cut would be much smaller, at only ½ to 1 cm.[note: 341] To understand this submission, it is necessary to set out what Dr Loh actually said. According to Dr Loh, a surgeon performing an incision for FBR needs to make[note: 342] (a) a “crestal cut” of 1 cm, AND (b) two “relief cuts”, where each relief cut would either be 1 to 2 cm if the foreign body is near the root, or ½ to 1 cm if the foreign body is higher up, at the gumline. The Defence submission, in relying on Dr Loh’s estimate of ½ to 1 cm, has lifted that estimate completely out of context. That estimate relates to the length of each relief cut and not the overall length of the cut. Even if the relief cut is at its shortest, ie, ½ cm, the collective length of the cut, comprising the crestal cut (at 1 cm) plus two relief cuts (at ½ cm each), still adds up to 2 cm. This is still comparable to Dr Andrew Tay’s estimate and, more importantly, by no means small.

189    To conclude on this point, I do not think that the lapse of time had impinged on the recollections of the patients to the point of rendering their testimonies unsafe. In contrast, for someone like Tay Sai Gek, she represented a genuine case where the witness’ memory plainly failed −I thus had no hesitation in giving the Accused the benefit of the doubt and acquitting him of all the charges relating to her. However, for those patients whose memories withstood the test of time, their affirmation that the procedures had not been performed is significant −the major nature of these procedures rendered it highly unlikely for a patient to be oblivious to what was going on. Furthermore, the patients’ clear recollection of the absence of post-operative wounds is also compelling, given that the incisions and stitches, if they existed, would have been sited at a sensitive part of the patient’s mouth (the gums) and by no means trivial in size. The patients would not have affirmatively testified as to the wounds being absent if they had indeed been there.

No reason for the patients to implicate the Accused without basis

190    Finally, it is highly telling that all the patients who testified against the Accused were independent witnesses with no motive to falsely implicate him. This was established in evidence in respect of Catherine Chia,[note: 343] Chong Moh Chin,[note: 344] Neo Kheng Yew,[note: 345] Juliann Rick,[note: 346] Sum Marn Peng,[note: 347] Russel Lee[note: 348] and Ng Pei Fen.[note: 349] Defence Counsel confirmed with each of these seven patients that they were satisfied with the Accused’s dental services, never filed any complaint or report against him and had no cause for ill will against him.

191    Against that backdrop, it is difficult to fathom why all seven patients would each affirm that the relevant procedures were not performed, knowing that this would incriminate the Accused, if they harboured any doubt as to whether the procedures might have been performed.

Prejudice from healing of surgical sites due to delay?

192    The Defence also complains that there was significant delay in bringing the case against the Accused, which prejudiced his defence.[note: 350]

193    The Defence highlights[note: 351] that the procedures which were the subject of the cheating charges had purportedly been performed between April and September 2014, while MoH’s letter suspending the Accused’s Medisave accreditation was sent shortly after that, on 1 December 2014. The police report against the Accused was then filed on 13 February 2015. The Defence tabulates[note: 352] the length of the time which elapsed between each of the relevant procedures (that are subjects of the cheating charges) and the date of MoH’s letter suspending the Accused’s Medisave accreditation:

Patient

Charge

Procedure

Date of Procedure

Timespan to suspension letter on 1 Dec 2014

Catherine Chia

DAC 922412

FBR & ABG

14 Apr 2014

7 months 16 days

Chong Moh Chin

DAC 922413

FBR & ABG

9 Apr 2014

7 months 21 days

Neo Kheng Yew

DAC 922414

FBR & ABG

9 Apr 2014

7 months 21 days

Juliann Rick

DAC 922415

FBR & ABG

12 Mar 2014

8 months 19 days

Sum Marn Peng

DAC 922416

FBR & ABG

18 Mar 2014

8 months 13 days

Russel Lee

DAC 922417

FBR & ABG

15 Aug 2014

3 months 16 days

Ng Pei Fen

DAC 922422

FBR & ABG

13 Sep 2014

2 months 17 days



The Defence argues that within the windows of time in the right column, spanning between 2½ and eight months, MoH should have called the patients for physical examinations to see if the procedures had indeed been performed. MoH’s failure to do so meant that by the time the Accused got around to defending the charges against him, any possible traces within the patients’ mouths which could have served as exculpatory indicia of the procedures having been performed would have ebbed away with the healing process.[note: 353]

194    A close examination of the expert evidence reveals that the Defence’s complaint is unsubstantiated. In essence, the Defence submissions highlight three types of checks which MoH could have conducted to assess if the procedures had indeed been performed: (a) Gum inspection; (b) X-rays; and (c) 3D CT scans. I will cover each of these checks in turn.

Gum inspection

195    The Defence argues that a visual inspection of the gum, even if done six months after a procedure, could have revealed a faint line at where the incision was made.[note: 354] The Defence relies on the following excerpt from Dr Andrew Tay’s cross-examination:[note: 355]

Q:    … Now, Dr. Tay, would you agree with me that about 6 months after the bone harvest procedure can be--- was carried out, okay, there will be no visible evidence left of the incision and the bone harvest?

A    Depending on how you did it, that’s possible, yes.

Q    “That’s possible,” yes. Is it because the gum recovers quite rapidly and quite completely leaving no evidence of the incision?

A    Um, again, depending on how you put it and how you did it, it use---it---it can, uh, but sometimes you can still see a very faint line.

[emphasis added]

196    It is clear from Dr Andrew Tay’s last reply in the extract above that he was not laying a general rule that a faint line will be seen even after six months. This is evident from how he qualified his statement with the word “sometimes”. In fact, experts from both sides had posited even shorter timeframes. For example, Dr Loh alluded to how one would see very little after only about two or three months, because of the healing of the oral mucosa.[note: 356] Even the Defence expert Dr Leo Fung had, when explaining why it was possible for the Accused to make multiple harvests from the same ramus in a short time, suggested that the surgery to the gum will no longer be detectable in six to eight weeks:[note: 357]

… the body heals within 6 to 8 weeks in terms of the mouth, when you cut the gum, in 6 to 8 weeks, you won’t be able to see like a surgery or something was cut at that point in time

[emphasis added].

197    I thus did not think that MoH’s failure to conduct a gum inspection prejudiced the Accused, as this would not necessarily have revealed the incision line.

X-rays

198    The Defence also argues that an X-ray, taken up to one year after the procedure, could have revealed the residual concavity at the site where bone was harvested.[note: 358] In support, the Defence cites the following excerpt from Dr Loh’s evidence-in-chief:[note: 359]

Q    If you did take an X-ray--- .. what will you see? …

A    … if you take a panoramic radiograph, uh, which is a big one,--- … 2 dimensional, um, it will depends on the extent. If you’ve taken out a big chunk of bone from the ramus, you will see that the density of the bone is different because the thickness is now changed. So, you will see at least a thin outline of that triangle---uh, the rectangle they removed.

Q:    And as time goes on, … how … would that … affect?

A:    … Uh, it will heal. And the healing will depend on how much you took out. If you have taken out a lot, then, um, you will still see some residual concavity. The edges won’t be as sharp anymore, it will even out over time, but you will some residual concavity.

Q    I see. 1 year on, what will you see?

A    1 year, uh, probably you will see quite a lot of healing already. You may still see some, uh, residual concavity if you had taken out a lot of bone.

[emphasis added]

199    The extract above clearly shows that Dr Loh was talking about a case where a “big chunk of bone” is harvested from the ramus. At one point, Dr Loh was even referring to taking out a piece of bone that was 1 cm by 1 cm, and how this would necessitate an incision of up to 4 cm in length.[note: 360] This aspect of Dr Loh’s evidence thus does not appear to be apposite, since the Defence’s case is that the bone harvests by the Accused did not remove big chunks of bone. Rather, as explained at paragraph 163 above, the Accused clams to have removed only small discs of bone that were 5mm in diameter and as thin as 1−2mm. To recapitulate, that is how the Defence explained why the Accused could perform multiple harvests on Tay Sai Gek’s left ramus, within a short span of time, without damaging the mandibular nerve. I accepted this aspect of the Accused’s evidence −this was one of the reasons why I have acquitted him of all the cheating charges in respect of Tay Sai Gek.

200    I thus do not think that MoH’s failure to perform an X-ray at the relevant harvest sites prejudiced the Accused. There is no indication that this would have revealed the bone indentations post-harvest, especially when the Accused claimed to have harvested only small bits of bone and not big chunks.

3D CT scans

201    The Defence also argues that 3D CT scans could have revealed if a bone harvest had been performed at the site, even if the scan was done six months to a year after the harvest.[note: 361] In support of this, the Defence cites the following excerpt from Dr Andrew Tay’s evidence-in-chief:[note: 362]

Q

… you said after 6 months, you would have difficulty telling from a radiograph whether any bone had been taken.

A

Yes.

 

…

Court:

But a 3D scan--- …may or may not?

Witness:

Might not be able to tell you.

Court:

Might not be able if the thing is mineralised sufficiently, is that it?

Witness:

It might, if it is completely mineralised like, you know, 10 years after, then you---you can’t tell anything. And… so what I said was, “How long after the original surgery did you scan the patient?” Soon after, you can tell. Some time, beyond, roughly around 6 months, not a magic figure, because biological variation. Uh, you might find that it would be too very difficult to tell for sure.

Court:

You are saying in the context of a 3D scan?

Witness:

3D scan, 6 months to a year.

Court:

You can tell?

Witness:

Usually, you can still tell something.

[emphasis added]



202    I reject the Defence’s attempt to interpret Dr Andrew Tay’s evidence as saying that a 3D CT scan done six months to a year post-procedure would show that bone was harvested from the ramus. As seen from the extract above, Dr Andrew Tay was explicit in qualifying his testimony, saying that the timeframe was “not a magic figure” and that there could be “biological variation”. If the Accused had wanted to advance the notion that a 3D CT scan could reveal traces of a bone harvest six months to a year post-procedure (such that a failure by MoH to do so resulted in real prejudice to his defence), it behoved the Defence to have at least adduced some evidence of this at trial. The Defence did not do this, and instead engaged in a post-trial exercise of selecting portions of the expert testimonies to cobble questionable propositions of science that found scant support on the evidence. I should also point out that the Defence’s own expert, Dr Leo Fung, testified that after six months, one would not see expect to see any more defects in the bone[note: 363] −he voiced this opinion when explaining why it was possible for the Accused to make multiple harvests from the same ramus in a short period of time. Yet, the Defence did not ask Dr Leo Fung to elaborate, nor suggest to him that his estimated timeframe should be qualified in any way. Similarly, the other Defence expert Dr Alfred Lau also said that bone can regenerate in six months[note: 364] −he too was not asked if his timeframe should be qualified.

203    I should also add that the Defence’s argument assumed that the patients would have agreed to undergo CT scans to facilitate MoH’s fact-finding, during those early stages of investigations. Throughout the course of the patient testimonies, the Defence had every opportunity to elicit from the patients whether they would have been willing to undergo a CT scan to assist MoH’s inquiries. The Defence did not see fit to do so but was content to remain silent about this issue, waiting only until submissions at close of trial to speculate. I am hard put to place any weight on this submission, as the question of whether the patients would have been willing to facilitate investigations by undergoing CT scans is not something that can simply be taken for granted. While 3D CT scans reveal more detail than X-rays, they also expose patients to a much higher dose of radiation. Even when compared to a panoramic X-ray, CT scans carry as much as eight to 16 times more radiation.[note: 365]

204    In advancing their submission on prejudice, the Defence also refers to a section of Dr Andrew Tay’s examination-in-chief where he mentioned that he managed to detect a depression at a bone harvest site more than a year after the procedure.[note: 366] The relevant section of the transcript cited by the Defence is extracted below:[note: 367]

Q:    Earlier, you mentioned that in a surgery you had encountered previously, there had been bone taken.

A:    Yes.

Q:    And that when this patient was operated---got u---upon subs---subs--- … subsequently more than a year after, you were able to tell that there was a---

A:     Depressed area.

Q:    there was a depressed area. … Now, how was it you are able to tell more than a year after in that situation?

A:    Alright. So, if you take the regular radiograph, it only shows you two-dimensionally, the state of the bone. If the bone had mineralised and grown back sufficiently, it would have blurred the lines that you had left behind. But if you had done a 3D scan, it is possible you may see a depressed area of the donor site, um, in the same way that we---we saw this in the jaw clinically when we did the second operation.”

[emphasis added]

I fail to see how this portion of Dr Andrew Tay’s testimony assists the Defence’s prejudice argument. Dr Andrew Tay was recounting a situation where he spotted a depression at the bone harvest site during a surgery −appearing to suggest that the gum was opened to allow visual inspection of the bone. It was in this context that Dr Andrew Tay mentioned seeing the depression after a year. I do not understand the Defence to be going so far as to suggest that the patients, to assist MoH’s investigations, had to have their gums sliced open for a visual inspection, failing which the Accused would be prejudiced.

205    As for Dr Andrew Tay’s statement about how a 3D scan might show the depressed area, this was clearly qualified −he said that “it is possible” to see the depressed area but did not comment on the strength of this possibility. In this respect, the Defence’s own expert Dr Leo Fung, took the view that even if the gum were sliced open, there is no guarantee that the indentation from the bone harvest could be seen, given that the bone heals after six months:[note: 368]

Q    Yes. So, once you open up the gum and expose the bone, let’s say in---within the time interval of July 2012 and January 2013, would the clinician be able to see the actual site of where he has previously drilled the bone on July 2012? … Will he be able to see where he actually,---

A    You---you may or may not. Depending on the patient, how quickly they heal. But 6 months has passed from what I can see. 6 months has passed and it’s unlikely that you’re going to see any defect in there since the bone has already grown back by then.

[emphasis added]

Conclusion on whether lapse of time prejudiced the Accused

206    Ultimately, I find that the extracts from the expert testimonies relied on by the Defence do not sufficiently demonstrate that traces of the purported procedures would have been detected by examining the patients early.

207    I am thus not convinced that the Accused was prejudiced by MoH’s failure to conduct early examinations of the patients.

Rarity of the FBR procedure

208    Before setting out my conclusion on the cheating charges, it is necessary to address arguments that both sides made about the rarity of the FBR procedure. To recapitulate, the list of FBR procedures that were the subject of the cheating charges is listed below:

 

Patient

Date that FBR was purportedly performed

1)

Juliann Rick

12 March 2014

2)

Sum Marn Peng

18 March 2014

3)

Chong Moh Chin

9 April 2014

4)

Neo Kheng Yew

9 April 2014

5)

Catherine Chia

14 April 2014

6)

Russel Lee

15 August 2014

7)

Ng Pei Fen

13 September 2014



If these FBR procedures had indeed been performed, as claimed by the Accused in his defence to the cheating charges, it means that he performed at least seven FBRs in seven months, ie, at a frequency of about one FBR every month.

209    The evidence of the Prosecution experts on the rarity of FBR procedures is set out below:

(a)     Dr Andrew Tay testified that as foreign bodies are very rare, he and his colleagues at the Singapore National Dental Centre almost never encounter them.[note: 369] He explained that foreign bodies are usually discovered when there is some swelling or pain or protrusion of the foreign body. Other than that, foreign bodies may be detected by an X-ray.[note: 370] As regards foreign bodies taking the form of amalgams, Dr Andrew Tay remarked that these were also rare, as he saw only a handful of them in his 30-year career.[note: 371]

(b)     Dr Loh similarly testified that foreign bodies in the gum are “very rare”.[note: 372] He remarked that the most common form of foreign bodies were amalgams,[note: 373] which occur in about 2% of the population. He explained that this meant that if all six million people in the Singapore population visit the dentist, the fact that there are 2,200 dentists practising dentists here means that each dentist would see over 50 patients with amalgams.[note: 374]

Based on the evidence of Dr Andrew Tay and Dr Loh, the Prosecution contends that it would not have been possible for the FBR procedures performed by the Accused to have reached the level of frequency which he claimed to have achieved.[note: 375] This in turn supports the inference that his Medisave claims for FBR procedures were not genuine.

210    The Defence attacks the Prosecution’s hypothesis by arguing that the evidence of Dr Loh is at odds with that of Andrew Tay. In particular, the Defence relies on Dr Loh’s point that one to three percent of the population have foreign bodies in the form of amalgams.[note: 376] Dr Loh explained that if a frequency rate of 2% is applied to all six million people in the Singapore population, then assuming all six million people visit the dentists practising in this country, which number about 2,200, each dentist would see over 50 patients with amalgams.374 The Defence then extrapolates this to say that if all six million people in the population were to visit their dentist within the year, each dentist would on average encounter 50 amalgams cases that year. The frequency would be even higher if we include foreign bodies other than amalgams. The frequency of the FBRs claimed to have been performed by the Accused (at only one FBR a month) would thus be well within the norm. Conversely, Dr Andrew Tay’s experience of having seen only a handful of amalgams in his entire career would not be reflective of the probabilities.

211    I note that the figure hypothesized by the Defence, ie, over 50 FBR performed by each dentist in a year, rests on the critical assumption that every single person in our population of six million (including babies) will visit the dentist in that year. No data was offered to show if such an assumption is even remotely realistic. The Defence’s hypothesis also rests on the further assumption that every one of those amalgam cases is detected −if they are not even detected, there would be no FBR to speak of. However, this runs counter to the fact that amalgams are innocuous and cause no pain,[note: 377] such that they are generally not detected unless the amalgam causes a dark stain on the gum called a “tattoo”.[note: 378] In fact, Dr Andrew Tay testified that tattoos are not common.[note: 379] One thus cannot simply presume that every one of those 50 notional cases of amalgams would have been detected, by the materialisation of a tattoo. To be sure, none of the patients called to testify complained of tattoos, nor was the phenomenon of the tattoo reflected in the Accused’s clinical notes on these patients. If most amalgams are not detectable, it is highly dubious to suggest that all amalgam cases would translate into FBR being performed.

212    Rather than making questionable extrapolations premised on highly stretched assumptions that have not been shown to correlate with reality, it is more fruitful to rely on the actual real-life experiences of the experts, as related in their sworn testimonies. In this respect, Dr Andrew Tay’s evidence was that he personally saw only a handful of amalgam cases in his entire career at the Singapore National Dental Centre. None of the Defence experts were able to recount any first-hand experiences of their own, where the frequency of FBRs encountered was higher than what Dr Andrew Tay personally faced.

213    Still, the overall tenor of the Defence experts’ opinions was that foreign bodies occur at a frequency higher than that posited by the Prosecution:[note: 380]

(a)     Dr Alfred Lau opined that while foreign bodies would include amalgams, [note: 381] the most common types of foreign bodies would be food particles such as pieces of bone, shells or nuts.[note: 382] Dr Alfred Lau explained that when such particles get caught in the pocket between the tooth and gum, the “foreign body removal” would include the non-surgical extraction of these particles.[note: 383]

(b)     Dr Leo Fung similarly opined that foreign bodies could comprise seeds, popcorn kernels and toothpicks.[note: 384] He explained that when such bodies get trapped in the pocket between the gum and tooth, the “foreign body removal” would entail extracting the body without surgery.[note: 385] Dr Leo Fung also encountered foreign bodies during his stint working at a Vancouver hospital, where cancer patients who underwent radiation treatment had radioactive seeds trapped in the tissue of their jaws.[note: 386]

214    The Defence experts thus defined the term “foreign body” very broadly, enmeshing a wide array of food and other items. Such a broad definition correspondingly translates into a higher frequency of occurrence of “foreign bodies”. This analysis, while not erroneous in and of itself, fails to answer the immediate issue at hand, which centres not on the frequency of foreign bodies, but on that of foreign body removal (ie, FBR). It was in this respect that I find much of the Defence experts’ evidence to be irrelevant. Both Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Leo Fung defined FBR to include the non-surgical removal of foreign bodies (however defined) trapped in the pocket between the tooth and gum. Such a loose definition has no bearing to the present context. Dr Andrew Tay explained that the FBR for which a Medisave claim may be made must entail a surgical incision, lifting of the gum flap and removal of the foreign body. Non-surgical removal of food stuck in the gum pocket does not count as “FBR” for which a Medisave claim may be made.[note: 387] More importantly, Dr Andrew Tay’s definition of FBR cohered with the Medisave claims in the cheating charges, where the Accused claimed to have performed surgical incisions to remove the foreign bodies, meaning that these were not simply food particles trapped in the gum pocket which could be non-surgically dislodged.

215    When the FBR definition is correctly delineated, the perceived frequency of FBR must necessarily be lower than if that definition includes fishing out of food particles trapped in the gum pocket. Given that both Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Leo Fung both adopted the latter definition, I find their evidence as to the frequency of FBR to be of no assistance. Dr Leo Fung’s evidence about how FBRs may also occur in the form of radioactive seeds embedded for cancer treatment similarly does not assist me, as that experience relates to a context which has no relation to the present factual matrix.

216    Having assessed the testimonies of both the Prosecution and Defence experts as regards the frequency of the FBR procedure, I agree with the Prosecution experts that FBR, when properly defined, is rare in dental practice. This was corroborated by Dr Andrew Tay’s own personal experience.

217    Based on this, the Accused’s Medisave claims for FBR clearly appear out of the ordinary, if we go by Dr Andrew Tay’s experience, as they suggest that the Accused performed one FBR every month, over the span of seven months in 2014. This, in my view, corroborates the evidence of the patients that the FBR procedures that were the subject of the cheating charges were never performed on them.

Conclusion on the cheating charges

218    The elements of the offence under s 420 of the Penal Code are not in dispute. As set out by Yong Pung How CJ in Gunasegaran s/o Payadaisamy v PP [1997] 2 SLR(R) 946 (“Gunasegeran”) (at [42]-[44]):

(a)     the accused must have deceived the victim;

(b)     the accused’s deception must have induced the victim to deliver property to a person; and

(c)     (in accordance with the definition of “cheating” in s 415 of the Penal Code) the accused must have had a dishonest or fraudulent intention when inducing the victim to deliver the property.

Having heard the evidence, I am satisfied that all three elements are established in respect of seven of the cheating charges.

219    To recapitulate, I found that in respect of the following seven patients, the Accused did not perform the procedures which he declared (in the Medisave claims that were the subject of the cheating charges) to have performed. My findings are summarised in the table below:

 

Patient

My conclusion

1)

Catherine Chia

(DAC 922412/2018)

As regards the ABG and FBR declared by the Medisave claim to have been performed:

- I agree with the Prosecution that the FBR was not performed; and

- I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt as to whether the ABG had indeed been performed.

2)

Chong Moh Chin

(DAC 922413/2018)

I agree with the Prosecution that both the ABG and FBR, declared by the Medisave claim in the respective cheating charges to have been performed by the Accused, were not performed.

3)

Neo Kheng Yew

(DAC 922414/2018)

4)

Juliann Rick

(DAC 922415/2018)

5)

Sum Marn Peng

(DAC 922416/2018)

6)

Russel Lee

(DAC 922417/2018)

7)

Ng Pei Fen

(DAC 922422/2018)



Following from the above, I amend the charge in DAC 922412/2018, by deleting the reference to ABG (so that only the reference to FBR remains) and reducing the sum alleged to have been paid by the CPF Board from $1,900 to $350 (the latter figure being what was specifically paid for FBR).

220    The above findings mean that the victim (ie, CPF Board) was deceived in respect of these seven patients. The next question would thus be whether it was the Accused who deceived the victim? This must be answered in the affirmative. The Defence does not seriously dispute that it was the Accused who filed the (false) Medisave claims with the CPF Board. This is unsurprising, given that the investigation statements furnished by the Accused to the police during investigations (referred to as the “Long Statements”) left no room for ambiguity. There were three Long Statements tendered in court, marked as exhibits B38, B39 and B40, which were (respectively) recorded on 8 July 2015 (the day of the raid on the Accused), 9 July 2015 and on 13 November 2015. The relevant answers from the Accused were in the Long Statement B38:

Q 53:

Did you submit the Medisave claims for your patients yourself?

A:

Yes, Mdm Loo will first fill in patient’s particulars and save it as a draft. I will fill up the clinical procedures by keying in the operation codes. And then I will submit the claim.

Q 54:

Why did you submit the Medisave claims for your patients yourself?

A:

I have to check that the procedures submitted are correct. I cannot let any Tom, Dick and Harry submit procedures. Mdm Loo may not have the medical knowledge to fill up this part so I will fill it up and submit the claim thereafter.

Q 55:

How did you fill up the clinical procedures in your Medisave claim?

A:

I based it on the patient notes, determine the suitable operation code.

Q56:

When did you start submitting Medisave claims for your patients?

A:

Once I was Medisave accredited.

Q 57:

How frequently did you submit the Medisave claims for your patients?

A:

I will do it whenever I am free. I will accumulate it and then submit them one shot when I have the time to do it. i have submitted the claims both at my clinics, and at my home. I just need to internet.

…

Q 59:

For what purpose did you disclose your login and password to the Mediclaim system to the clinic staff?

A:

In order to fill up the first part of the form - the patient’s particulars. I will fill up the operation codes thereafter and do the final submission.

…

Q 90:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-002-011 to 012. Who submitted this ‘Universal Claim Form’ via the Medisave system to make Medisave claims?

A:

I submitted it

Q 91:

Who authorised and gave instructions to submit this ‘Universal Claim Form’ via the Medisave system to make Medisave claims?

A:

The final submission is done by me.

[emphasis added]



221    I thus conclude that the first element in Gunasegeran is satisfied in this case, ie, that the Accused had deceived the victim.

222    The second element is that the deception must have induced the victim to deliver property. This element has also been made out on the evidence. It is not in dispute that upon the Medisave claims being filed, the CPF Board was induced to make payment on these claims by transferring the claim sums from the patients’ Medisave accounts to the Accused’s clinic.

223    The final element of the charge is that the Accused must have had a dishonest or fraudulent intention when inducing the victim to deliver the property. In this case, the cheating charges alleged that the Accused “dishonestly” induced the CPF Board to make payment. “Dishonestly” is defined by s 24 of the Penal Code as follows:

Whoever does anything with the intention of causing wrongful gain to one person, or wrongful loss to another person, is said to do that thing dishonestly.

224    Section 23 of the Penal Code in turn defines “wrongful gain” and “wrongful loss”:

“Wrongful gain” is gain by unlawful means of property to which the person gaining it is not legally entitled; “wrongful loss” is loss by unlawful means of property to which the person losing it is legally entitled.

The payments from the CPF accounts of the patients constituted wrongful gain to the Accused’s clinic, as well as wrongful loss to the CPB Board. While not technically a required ingredient for the offence, the Accused also stood to gain personally from the transfers to his clinic, given that he was the clinic’s sole owner and sole director.[note: 388]

225    The question is thus whether the Accused could be said to have intended to cause the wrongful gain or wrongful loss. The circumstances are clear that he did. The Accused was the dentist who purported to have performed the procedures for which the Medisave claims were made, which I have found not to have been performed. He would have known that the Medisave claims were false. During the trial, he did not raise the defence of mistake, in the sense of claiming that the false Medisave claims were unintentionally filed. In any case, any such defence would have been nullified by his subsequent conduct. Of the seven patients, five[note: 389] were subjected to MoH’s audit.[note: 390] Despite these procedures being put in MoH’s crosshairs of scrutiny, the Accused did not withdraw his Medisave claims or admit that the claims were mistakenly filed.
