Instead, he pressed ahead in justifying the claims, with photographs and other documentation. Such ex-post behaviour by an accused person, ie, after the victim has been induced to deliver the property, can properly be taken into account in determining if the inducement had been effected with dishonest intent: see in Gunasegeran, at [48]-[50]. As such, I am of the view that the final element in Gunasegeran is present here −the inducements were effected with dishonest intent.

226    Consequently, I convict the Accused of the charges in respect of the seven patients listed at paragraph 219 above, albeit that the conviction for Catherine Chia is under the charge as amended by myself.

227    I also acquit the Accused of:

(a)     the two cheating charges in respect of the patient James Lee; and

(b)     the four cheating charges in respect of the patient Tay Sai Gek,

as I give the benefit of the doubt to the Accused’s claim that the procedures (to which these six charges related) had indeed been performed.

The Forgery Charges

228    To recapitulate, I have convicted the Accused of the cheating charges in respect of the following seven patients (albeit the charge in respect of Catherine Chia was amended by myself):

2)

Sum Marn Peng

3)

Neo Kheng Yew

9 April 2014

5)

Catherine Chia

14 April 2014

6)

Russel Lee

7)

13 September 2014



In July 2014, MoH commenced an audit in respect of the first five patients in the table, to see if ABG and FBR had indeed been performed on the dates in the right column, as declared in the Medisave claims.[note: 391] As regards the last two patients (Russel Lee and Ng Pei Fen), the ABG and FBR were purportedly performed after the audit in July 2014 −they were thus not caught by the audit.

229    In response to the audit, the Accused tendered various documents to MoH, including photographs to show that the procedures had been performed. The forgery charges in the present case relate to four of the five patients whose cases were audited:

(a)     Catherine Chia;

(b)     Chong Moh Chin;

(c)     Juliann Rick; and

(d)     Neo Kheng Yew.

230    The Prosecution’s case on the forgery charges stem from the same root position undergirding the cheating charges: that the underlying procedures were not performed. The forgery charges alleged that the Accused had, to deceive MoH’s auditors into thinking that the audited procedures were performed (when they were not), forged the photographs which were submitted to MoH.

Background to seizure of exhibits in the forgery charges

231    The MoH officer assisting with the documentation for the audit was Finance Executive Ker Lai Sim (PW15). On 24 July 2014, she sent an email, adduced at trial as exhibit B4, to the Accused’s clinic. The email in B4 sought documentation pertaining to procedures purportedly performed on various patients, for whom the Accused had made Medisave claims, including the four patients in paragraph 229 above.

232    The Prosecution’s case is that the Accused’s clinic responded to the email in B4 by submitting to MoH, inter alia:

(a)     each patient’s operation report (which set out the procedures for which the Medisave claims had been made); and

(b)      photographs of radiographs (ie, not the original radiographs themselves), where the radiographs were purportedly taken of the patient’s teeth before and after the procedure being audited.

233    At the trial, Ker Lai Sim testified as to how she went about making copies of documents that she received from clinics being audited, for MoH’s records.[note: 392] In the case of documents received from the Accused’s clinic, the photographs of the patients’ teeth were enclosed in small Ziplock sachets. She had removed the photographs from the sachets and arranged them (facing downwards) on a photocopier screen, before overlaying the operation report on top of the photographs. She then created a colour photocopy that captured both the photographs and the operation report, on a single A3-sized sheet of paper.[note: 393] Pursuant to this process, she created the following exhibits:[note: 394]

(a)     P6A, being a single A3-sized document capturing:

(i)        Catherine Chia’s operation report; and

(ii)        three photographs of radiographs of her teeth.

(b)     P7A, being a single A3-sized document capturing:

(i)        Chong Moh Chin’s operation report; and

(ii)        four photographs of radiograph of her teeth.

(c)     P8A, being a single A3-sized document capturing:

(i)        Neo Kheng Yew’s operation report; and

(ii)        four photographs of radiographs of his teeth.

(d)      P4, being a single A3-sized document capturing:

(i)        Juliann Rick’s operation report; and

(ii)       three photographs of radiographs of her teeth (of which only one photograph is relevant to the forgery charge).

Ker Lai Sim testified that after making these photocopies, she returned the photographs and operation reports to the Accused’s clinic, under a cover letter dated 25 September 2014 (adduced at trial as exhibit P10).[note: 395]

234    About 9½ months later, on the morning of 8 July 2015, the police conducted a raid on the Accused, executed concurrently at his residence and both branches (Punggol Field and Hougang) of his clinic.[note: 396] During the raid at the Accused’s residence, the police seized:[note: 397]

(a)     In respect of Catherine Chia:

(i)       An operation report, admitted as exhibit B5; and

(ii)        three photographs of her teeth, admitted as exhibits B35(1), B35(2) and B35(3) (collectively referred to as “B35(1)-(3)”).

(b)     In respect of Chong Moh Chin:

(i)       An operation report, admitted as exhibit B6; and

(ii)        four photographs of her teeth, admitted as B36(1), B36(2), B36(3) and B36(4) (collectively referred to as “B36(1)-(4)”).

(c)     In respect of Neo Kheng Yew:

(i)       An operation report, admitted as exhibit B8; and

(ii)        four photographs of his teeth, admitted as exhibits B37(1), B37(2), B37(3) and B37(4) (collectively referred to as “B37(1)-(4)”).

The Prosecution’s case is that the operation reports and photographs in (a) to (c), seized from the Accused’s residence, were the very same items listed in (a) to (c) of paragraph 233 above, which had been submitted to MoH and which Ker Lai Sim returned to the Accused’s clinic (after making the copies P6A, P7A and P8A).

235    During the raid at the Accused’s clinic, the police seized the patient cards of various patients, including those of Catherine Chia, Chong Moh Chin and Neo Kheng Yew. These patient cards documented, inter alia, the patient’s visits to the Accused’s clinic and the procedures performed. The patient’s radiographs were attached to the patient cards, with each radiograph inserted into a small Ziplock sachet that was stapled to the relevant section of the patient card. For purposes of the trial, the Prosecution had removed the radiographs from the patient cards and collated the radiographs by attaching them to a 12-page document that was adduced as exhibit P3. The Prosecution then matched the photographs seized from the Accused’s home (which the Prosecution says were the photographs submitted by the Accused to MoH for the audit and thereafter returned by MoH’s Ker Lai Sim to the Accused) with the radiographs in P3 (seized from the Accused’s clinic) and came to the following conclusions:

(a)      B35(1) and B35(2) were images of the top radiograph at page 1 of P3, denoted in this judgment as P3(1)A.[note: 398]

(b)      B35(3) was an image of the bottom radiograph at page 1 of P3, denoted in this judgment as P3(1)C.[note: 399]

(c)      B36(1) and B36(2) were images of the top radiograph at page 2 of P3, denoted in this judgment as P3(2)A.[note: 400]

(d)      B36(3) and B36(4) were images of the bottom radiograph at page 2 of P3, denoted in this judgment as P3(2)C.[note: 401]

(e)      B37(1) and B37(2) were images of the bottom radiograph at page 3 of P3, denoted in this judgment as P3(3)B.[note: 402]

(f)      B37(3) was an image of the same radiograph as that captured by B37(4).

The radiographs listed immediately above are referred to in this judgment as the alleged “source radiographs”, as they have been alleged by the Prosecution to be the source image captured by each corresponding photograph above. The exception would be in the case of the photographs B37(3) and B37(4), for which the Prosecution was not able to retrieve the source radiograph(s). The Prosecution’s case is that the 10 photographs underlined in bold font above were forged. Specifically, after the images of the alleged source radiographs were captured, these images were then altered to introduce features that would convey the impression that the audited procedures were performed (when they never were). The altered images were then printed to produce the 10 photographs underlined in bold font above.

236    The Prosecution’s case on the forgery charges thus hinged on establishing that these 10 photographs were identical to the alleged source radiographs (or, in the case of B37(3) identical to the photograph B37(3), which captured the same source radiograph), with the only material difference being the alterations.

237    In respect of the fourth patient, Juliann Rick, it was also the Prosecution’s case that the photographs captured in P4 purported to show her teeth before and after the FBR procedure (which, according to the cheating charge in respect of Juliann Rick, was never performed). Specifically, the Prosecution claims that the photograph reproduced at the extreme left in P4 had been altered to insert a white dot. However, (as was the case with B37(3) and B37(4) above), the police were unable to retrieve the source radiograph which this photograph purported to capture. More importantly, unlike in the case of the photographs above, the police were not even able to retrieve the original photographs that were photocopied in P4. The Prosecution thus had to rely on P4 itself, which was obtained from MoH, as second-hand evidence of the photographs that the Accused tendered to MoH for the audit in respect of Juliann Rick.

Experts’ methodologies in respect of the forgery charges

238    As was to be expected, the parties’ respective cases on the forgery charges centred predominantly on the expert evidence. Before delving into the expert testimonies proper, it is first necessary to provide an outline of the approaches adopted by the experts, as well as highlight how their underlying methodologies differed as between the Prosecution and Defence.

239    The photographs in the forgery charges purported to capture radiographs that had supposedly been shot before and after the audited procedure. The Prosecution experts took the view that the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs, bore striking similarities with each other, as well as with the alleged source radiograph. They opined that successive radiographs would not display that degree of similarity. This led inexorably to the conclusion that the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs could not have captured different radiographs. Rather, they must have captured the same source image, this being the alleged source radiograph that the police seized. The Prosecution experts’ testimonies thus focused on demonstrating how the images in the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs and in the alleged source radiograph were the same, with the only material difference being that the photographs contained features that were added to convey the impression that the audited procedures had been performed, which additions were absent in the alleged source radiograph from which the photographs were derived.

240    Conversely, the Defence experts highlighted the differences in features and appearance existing between the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs, as well as between these photographs and the alleged source radiograph, to show that all three images came from different sources, ie, that the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs had captured two successive radiographs, while the alleged source radiograph was yet another radiograph. However, the Defence was not able to produce the source radiographs which the Accused claimed to have been captured by the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs.

241    In a nutshell, the Prosecution experts focused on similarities, while the Defence experts focused on differences. Even then, the traits which the Prosecution experts focused upon (where the perceived similarities occurred) were very different in character from those traits which the Defence experts focused upon (where the perceived differences occurred). This is explained in the following section.

Prosecution experts’ methodology

242    In highlighting the similarities between the images, the Prosecution experts paid particular attention to the following two broad areas:

(a)     Firstly, the Prosecution focused on the striking similarities in the shape and positioning of the patient’s anatomical structures. The Prosecution experts opined that such similarities are compelling, considering the variables involved when intraoral analogue X-rays are taken. The radiograph film is first placed in a film holder that is attached to an implement called a bite plate.[note: 403] The patient then sits on a chair and bites on the bite plate, which holds the radiograph film in place inside the patient’s mouth. The X-ray cone is then aimed at the patient’s mouth and switched on. The X-ray beam passes through the patient’s mouth, striking the radiograph film and transferring the image of the teeth onto the film.[note: 404] When taking the next radiograph, the film holder is removed from the patient’s mouth to allow a fresh radiograph film to be mounted, and the process is repeated. It is thus extremely difficult for successive radiographs to reproduce the shape and positioning of the patient’s anatomical structures, to the degree of similarity seen in the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs in the forgery charges,[note: 405] given the following variables at play:

(i)       When the film holder is replaced into the patient’s mouth for the subsequent radiograph to be taken, there is no way to position the film in exactly the space as the previous occasion.[note: 406]

(ii)       The patient’s movements, including the position and tilt of his head, also affects the angle at which the X-ray beam hits the radiograph film.[note: 407]

(iii)       The positioning of the X-ray cone, from which the X-ray beam emanates, is yet another variable. The fact that the X-ray emanates in a conical beam (as opposed to parallel beams) means that variations will be magnified. This, coupled with the variable distance between the cone and the radiograph film, means that even small changes generate a lot of distortion.[note: 408] This in turn makes taking identical radiographs impossible as it is difficult to position the cone in a manner ensuring that the X-ray beam’s vertical and horizontal angulation is the same in successive shots.[note: 409]

(iv)       Furthermore, once the patient bites on the bite plate, the radiograph film is concealed within the patient’s mouth, meaning that it is very difficult to aim the X-ray cone to strike the film at the exact same angle as before.[note: 410]

The Prosecution experts thus opined that it is impossible for successive radiographs to achieve 100% reproducibility in terms of shape and angulation,[note: 411] as there would always be at least slight differences between successive radiographs.[note: 412]

(b)     Secondly, the Prosecution experts also focused on unique features that were clearly not part of the patient’s anatomy, such as:

(i)       physical defects on the surface of the alleged source radiograph (eg, scratches and indentations); and

(ii)       artefacts, ie, objects that were not part of the clinical setting but were idiosyncratically captured in the image, whether during the process of shooting or developing the radiograph.

The Prosecution experts explained that such physical defects and artefacts, being unique to the radiograph film (and having nothing to do with the patient’s anatomical structures), should not be replicated across multiple radiographs.

Defence expert’ methodology

243    The Defence experts focused on the differences between the images, to support the contention that the photographs captured different radiographs and not the alleged source radiograph seized by the Prosecution. In listing these differences, much focus was placed by the Defence on the following traits:

(a)     Dissimilarities in features such as dots, lines, and various other shapes (including irregular patches and streaks), where these features appeared in one image but either did not appear, or appeared differently, in the other images.

(b)     Differences in appearance, in terms of brightness, definition and texture (eg, appearance of bone patterns).

There were also limited instances where the Defence experts (like the Prosecution experts) focused on the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures, highlighting what they perceived to be differences therein as between the images. The Defence experts had on occasion also highlighted differences in the image’s area of capture.

244    As to why some physical defects (such as scratches and indentations) were transposed across images, the Defence surmised[note: 413] that this might have arisen from multiple radiograph films being damaged at the same spot, while stacked together.

My views on the methodologies

245    It is apparent that the focus of the methodologies from both sides differ significantly. In deciding which aspects of these methodologies should be adopted, I am guided by the decision in Armstrong, Carol Ann (executrix of the estate of Peter Traynor, deceased, and on behalf of the dependents of Peter Traynor, deceased) v Quest Laboratories Pte Ltd [2020] 1 SLR 133 (“Armstrong v Quest”), where the Court of Appeal remarked (at [90]):

Hence, it appears to us that the question of whether to accept or reject an expert’s evidence is ultimately not a question of whether and how the evidence is controverted, but whether any eventual view arrived at is supportable in logic and evidence. The court’s determination as to whether it should accept parts of an expert’s evidence (and if so which parts) is guided by considerations of consistency, logic and coherence … . This requires a scrutiny of the expert’s methodology and the objective facts he had based his opinion upon … .

246    I have looked at the methodologies advanced by both sides to see if they are logical, as well as assessed if the conclusions flowing from those methodologies are supported by the evidence. I set out my views below.

(1)    Shape and positioning of anatomical structures

247    I find the methodology adopted by the Prosecution experts, in terms of focusing on similarities in shape and positioning of the anatomical structures, to be persuasive in logic and coherence. Given the variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam, listed at paragraph 242(a) above, one would naturally expect that strikingly similar shape and positioning in successive radiographs would be the exception rather than the norm. Particularly in a routine clinical setting, where radiographs are captured to facilitate a procedure on a real-life patient (as opposed to radiographs for research purposes, which may be deliberately captured at angles to maximize the similarity between shots). Even the Defence experts, Dr Alfred Lau[note: 414] and Dr Leo Fung,[note: 415] both agreed with the Prosecution’s position that there are many variables at play during the taking of radiographs impacting on shape and angulation.

248    The shape and positioning of the anatomical structures would thus serve as a relatively unique identifier for the radiograph. Isolated instances of striking similarities could still be attributed to coincidence, but when they occur repeatedly in what is supposed to be a routine clinical setting, question marks would be raised that merit an explanation.

(2)    Dissimilarities in features and differences in appearance

249    While the Defence experts focused on dissimilarities in features (such as dots, lines, and other shapes) and differences in appearance (in terms of brightness, definition and texture), the Prosecution experts countered that these variations could be explained by the occurrence of “reprographic errors”,[note: 416]ie, deviations in features and appearance generated when the radiograph is reproduced, whether at the stage of capturing the image or printing it. In this case, the radiographs were reproduced into photographs via three steps:

(a)     According to the Accused, photographic images of radiographs were captured in the following manner: the radiographs were put against a light box[note: 417] and a portable digital camera then used to shoot the illuminated radiographs.[note: 418]

(b)     The soft copy images were then downloaded from the digital camera and edited with photo-editing software to:[note: 419]

(i)       overlay a label above the image, containing the patient’s name, tooth number and date on which the procedure depicted in the image was purportedly performed on the tooth; and

(ii)       crop the image down to size.

(c)     Thereafter, the edited soft copies of the images were printed onto photo paper, thereby producing the exhibits in B35(1)-(3), B36(1)-(4) and B37(1)-(3).

The Prosecution’s position is that reprographic errors could have arisen at any point from capture to printing.[note: 420]

250    To support this contention, the Prosecution extracted a wide array of concessions from the Defence experts as to how reprographic errors can arise:

(a)     As at the point of capture of the photographic image of the radiograph:

(i)       Appearance of features such as dots and smudges could arise from reprographic errors.[note: 421] While not explicitly articulated, this would obviously cover instances where particles and smudges on the radiograph film that are not part of the radiographic image get reproduced onto the photographic images.

(ii)       Differences could also arise from variations in the camera’s focus settings[note: 422] or in the distance between the camera and the radiograph,[note: 423] at the time of capturing the image.

(iii)       As regards differences in brightness, definition and texture, these can arise from:

(A)       Adjustments made to the camera’s exposure settings;[note: 424] and

(B)       Fluctuations in the surrounding lighting conditions when the photograph is taken, including the illumination from the light box.[note: 425]

(b)     As at the point of editing of the soft copy of the photographic image with photo-editing software, variations could also arise from adjustments made to the image file’s settings.[note: 426]

(c)     Finally, at the printing stage, differences could arise arising from:[note: 427]

(i)       the settings of the printer used to print the image file;

(ii)       the quality of the photo paper onto which the image is printed; and

(iii)       the type of photo printing ink used.

251    Apart from reprographic errors, the Defence experts also conceded that there were other explanations for why differences between images could arise, even if one image was derived from the other:

(a)     Some of the photographs in the cheating charges captured only a subset of the area captured by the alleged source radiograph. The Defence had raised this dissimilarity as yet another difference supporting the suggestion that the photographs were not derived from the alleged source radiographs.[note: 428] However, the Defence’s own expert conceded that the difference in size could simply have been be due to cropping of the image after it is taken[note: 429] −something which the Accused admitted had been done for some of the photographs.419

(b)     The Defence experts also explained that differences between photographs and the radiographs which they captured could arise from degradation of the radiograph film after the photograph is taken.[note: 430]

252    The Prosecution thus contends that the differences highlighted by the Defence as between the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs, or between these photographs and the alleged source radiograph, could be attributed either to reprographic errors or a host of other factors, and do not preclude the prospect of the photographs being forged from the alleged source radiograph.

253    The Defence complains that in relying on the phenomenon of reprographic errors, the Prosecution failed to call any forensic imaging expert. Instead, the Prosecution chose simply to rely on the Prosecution experts, who were qualified in dentistry rather than in the field of digital imaging.[note: 431] The Defence thus contends that the Prosecution experts “stepped outside the boundaries of their expertise” in using the phenomenon of reprographic errors to explain away the differences raised by the Defence experts.[note: 432] I find this objection to be without merit, for the reasons below.

(a)     At the threshold, one must recognise that the Prosecution had, from the outset, taken a targeted approach of focusing specifically on size and positioning of key anatomical features, as well as on unique fingerprints such as physical defects on the radiograph film and imaging artefacts. The multitude of dissimilarities in dots, lines, and other shapes, as well as the differences in brightness, definition and texture, was not something raised by the Prosecution. Rather, they were raised by the Defence, pursuant to its theory that these variations established that the photographs were not forged from the alleged source radiographs. An inseparable corollary of this theory must be that the differences are not reprographic errors −absent such a corollary, the endless litany of dots, lines and other shapes which the Defence tried to string together would fail to portray any semblance of coherence. Having raised this theory as the central plank undergirding his defence to the forgery charges, the Accused thus bore the evidential burden to establish it, including the necessary corollary that the differences were not merely the product of reprographic errors (something which even the Defence experts conceded does happen). To discharge that evidential burden, the Defence saw fit to rely only on the testimonies of the dental professionals that it called as expert witnesses, without calling any forensic imaging experts. The Defence thus has no cause to complain if the Prosecution enters the arena on those very same terms, relying on its own dental professionals to counter the Defence experts.

(b)     Furthermore, as alluded to above, much of the evidence elicited by the Prosecution on reprographic errors came from concessions made by the Defence experts on the stand. The fact that the Defence experts were not experts in imaging or photography did not stop them from agreeing that reprographic can and do occur. This is not surprising, given that any person who has ever used a digital device to capture, edit and print images would have some measure of familiarity with this area. In fact, apart from a general acceptance that reprographic errors happen, the Defence experts went on to agree that many of the specific differences in features and appearance that they had highlighted in their testimonies could have been generated by the process of capturing the image (with the camera) or printing it.[note: 433]

Given the above, I do not think that the Prosecution should be faulted for not calling a forensic imaging expert in this case.

254    Having considered the methodologies employed by the experts on both sides, I am of the opinion that the Defence’s methodology for comparing the images, which focuses heavily on dissimilarities in features (such as lines, dots and various other shapes) and differences in appearance (in terms of brightness, definition and texture), should be viewed with some circumspection. Even the Defence expert Dr Firdaus conceded, repeatedly, that the methodology of simply spotting the differences between the photographs in the forgery charges and the alleged source radiographs (which the photographs were alleged to have captured) is not suitable for determining if the former was derived from the latter.[note: 434] He conceded that the possibility of reprographic errors is a factor that must be accounted for when evaluating the differences between the images.[note: 435] I thus agree with the Prosecution that in assessing the differences in features and appearance between images, one must not lose sight of the prospect that a photograph of a radiograph can still reveal differences in features and appearance when compared with that radiograph, or when compared with another photograph of that same radiograph, despite all the images deriving from the same source, by virtue of the operation of reprographic errors.

255    The stark difference in methodologies adopted by both sides also feeds into a related point: The Defence recounts how the Prosecution expert, Dr Loh, had on multiple occasions professed that some of the photographs in the forgery charges were so blurry that he was in no position to engage in a meaningful comparison of the details that the Defence sought to draw his attention to. Specifically, the Defence highlights[note: 436] various instances where Defence Counsel asked Dr Loh to look at the photographs and compare details such as the texture within bone marrow spaces and bone trabeculae pattern,[note: 437] as well as the shapes of various amorphous patches.[note: 438] Dr Loh had responded that the photographs were too blurry to embark on a comparison of such fine features and, in any case, he disagreed that these features bore the differences which the Defence claimed to exist. The Defence complains about the seeming inconsistency for Dr Loh to dismiss the quality of the images as being too poor to afford an assessment, while at the same time rely on features within those very same images to conclude that the images are forged.[note: 439] However, this complaint ignores the critical distinguishing factor, being the methodology at play. Dr Loh’s responses simply meant that if one were to embark on the Defence’s approach of assessing whether all these fine details display material differences in appearance across the photographs, higher quality images will be required. That limitation is less operative on the methodology adopted by the Prosecution, which was much more targeted and focused on striking similarities in shape and positioning of anatomical structures, as well as the inexplicable replication of features that were clearly not part of the anatomical context. I thus see no contradiction in Dr Loh’s position.

Were the photographs forged?

256    Having canvassed my general views on the methodologies employed by the experts, I move on to the evidence in respect of each patient.

257    In the sections which follow, the image of each alleged source radiograph has been laid alongside the image(s) of the photograph(s) allegedly forged from that radiograph −all have been lined up as a set to facilitate comparison. The image sizes have also been adjusted, so that images within the same set are brought to the same scale, thereby controlling for any variations that might have arisen from differences in the zoom settings of the camera which took the photographs. For each set, a five-by-six grid has been overlaid over one of the images (mostly the alleged source radiograph) to facilitate pinpointing of specific features.

258    As the images reproduced in this judgment are inserted merely to aid in visualisation and pinpointing of specific features, they should not be taken as a substitute for the actual physical exhibits, especially given the risk that the process of reproducing the images into this judgment could have given rise to a further layer of reprographic errors. A proper evaluation of the features on the radiographs and photographs thus requires scrutinizing the actual physical exhibits themselves.

259    Throughout the analysis below, certain radiology-related terms will appear repeatedly. One of these is the term “radiopaque” (sometimes the term “radio opaque” was used in the trial), the antonym to which is the term “radiolucent”. Anatomical structures are radiopaque if they are resistant to the passing through of X-rays beams (eg, teeth and bones) and appear whiter on the radiograph. Anatomical parts which are more open to the passing through of X-ray beams are called radiolucent and appear darker on the radiograph. For those parts of the radiograph where there are no anatomical parts, meaning that the X-rays have passed through hollow space, these appear black on the radiograph. As such, when the experts testified as to a feature on the radiograph being more radiopaque (or “radio opaque”), they were saying that the feature appeared lighter. Conversely, when they testified that the feature was more radiolucent, they meant that the feature appeared darker.

The three photographs of Catherine Chia’s teeth: B35(1)-B35(3)

260    To recapitulate, the Accused faced a single cheating charge in respect of Catherine Chia.[note: 440] That charge alleged that he dishonestly submitted a Medisave claim declaring that he had performed FBR (at the tooth #33 area) and ABG (at the tooth #36 site) on Catherine Chia, when these procedures had not been performed. Following from this, the Prosecution’s case on the forgery charges in respect of Catherina Chia is that the Accused forged three photographs, B35(1)-(3), to deceive MoH auditors into thinking that the FBR and ABG procedures (which were the subject of the cheating charge) had been performed on Catherine Chia, when they had not.

261    Specifically, the Prosecution’s case is as follows:

(a)      B35(1) was an image of P3(1)A that had been:

(i)        altered to depict a white dot at tooth #33, to portray this as a foreign body in need of removal; and

(ii)       altered to depict a distinct socket at the tooth #36 site.

DAC 922428/2018 focused on the first alteration, charging the Accused with dishonestly altering B35(1) by adding the white dot.

(b)      B35(2) was also an image of P3(1)A and had been:

(i)       used to depict the absence of the white dot at tooth #33, to portray this as the aftermath of the FBR (with the foreign body now removed); and

(ii)        altered to depict a distinct socket still at the tooth #36 site.

DAC 922429/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B35(2) by making the tooth socket appear more distinct.

(c)      B35(3) was an image of P3(1)C that had been:

(i)       used to depict the absence of the socket at the tooth #36 site, to portray this as the aftermath of an ABG (with the socket now filled with graft material); and

(ii)        altered to depict white dots above the bone line at tooth #36, to portray this as graft material used in the ABG.

DAC 922430/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B35(3) by adding the white dots.

262    The table below reproduces the images of P3(1)A (with a grid overlaid for ease of navigation), B35(1) and B35(2):

263    The table below reproduces the images of P3(1)C (with a grid overlaid for ease of navigation) and B35(3):

(1)    B35(1) & B35(2): Both were images of P3(1)A

264    The first issue is whether the photographs B35(1) and B35(2) were images of P3(1)A.

265    The Prosecution experts testified that both photographs were images of P3(1)A. As regards the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures, Dr Loh cited the following similarities.

(a)     The shape of the filling at tooth #37 (at the top right corner of the images) looked the same in P3(1)A, B35(1) and B35(2). He found this remarkable, given that fillings are three-dimensional structures, making it difficult to capture them at an angle where the shape is the same across successive radiographs.[note: 441]

(b)     The positioning of the bite plate (the thin bar stretching horizontally across the top of the images) relative to the position of the teeth was the same in all the images.[note: 442]

(c)     The relative positioning of teeth #34 and #35 (at the spot corresponding to cell B2), as well as the size of the gap between these two teeth, were identical across the images.[note: 443]

266    As regards replication of physical features on the radiograph film, Dr Loh alluded to the indentation at the top left corner of P3(1)A (at the spot corresponding to cell A1). He opined that this could either be the “embossed dot” (an indentation added by the radiograph film manufacturer to allow users to tell which is the surface with the emulsion coating) or simply an indentation caused by the clip used to hold the film when the radiograph was being developed.[note: 444] Dr Loh said that this physical feature, which manifested itself as a white dot at the top left corner in the image of P3(1)A, was replicated in both B35(1) and B35(2), in the same shape and at the same position.[note: 445]

267    Based on these observations, Dr Loh concluded that B35(1) and B35(2) were identical, save for the white dot (corresponding to cell C1) alleged by the Prosecution to have been added to depict the foreign body purportedly removed.[note: 446] Dr Andrew Tay similarly opined that B35(1) and B35(2) were derived from P3(1)A, given the high degree of identicality between them.[note: 447]

268    The Defence experts canvassed the prospect that B35(1) and B35(2) were not derived from the same source radiograph but had instead captured two separate radiographs, with P3(1)A being yet another radiograph (meaning that there were three separate radiographs involved). While all three images may have looked similar, the Defence experts pointed to an array of dissimilarities in features and appearance, to support the Accused’s claim that these images arose from three separate shots of the patient’s mouth. These dissimilarities, as catalogued in the Defence submissions,[note: 448] are listed below.

(a)     Dr Leo Fung highlighted the differences between P3(1)(A) on the one hand, and B35(1) and B35(2) on the other:

(i)       The image of tooth #37 in P3(1)A was “amorphous” when compared with that in B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 449]

(ii)       There was a black horizonal line at the root of tooth #33 in P3(1)A (near the top edge of cell D1), that was not in B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 450]

(iii)       There was a black cavity shaped like a thin long scoop at the mesial portion of tooth #34 in P3(1)A (cutting diagonally across the boundary dividing cells B1 and B2), but not in B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 451]

(iv)       There was a fine white dot at the top left corner of P3(1)A (at cell A1), but not in B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 452]

(v)       There was a black semi-circular image, indicative of a cavity, on the top left of tooth #34 in P3(1)A (at cell B1), that was not visible in B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 453]

(b)     Dr Leo Fung also highlighted the differences when B35(1) and B35(2) were compared with each other:

(i)       There was a white patch at the neck of tooth #35 in B35(1), but not in B35(2)[note: 454] (this “patch” referred to the white dot that the Prosecution alleged had been added to depict the foreign body purportedly removed).

(ii)       The bottom left portion of the restoration on tooth #37 (corresponding to the bottom portion of cell B5) “appears sharper” in B35(2) than in B35(1).[note: 455]

(iii)       There was a circular dot in the triangular area of bone between teeth #34 and #35 (corresponding to cell C2) in B35(2), but not B35(1).[note: 456]

(c)     As for Dr Alfred Lau, he highlighted the differences between P3(1)A and B35(1):

(i)       The “enamel pattern” at teeth #34 and #35 looked different, as between P3(1)A (at cells B1 and B2) and B35(1).[note: 457]

(ii)       There were dark streaks at tooth #37 in P3(1)A (at cells B6 and C6) that were not visible in B35(1).[note: 458]

(iii)       There were white patches at the root of tooth #34 in P3(1)A (at cell D2) but not B35(1).[note: 459]

(iv)       There was a white dot on the upper left corner of B35(1) that was not visible at the corresponding spot in P3(1)A (at cell A1).[note: 460]

(v)       There were white patches at tooth #35 in B35(1) which were not visible in P3(1)A (at cell B3).[note: 461]

(d)     Dr Alfred Lau also highlighted the differences when B35(1) and B35(2) were compared with each other:

(i)       The mesial edge of the amalgam at tooth #37 (corresponding to the bottom portion of cell B5) had more “overhang” in B35(1), as compared to B35(2).[note: 462]

(ii)       The pulpal content at tooth #37 (corresponding to cell B6) had more “distinct radiopacity” in B35(1), as compared to B35(2).[note: 463]

(iii)       The distal root of the tooth #36 socket (corresponding to cells C5 and D5) was narrower in B35(1) compared to B35(2).[note: 464]

(iv)       There was a “distinct enamel pattern” at tooth #35 (corresponding to the upper parts of cells B2 and B3) which looked different, as between B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 465]

(v)       There were white patches at tooth #35 in B35(1) (corresponding to the bottom half of cell B3) but not B35(2).[note: 466]

(e)     Similarly, Dr Firdaus highlighted the differences between P3(1)A on the one hand, and B35(1) and B35(2) on the other:

(i)       There was a radiopaque dot at the top left-hand corner of B35(1) and B35(2) that was not visible at the corresponding location in P3(1)A (at cell A1).[note: 467]

(ii)       There was a “stark contrast” in the quality of the image of teeth #34 and #35, as between P3(1)A and B35(1).[note: 468]

(iii)       The restoration at tooth #37 was more radiolucent in P3(1)A, thus allowing shadows and black lines in the tooth to be observed, while the same feature in B35(1) had a radiopacity that was “more solid and dense”.[note: 469]

(iv)       There was a black area of radiolucency in the middle of tooth #37 in P3(1)A that was not in B35(2).[note: 470]

(v)       The lamina dura[note: 471] and surrounding bone at the root tip of tooth #35 had a more “significant outline” in P3(1)A (at cell D3), but this was not clear in B35(2).[note: 472]

269    Having assessed the evidence above, I conclude that both B35(1) and 35(2) were images of P3(1)A.

270    Firstly, I accept the observation of Dr Loh that the shape and angulation of the anatomical structures were the same across all three images. The shape of the restoration at tooth #37, the shape of the bite plate and its positioning vis-à-vis the teeth, as well as the shape, size and positioning of the gap between teeth #36 and #37, are the same. Given the array of variables at play impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam, set out at paragraph 242(a) above, it would have been difficult to achieve these similarities across two different shots, let alone three. These similarities thus give rise to an inference that B35(1) and B35(2) were both photographs of P3(1)A.

271    There were some instances when the Defence experts purported to highlight what might conceivably be considered as differences in shape or positioning of anatomical features. For example, they suggested that the bottom left edge of the restoration of tooth #37 (at cell B5) appeared (in the words of Dr Leo Fung) “sharper” or (in the words of Dr Lau) had more “overhang”. However, having examined the physical exhibits, I could not see any difference. Dr Alfred Lau also suggested that the distal root of the tooth #36 socket was “narrower” in B35(1) than in B35(2). However, when I examined the exhibits, I could not detect any difference in thickness between the images. As for the dots, lines and other shapes highlighted by the Defence experts, the prospect of these dissimilarities having arisen from reprographic errors during the capture or printing of the image could not be ruled out.

272    I have also considered if any physical features on the surface of P3(1)A were transposed to B35(1) and B35(2). As explained above, Dr Loh referred to the indentation at the top left corner of P3(1)A (at the spot corresponding to cell A1), which he surmised could have been the “embossed dot” added by the manufacturer. He suggested that this embossed dot had been transposed to B35(1) and B35(2), in the form of the white dot at the top left corner of both images. This white dot was in turn situated within a slightly larger grey patch in B35(1) and B35(2). However, my physical examination of P3(1)A showed that the embossed dot therein was not, as suggested by Dr Loh, transposed onto B35(1) and B35(2). Ie, the white dot on B35(1) and B35(2) was not the embossed dot on P3(1)A. Within B35(1) and B35(2), the white dot was situated slightly to the left of centre within the grey patch, while the embossed dot on P3(1)A would, if transposed to B35(1) and B35(2), have been situated more towards the right edge of the grey patch. I thus disagree with Dr Loh on this point. Even if B35(1) and B35(2) had been derived from P3(1)A, the embossed dot on P3(1)A was not one of the features that had been transposed to B35(1) and B35(2). What is more noteworthy is not the white dot within the grey patch (which I have found not to be the embossed dot) but the grey patch itself:

(a)     The grey patch represents a feature that has been replicated in both B35(1) and B35(2). Dr Leo Fung, agreed that the grey patch had the same shape and occupied the same location (corresponding to the upper half of the boundary line dividing cells A1 and A2) in both B35(1) and B35(2).[note: 473] He initially tried to explain this similarity by saying that both radiograph films could have been clipped together, at the same corner, when being dipped in the developing solution.[note: 474] However, this is an unlikely explanation. Firstly, it this would require the person developing the radiograph film to coincidentally pick the exact same corner and the same side of both films to apply the clip. Secondly, both B35(1) and B35(2) were meant to depict Catherine Chia’s mouth ‘before’ and ‘after’ the purported procedure −Dr Leo Fung agreed that this meant that the underlying radiographs would have been developed one after the other, and not together,[note: 475] thereby precluding the prospect of both radiographs being clipped together when being developed. That being the case, it is inexplicable that the grey patch should be replicated in both B35(1) and B35(2) −in the same shape and at the very same spot vis-à-vis the anatomical structures. This was highly coincidental if both photographs had indeed captured different source radiographs.

(b)     More importantly, the grey patch also represents a physical feature on the surface of P3(1)A that was replicated in both B35(1) and B35(2). On physically examining P3(1)A, one sees that the location on P3(1)A corresponding to the grey patch is an area where the emulsion had layer peeled off. This “peeled-off area” was not clearly captured in the image of P3(1)A reproduced in this judgment above, but a physical examination[note: 476] of P3(1)A yields a better view of the peeled-off area’s shape and location. The Prosecution’s case is that the peeled-off area in P3(1)A corresponded to the grey patch in B35(1) and B35(2), although Dr Leo Fung disagreed.[note: 477] Upon physically examining the surface of P3(1)A, I agree with the Prosecution. The peeled-off area at the top left of P3(1)A was clearly transposed to B35(1) and B35(2), in the form of the grey patch, which was sited at same spot as the peeled-off area. On a related point, while the Defence experts testified that the white dot within the grey patch in B35(1) and B35(2) could not be seen in P3(1)A (see paragraph 268(a)(iv), 268(c)(iv) and 268(e)(i) above), a close scrutiny of the image of P3(1)A shows that the white dot is present at the same corresponding spot, albeit fainter.

These indicators thus point me to the conclusion that the peeled-off area in P3(1)A was replicated in both B35(1) and B35(2). There is no explanation for this, if both these photographs were indeed images of two other radiographs.

273    I am thus satisfied that both B35(1) and B35(2) were images of P3(1)A. However, this does not dispose of the analysis. To address the allegations in the forgery charges, I must also assess the following:

(a)     In respect of B35(1), whether the white dot (at tooth #33) was added to depict the foreign body that was purportedly removed.

(b)     In respect of B35(2), whether the tooth #36 socket was made to look more distinct.

274    I canvass each of these questions below.

(2)    B35(1): White dot was added

275    As a preliminary step, I rule out the possibility that the white dot was actually a foreign body which the Accused removed. As explained above, when finding the Accused guilty of the cheating charge in respect of Catherine Chia, I was satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that FBR had not been performed on her. The question thus arises as to how the white dot came to appear in B35(1). Dr Loh was of the view that the white dot was inserted into the radiograph.[note: 478]

276    I agree with the Prosecution that the white dot was added to B35(2). The white dot was conspicuously absent from P3(1)A, despite this being the source radiograph from which B35(1) was derived. The white dot in B35(1) was also prominently situated at tooth #33, ie, the very tooth where the FBR purportedly took place. Given that B35(1) was submitted to MoH auditors together with B35(1) (where the white dot was absent) to show that FBR had occurred at tooth #33, both photographs were clearly meant to portray Catherine Chia’s mouth ‘before’ and ‘after’ the FBR at tooth #33. This is reinforced by the Accused’s Long Statement, where he stated that the photographs B35(1) and B35(2) showed “Removal of foreign body at tooth #33”.[note: 479]

277    I am thus satisfied that B35(1) was an image of P3(1)A that had been altered by the addition of the white dot at the tooth #33 site.

(3)    B35(2): Was the tooth socket made to look more distinct?

278    The Prosecution’s case is that the tooth #36 socket in B35(2) was altered to look more distinct so that, when contrasted with B35(3) (examined further below) where the socket was clearly absent and there were white dots purportedly depicting bone graft granules above the bone line, both images would collectively convey the impression that ABG had been performed.

279    The Prosecution experts explained that the socket at B35(2) must have been added because it looked unnatural. This could be discerned from the “lamina dura”, which is the thin layer of bone surrounding the tooth root. The Prosecution experts explained that immediately after a tooth is extracted, the lamina dura of the socket (left by the extracted tooth) looks much more distinct, with a clear white outline surrounding the socket.[note: 480] As the socket heals with time, growth of bone into the socket breaks the outline. The lamina dura thus grows increasingly indistinct with time. In the case of B35(2), the image purported to capture a radiograph shot on 14 April 2014, ie, about four months after the tooth was extracted.[note: 481] With the lapse of such a significant duration, the socket’s outline ought to have been much more indistinct, due to ingrowth of bone.[note: 482] It would have looked something like the socket in P3(1)A, which appeared much more natural.[note: 483] It would not appear as distinct as the socket in B35(2), which looked more like a freshly extracted socket.[note: 484]

280    I harbour some doubts about the Prosecution experts’ opinions in this regard, which I think would be safer resolved in the Accused’s favour. Firstly, I observe that the shape of the socket in B35(2) was the same as that in P3(1)A (which the Prosecution agreed had not been tampered with). In terms of shape and positioning, the socket in B35(2) does not appear to have been altered in any way. The only difference is that P3(1)A had much more white shading running across the socket −this was absent in B35(2), thus giving the appearance that the latter’s socket was “more distinct”. However, the Prosecution did not explain why this difference in shading could not have arisen from reprographic errors and necessarily had to be caused by image manipulation instead. The Prosecution has leaned heavily on the phenomenon of reprographic errors to discount minor differences in appearance between the images −surely the sauce for the goose must be good for the gander. The Prosecution ought to have adduced some evidence to show me that the relative dearth of white shading over the socket in B35(2) could not have resulted from the process of capture or printing of the image.

281    As such, while I am satisfied that B35(2) was an image of P3A(1), I am not sufficiently convinced that B35(2) had been altered to make the tooth socket look more distinct. The Prosecution has failed to prove beyond reasonable doubt that the photograph in B35(2) was forged. I thus acquit the Accused of the forgery charge in DAC 922429/2018.

(4)    B35(3): Was this image forged?

282    To show that B35(3) was forged, the Prosecution sought to establish that this photograph was:

(a)     an image of P3(1)C and:

(b)      altered to add the white dots above the bone line (at tooth #36), to portray this as graft material used in the ABG.

283    As regards the first aspect, the Prosecution experts were of the view that the B35(3) was an image of P3(1)C. Dr Andrew Tay concluded that B35(3) was a photograph of P3(1)C, given the similarities in the general shape and angulation of the teeth, as well as the fact that the brown discolouration at the crown of tooth #37 appeared in both images. He also pointed to a coiled tubular object which appeared on the right edge of tooth #37 in P3(1)C, observing that the tip of that coiled tube also appeared in B35(3), just above the bone line at the right edge of the photograph.[note: 485] As for Dr Loh, he similarly referred to the coiled tubular object, which he suspected to be gutta-percha,[note: 486] in P3(1)C. He observed that its tip could also be seen at the right edge of B37(3), where the photograph had been cropped.[note: 487] He also referred to a dot at the top right portion of the tooth #35 crown, immediately to the left of the bite plate’s left edge. He observed that the dot was situated at the same spot in both P3(1)C (at the left side of cell A2) and B35(3).[note: 488] Dr Loh thus concluded that B35(3) and P3(1)C were the same image.[note: 489]

284    The Defence experts, on their part, canvassed the prospect that B35(3) was not derived from the P3(1)C but was a photograph of a separate radiograph. The Defence experts pointed to an array of dissimilarities in features and appearance, in support of the Accused’s claim that both images arose from two separate shots of the patient’s mouth. These dissimilarities have been catalogued in the Defence submissions[note: 490] but I do not propose to list them here.

285    The Prosecution further contends that B35(3) was altered by the addition of white dots above the bone line at tooth #36, to depict bone graft granules in the aftermath of the purported ABG procedure. As support for the contention that the white dots were added, the Prosecution highlights how the dots were depicted as floating over the bone line. This, argues the Prosecution, was unnatural and went against the evidence of Dr Loh as to how a graft site should look post-ABG. Dr Loh testified that bone granules at a graft site are packed in a heap, with the gum flap being tightly stitched over the heap, firmly pressing the granules downwards. The granules would thus be seen as densely pressed together and not, as depicted in B35(3), floating above the bone line.[note: 491] Dr Loh had never seen such floating granules in the wake of an ABG.[note: 492]

286    In my view, the evidence is insufficient to satisfy me beyond reasonable doubt that B35(3) was forged.

287    Firstly, I am not sufficiently convinced that B35(3) is an image of P3(1)C. While the Prosecution experts pointed to some similarities in the features (such as the dot at the crown of tooth #37 and the location of the gutta-percha), the number of reference points within both images are far fewer than those in B35(1) and B35(2), and thus fail to provide me with sufficient comfort to affirmatively conclude that the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures in both images are the same. This is in part attributable to the fact that the area captured in B37(3) is smaller than P3(1)C, thereby decreasing the points of commonality which could be mapped to each other. For example, because the gutta-percha was cropped off, I am unable to fully compare if this object had indeed been reproduced in B37(3) with sufficient similarity in terms of shape and positioning. As for the brown patch relied on by Dr Andrew Tay, I note that this was shaped differently in both images and thus not something that the Prosecution could really claim to support its case. Finally, unlike in the case of B35(1) and B35(2), there are no physical defects or other imaging artefacts in P3(1)(C) which I can see being replicated in B35(3).

288    As for the Prosecution’s contention that the white dots above the bone line (at tooth #36) were added, I also found the Prosecution’s expert evidence to be somewhat equivocal. Dr Loh testified that in his many years of experience, he never saw bone granules floating above the bone line in the wake of an ABG, as depicted in B35(3), because the granules would have been tightly packed downwards when the gum flap is firmly stitched in place.492 However, as the Defence rightly points out,[note: 493] the other Prosecution expert (Dr Andrew Tay) was willing to accept the possibility that bone graft granules may on occasion be viewed in the radiograph as floating above the bone line.[note: 494] This possibility was also corroborated by the Defence expert, Dr Alfred Lau, who testified that bone graft granules may be seen floating above the bone line post-ABG if the granules had been trapped in the gum or soft tissue.[note: 495] Specifically, bone granules may be packed into the graft site and held in place with a resorbable membrane,[note: 496] with the gum flaps stitched over the membrane (which in turn holds the granules in place under it). Any stray bone granules that happen to lie on top of the membrane when the gum flaps are folded over and stitched down may appear in the radiograph as floating, as they would be held above the bone line by the membrane, despite being tucked under the gum.[note: 497] I am thus unable to rule out the possibility that bone granules may be appear in a radiograph as floating over the bone line, after an ABG.

289    Finally, my doubts about the forgery allegations relating to B37(3) are compounded by the fact that the Prosecution failed to establish beyond reasonable doubt that ABG was not performed on Catherine Chia, on 14 April 2014. That is why I amended the cheating charge in DAC 922412/2018 to remove the reference to ABG not having been done.

290    As such, I am neither convinced that B35(3) is an image of P3(1)C nor sufficiently satisfied that the white dots above the bone line (at tooth #36) in B35(3) were added. The Prosecution has failed to prove beyond reasonable doubt that the photograph in B35(3) was forged. I thus acquit the Accused of the forgery charge in DAC 922430/2018.

The four photographs of Chong Moh Chin’s teeth: B36(1)-(4)

291    To recapitulate, the Accused faced a single cheating charge in respect of Chong Moh Chin.[note: 498] That charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly submitted a Medisave claim declaring that he had performed FBR (at the tooth #16 area) and ABG (at the tooth #36 site) on Chong Moh Chin, when both these procedures had not been performed. Following from this, the Prosecution’s case on the forgery charges in respect of Chong Moh Chin is that the Accused forged four photographs, B36(1)-(4), to deceive MoH auditors into thinking that the FBR and ABG procedures (which were the subject of the cheating charge) had been performed on Chong Moh Chin, when they had not.

292    In respect of the FBR procedure, the Prosecution’s case is as follows.

(a)      B36(1) was an image of P3(2)A that had been:

(i)        altered to depict a white dot next to tooth #16, to portray this as a foreign body in need of removal; and

(ii)       altered to depict the false date “9-4-14” (ie, 9 April 2014, being the date that the FBR was purportedly performed on Chong Moh Chin).

DAC 922431/2018 focused on the first alteration, charging the Accused with dishonestly altering B36(1) by adding the white dot.

(b)      B36(2) was also an image of P3(2)A and had been:

(i)        altered to depict the same false date, “9-4-14” (ie, 9 April 2014); and

(ii)       used to depict the absence of the white dot next to tooth #16, thereby portraying this as the aftermath of the FBR (with the foreign body now removed).

DAC 922432/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B36(2) by labelling it with the date 9 April 2014 −this date being false because the source radiograph captured by B36(2) (ie, P3(2)A) was actually shot in the year 2007.

The table below reproduces the images of P3(2)A (with a grid overlaid for ease of navigation), B36(1) and B36(2):

293    In respect of the ABG procedure, the Prosecution’s case is as follows:

(a)      B36(3) was an image of P3(2)C that had been altered to depict a distinct socket at the tooth #36 site.

DAC 922433/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B36(3) by making the tooth socket appear more distinct.

(b)      B36(4) was also an image of P3(2)C and had been:

(i)       used to depict the absence of the socket at the tooth #36 site, thereby portraying this as the aftermath of an ABG (with the socket now filled with graft material); and

(ii)        altered to depict white dots above the bone line at tooth #36, thereby portraying this as graft material used in the ABG.

DAC 922434/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B36(4) by adding the white dots.

The table below reproduces the images of P3(2)C (with a grid overlaid for ease of navigation), B36(3) and B36(4):

(1)    B36(1) & B36(2): Both were images of P3(2)A

294    The first issue is whether the photographs B36(1) and B36(2) were images of P3(2)A.

295    The Prosecution experts opined that both photographs were images of P3(2)A:

(a)     Dr Loh pointed to the area of overlap between teeth #16 and #17 (at the extreme left end of the cell D3). He noted the similarity in the degree of overlap and shape of the overlapping area, commenting that the “inevitable conclusion” was that the images were the same.[note: 499] As for Dr Andrew Tay, he too found the angulation, shape and orientation of the anatomical structures in the image to be identical.[note: 500]

(b)     Dr Loh also looked at the curved white structure above the apices of teeth #16 and #17 (traversing cells A1, B2 and B3). This was called the zygoma and was part of the cheekbone.[note: 501] Dr Loh explained that when an X-ray is taken, the zygoma may be superimposed at various locations −sometime above, sometimes below and sometimes at the apices of the teeth roots.[note: 502] Yet, in all three images here, the zygoma was reproduced in the same shape and juxtaposed at the exact same location vis-à-vis the apices of the roots of teeth #16 and #17. Dr Loh opined that taking successive radiographs with such similarity in the shape and positioning of the zygoma was “nearly impossible”.[note: 503] Likewise, Dr Andrew Tay also found the location of the zygoma to be identical across the images.[note: 504]

(c)     Dr Loh also observed that the white dot at the bottom left corner of the image (corresponding to cell E1) was replicated in all three images.[note: 505] Similarly, Dr Andrew Tay focused on this dot, observing that it was found across all three images, at roughly the same area. [note: 506]

Dr Loh thus took the view that P3(2)A, B36(1) and B36(2) were the same image.[note: 507] Dr Andrew Tay was similarly of the view that both B36(1) and B36(2) were derived from P3(2)A.[note: 508] He opined that the images were “identical” (save for the purported foreign body next to tooth #16),[note: 509] commenting that it was statistically impossible” to capture two successive radiograph images with this degree of similarity.[note: 510]

296    The Defence experts canvassed the prospect that B36(1) and B36(2) were not derived from the same source radiograph but had instead captured two separate radiographs, with P3(2)A being a third separate radiograph. While all three images may have looked similar, the Defence experts pointed to an array of dissimilarities in features and appearance, to support the Accused’s claim that these images arose from three separate shots of the patient’s mouth. The dissimilarities, as catalogued in the Defence submissions,[note: 511] are listed below.

(a)     Dr Leo Fung highlighted the differences between P3(2)A on the one hand, and B36(1) and B36(2) on the other:

(i)       There was a white dot at the centre of the sinus that was visible in P3(2)A (at cell A2) but not B36(1) and B36(2).[note: 512]

(ii)       The shape of the root at tooth #15 and the white line running above it in P3(2)A (see the diagonal white line in cell B4) were “very distinct and clear” when compared with B36(1) and B36(2).[note: 513]

(b)     Dr Leo Fung also highlighted the differences when B35(1) and B35(2) were compared with each other:

(i)       There was a white dot at the distal area of tooth #17 in B36(1) (corresponding to the top end of the boundary line dividing cells D1 and D2) that was not visible in B36(2).[note: 514]

(ii)       There was a white dot at the base of the sinus above tooth #17 in B36(1) (corresponding to cell A2) that was not visible in B36(2).[note: 515]

(c)     As for Dr Alfred Lau, he highlighted the differences between P3(2)A and B36(1):

(i)       There was a dark spot at the top left corner in P3(2)A (at top left corner of cell A2) that was not visible in B36(1).[note: 516]

(ii)       There was a white spot inside the sinus area in P3(2)A (at cell A2) that was not visible in B36(1).[note: 517]

(iii)       The bone marrow pattern between teeth #16 and #17 showed a “difference”, as between P3(2)A (at the upper left corner of cell C3) and B36(1).[note: 518]

(iv)       There was a white dot visible at the root of tooth #16 in B36(1) that was not visible at the corresponding location in P3(2)A (at cell C4)[note: 519] (this was the dot that the Prosecution claimed was added to depict a foreign body).

(v)       There was a white dot at the distal area of tooth #17 in B36(1) that was not seen in P3(2)A (The Defence submissions appear to be wrong in highlighting this feature as a “white dot”. According to the Transcripts, when Dr Lau referred to the distal area of tooth #17, he was referencing the bone marrow pattern and not a white dot. He observed that the bone marrow pattern in P3(2)A, at cell B1, was “different” when compared with that in B36(1), although he was “not able to describe it in words”[note: 520]).

(vi)       There was a white dot between teeth #16 and #15 in B36(1) that was not visible in P3(2)A (Again, the Defence submissions appear to be wrong in highlighting this feature as a “white dot”. According to the Transcripts, when Dr Alfred Lau referred to the location between teeth #16 and #15, he was referencing the interdental space and not the white dot. He observed that the interdental space in P3(2)A, at cell D4, appeared wider as compared to that in B36(1)[note: 521]).

(d)     Dr Alfred Lau also highlighted the differences when B35(1) and B35(2) were compared with each other:

(i)       There was a white dot at tooth #17 in B36(1) (corresponding to the bottom left corner of cell A2) that was not visible in B36(2).[note: 522]

(ii)       There was a white dot at the distal area of tooth #17 in B36(1) (corresponding to the top end of the boundary line dividing cells D1 and D2) that was not seen in B36(2).[note: 523]

(iii)       The bone pattern near the apex of tooth #17 in B36(1) (corresponding to the top right portion of cell B2) was “different in shape” when compared with B36(2).[note: 524]

(iv)       There was a white dot at the lower right corner of the image in B36(1) (corresponding to the bottom end of the boundary line dividing cells E5 and E6) that was not visible in B36(2).[note: 525]

(e)     Similarly, Dr Firdaus highlighted the differences between P3(2)A on the one hand, and B36(1) and B36(2) on the other:

(i)       There was a white dot at the bottom left corner of P3(2)A (at cell E1) which looked different when compared with B36(1), where the corresponding object looked more like a “radio opaque circle”,[note: 526] or with B36(2), where the corresponding object took the form of a white dot that was “slightly different in shape and position”.[note: 527]

(ii)       There was a white dot at the top right of B36(1) that was not visible in the corresponding location in P3(2)A (The Defence submissions appear to be wrong in highlighting the white dot as being at the top “right”. According to the Transcripts, when Dr Firdaus cited the white dot at the top of B36(1), he was referencing the top left of the image, corresponding to cell A2[note: 528]).

(iii)       There was a small white dot at the distal area of tooth #17 in B36(1) (corresponding to the top end of the boundary line dividing cells D1 and D2) that was not visible in P3(2)A.[note: 529]

(iv)       The floor of the maxillary sinus in B36(1) was “broad and highly dense” when compared with the corresponding white line in P3(2)A (at cells B2 and B3).[note: 530]

(v)       When tooth #15 in P3(2)A was compared with the corresponding tooth in B36(1) and B36(2), the tooth in B36(1) bore a “more radio opaque” root but “less significant” canal outline,[note: 531] while the same tooth in B36(2) similarly had a “more radio opaque” appearance and “less well-defined” lamina dura.[note: 532]

(vi)       The interdental bony region between teeth #16 and #17 in B36(2) was “less significant” when compared with the corresponding region in P3(2)A (corresponding to the upper portion of cell C3).[note: 533]

297    Having assessed the evidence above, I conclude that both B36(1) and 36(2) were images of P3(2)A.

298    I begin with the size and positioning of the anatomical features. In this respect, I agree with the Prosecution experts that (a) the size and shape of the overlap between teeth #16 and #17; and (b) the shape and positioning of the zygoma above both these teeth, were the same across all three images. Even the Defence expert, Dr Firdaus, agreed that the positioning of the zygoma was “identical”.[note: 534] Given the many variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam, canvassed at paragraph 242(a) above, I agree that it would have been unlikely for such three dimensional anatomical structures to be juxtaposed against one another with such striking similarity, as regards the shape and positioning of the overlapping areas, across not just two but three successive shots. These similarities lent themselves to a strong inference that B36(1) and B36(2) were photographs of P3(2)A.

299    There were some instances when the Defence experts purported to highlight what might be considered as differences in shape or angulation. For example, Dr Alfred Lau suggested that the interdental space between teeth #16 and #15 appeared wider in P3(2)A than in in B36(1). However, on examining the physical exhibits, I do not detect any difference in width. As for the array of dots, lines and other shapes raised by the Defence experts, I am unable to rule out the prospect that these dissimilarities arose from reprographic errors during the image capture and printing process. For some of these features, the Defence experts were not even able to articulate the alleged difference with any degree of precision. For example, when Dr Alfred Lau said that the bone marrow pattern between teeth #16 and #17 looked “different”, he did not explain how this was so.

300    In terms of replication of features that were not part of the anatomical context, I note that there was an embossed dot at the top left corner on P3A(1) (at the top left corner of cell A2) that was not replicated in B36(1) or B36(2). However, this was simply because the latter two images appeared to have been cropped at the top. This means that even if both these photographs were images of P3(2)A, the cropping of the section where the embossed dot would have been situated meant that there was no way to tell if the embossed dot in P3(2)A had been replicated in the two photographs.

301    However, there was a particularly noteworthy non-anatomical feature which served as a unique identifying fingerprint. This was the dot at the bottom left corner of the image (corresponding to the cell E1). A physical examination of the radiograph film P3(2) shows that this dot was not due to a physical indentation on the film itself.[note: 535] The dot was also not part of the patient’s anatomy, given how it was situated in the black space of the oral cavity. The dot was thus an artefact[note: 536] −something which was not part of the anatomical context that was nevertheless captured in the radiographic image. This artefact was unique because it bore the same ‘C’ shape and was juxtaposed at the same location across all three images. During examination-in-chief, the Defence expert Dr Firdaus initially said that the shape and location of the artefact varied slightly across the images, looking more like a “radio opaque circle” in B36(1)526 and more like a white dot that was “slightly different in shape and position” in B36(2).527 I do not agree with this observation. A close examination of the physical exhibits shows that the artefact clearly bore the same unique ‘C’ shape across all three images. While the artefact looked slightly blurrier in the image of P3(2)A, possibly because of reprographic errors, it was still distinctly ‘C’-shaped. Furthermore, I also assess that its position (using #17 as the anchoring point of reference) to be the same across all three images. Upon further probing in cross-examination, Dr Firdaus conceded that:

(a)     the artefact did bear the same ‘C’ shape[note: 537] across all three images, with any slight differences in shape possibly being attributable to reprographic errors;[note: 538] and

(b)     the artefact was located at the same unique spot across all three images, factoring in the prospect of any reprographic errors and differences in scale.[note: 539]

302    While features of a patient’s anatomical structure may on occasion be replicated across successive radiographs with some similarity in same shape and location, the same cannot be said for an artefact such as the ‘C’-shaped dot. Such artefacts, which having no relation to the patient’s anatomy, would be random. One would thus be hard put to find any explanation for them appearing in different radiographs in the same shape and at the same location. Under cross-examination, Dr Firdaus agreed that the possibility of such an artefact appearing in the same shape and location on two different radiographs would be almost non-existent.[note: 540] The presence of this feature thus gave him a “high index of suspicion” that B36(1) and B36(2) were derived from P3(2)A.[note: 541]

303    I am thus satisfied that both B36(1) and B36(2) were images of P3(1)A. Still, this does not dispose of the analysis. To address the allegations in the forgery charges, I must assess the following:

(a)     In respect of B36(1), whether the white dot (next to tooth #16) was added to depict the foreign body that had purportedly been removed.

(b)     In respect of B36(2), whether the photograph was altered by the addition of a label bearing a false date (ie, “9-4-14”).

304    I deal with each of these questions below.

(2)    B36(1): White dot was added

305    I first rule out the possibility that the white dot next to tooth #16 in B36(1) was actually a foreign body which the Accused removed. As explained above, when finding the Accused guilty of the cheating charge in respect of Chong Moh Chin, I was satisfied that no foreign body was removed from the tooth #16 area. This leads to the question as to how the white dot came to appear in B36(1). Dr Loh was of the view that this white dot was added, whether intentionally or inadvertently.[note: 542] Dr Andrew Tay similarly took the view that it was added.[note: 543]

306    I agree with the Prosecution experts that the white dot was added to B36(1). The white dot was conspicuously absent from P3(2)A, notwithstanding this being the source radiograph from which B36(1) was derived. The white dot was also prominently situated next to #16, ie, the very tooth where the FBR purportedly took place. Given that B36(1) was submitted to MoH auditors together with B36(2) (where the white dot was absent) to show that FBR had taken place at tooth #16, both photographs were clearly meant to portray Chong Moh Chin’s mouth ‘before’ and ‘after’ the FBR at tooth #16. This is buttressed by the Accused’s Long Statement, where he stated that the photographs B36(1) and B36(2) showed “Removal of foreign body at tooth #16”.[note: 544]

307    I am thus satisfied that B36(1) was an image of P3(2)A that had been altered by the addition of the white dot at the site where FBR was purportedly performed (next to tooth #16).

(3)    B36(2): Was the date on the label false?

308    All the photographs in the forgery charges had been edited with photo-editing software to overlay a label above the image. The label contained the patient’s name, the date the procedure was performed on the patient, and the number of the tooth (depicted in the image) on which the procedure was performed. In the case of B36(1) and B36(2), the date on the label was “9-4-14” (ie, 9 April 2014).

309    The Prosecution’s case is that the source radiograph captured by B36(1) and B36(2) was P3(2)A, which was shot on 22 November 2007, ie, over 6½ years prior to 9 April 2014. The 9 April 2014 was thus false and had been inserted by the Accused into B36(1) and B36(2) to give the impression that the underlying radiographs were shot on the date that the Accused purportedly performed the ABG and FBR on Chong Moh Chin. To recapitulate, I had convicted the Accused on the cheating charge in DAC 922413/2018 as I found that neither procedure had been performed on Chong Moh Chin on 9 April 2014.

310    It is necessary to give some background to the provenance of P3(2)A. As explained at paragraph 235 above, during the raid on the Accused’s clinic, the police found radiographs of patients stored in small Ziplock sachets that were stapled to the patient cards.[note: 545] The Investigation officer, Beverly Seetoh (PW14) (“IO Beverly”), testified that each Ziplock sachet attached to the patient card enclosed only one radiograph[note: 546] plus a small piece of paper. The date on which the radiograph was taken (plus the patient’s name and the number of the tooth captured by the radiograph) was handwritten on that piece of paper. The police had seized the patient cards of various patients.
