For purposes of the trial, the Prosecution removed the radiographs from the Ziplock sachets that were stapled to the seized patient cards and inserted each radiograph into a fresh Ziplock sachet −these included the alleged source radiographs such as P3(1)A, P3(1)C and P3(2)A. The fresh Ziplock sachets containing the radiographs were then collated and stapled to P3. The Prosecution also reproduced the handwritten details captured by the small pieces of paper by typing these out on fresh squares of paper which were then slotted together with each corresponding radiograph, within the Ziplock sachets stapled to P3.[note: 547]

311    In respect of P3(2)A, the handwritten square of paper that was seized (and hence the typewritten square of paper accompanying the radiograph now attached to P3) bore the date “22/11/2017”. The Prosecution’s case is that this shows that P3(2)A was shot on 22 November 2017. The 9 April 2014 date on B36(1) and B36(2) was thus false.

312    I find the Prosecution’s case on this to be sketchy. No evidence was called on the practice of the clinic in cataloguing patient radiographs. It was not clear which of the staff were responsible for inserting the handwritten pieces of paper containing the date of the radiograph and, more importantly, the processes in place governing what is scribbled on the pieces of paper which go into the Ziplock sachets. I could not find anything on this in the Accused’s statement. While there did not appear to be any explicit dispute by the Defence about whether the date on the piece of paper in the Ziplock sachet containing P3(2)A correctly captured the date of the radiograph, this was an instance where the burden of proof lay squarely on the Prosecution. It was for the Prosecution to show that the actual date of P3(2)A was something other than 9 April 2014, since this formed the very gravamen of the charge in DAC 922432/2018. Unfortunately, the Prosecution did not adduce any evidence on how the Accused’s clinic dated patient radiographs. The Prosecution’s written submissions also do not allude to why the date on the handwritten piece of paper should be treated as the correct date. Additionally, while I appreciate that the Prosecution might have been trying to facilitate the convenience of the court by replacing the handwritten pieces of paper with something that was nicely typed out, they should have at least adduced the original handwritten pieces of paper, as that was the original evidence establishing what the Prosecution now claims to be the correct date of the radiograph. This was not done. I had to glean what the handwritten note looks like from the black and white photocopy of the patient card at the first page of exhibit B11.

313    With respect, the Prosecution did not put sufficient thought into marshalling the evidence on this particular charge. It has not been sufficiently proven that P3(2)(A) was taken on a date other than 9 April 2014. I thus acquit the Accused of the forgery charge in DAC 922432/2018.

(4)    B36(3) & B36(4): Both were images of P3(2)C

314    I next determine whether the photographs B36(3) and B36(4) were images of P3(2)C.

315    The Prosecution experts took the view that that both images were images of P3(2)C. Apart from canvassing the similarities in the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures, both Dr Andrew Tay and Dr Loh paid special attention to the black shard-shaped object at the crown of tooth #35 in P3(2)C (at the right side of the boundary line dividing cells A1 and B1). A physical examination of the surface of P3(2)C reveals that this is a physical defect where the emulsion layer appears to have been scratched off the radiograph film. Dr Andrew Tay suggested that the scratch could have arisen when the radiograph film was clipped while being dipped into the developing solution[note: 548] (a suggestion which Dr Firdaus concurred with[note: 549]). Both Dr Andrew Tay[note: 550] and Dr Loh[note: 551] found it remarkable that such a unique physical defect on P3(2)C could have been replicated in both B36(3) and B36(4), in the same shape and at the same location. Dr Loh opined that as this was a physical feature on the radiograph film, it was “virtually impossible” for it to have been replicated across separate radiographs in such a manner.[note: 552]

316    The Prosecution experts thus concluded that B36(3) & B36(4) were derived from the same image[note: 553] or, more specifically, derived from P3(2)C, save that the photographs may have been cropped after being created.[note: 554]

317    The Defence experts canvassed the prospect that B36(3) and B36(4) were not derived from the same source radiograph but had instead captured two separate radiographs, with P3(2)C being a third radiograph. While all three images may have looked similar, the Defence experts pointed to an array of dissimilarities in features and appearance, to support the Accused’s claim that these images arose from three separate shots of the patient’s mouth. These dissimilarities, as catalogued in the Defence submissions,[note: 555] are listed below.

(a)     Dr Leo Fung highlighted the differences between P3(2)C on the one hand, and B36(3) and B36(4) on the other:

(i)       There was an “elliptical bound patch” to the right of tooth #35 in P3(2)C (at cells D2 and D3) that was not visible in B36(3) and B36(4).[note: 556]

(ii)       The roots of tooth #37 in P3(2)A appeared “more distinct and upright” as compared to in B36(3) and B36(4).[note: 557]

(b)     Dr Leo Fung also highlighted the differences when B36(3) and B36(4) were compared with each other:

(i)       There was a white dot at the root of tooth #35 in B36(3) (corresponding to the top right corner of cell E1) that was not visible in B36(4)[note: 558] (As will be explained at paragraph 433 below, this observation was wrong as the white dot, whilst seen on the image of B36(3) reproduced in this judgment, was not on the photograph B36(3) itself).

(ii)       The “angulation” of tooth #37 and its root tip was different, as between in B36(3) and B36(4).[note: 559]

(c)     As for Dr Alfred Lau, he highlighted the differences between P3(2)C and B36(3):

(i)       The “dark streak” on the tip of tooth #35 in B36(3) was narrow and sharper as compared to P3(2)A (this was the shard-shaped structure which the Prosecution experts highlighted as being a physical defect on P3(2)A, that had been replicated in both B36(3) and B36(4)).[note: 560]

(ii)       The “white streak” to the right of tooth #37 in P3(2)A (at cell C5) was narrower as compared to B36(3).[note: 561]

(iii)       The occlusal fossa of tooth #37 and the shape of the pulp just underneath its crown looked “different”, as between P3(2)A (at cell B4) and B36(3).[note: 562]

(d)     Dr Alfred Lau also highlighted the differences when B36(3) and B36(4) were compared with each other:

(i)       The white dot at the apex of tooth #35 in B36(3) (corresponding to the top right corner of cell E1) was not visible in B36(4)[note: 563] (As will be explained at paragraph 433 below, this observation was wrong as the white dot, whilst seen on the image of B36(3) reproduced in this judgment, was not on the photograph B36(3) itself).

(ii)       The “downward extension” of the tooth #35 root canal in B36(3) (corresponding to the boundary dividing cell D1 and D2) was shorter as compared to B36(4).[note: 564]

(iii)       The oval-shaped opaque area over the root of tooth #37 (corresponding to cells D4 and D5) was more “rounded” in B36(3) but more “irregular” in shape in B36(4).[note: 565]

(e)     Similarly, Dr Firdaus highlighted the differences between P3(2)C on the one hand, and B36(3) and B36(4) on the other:

(i)       The small radiopaque dot above tooth #35 in B36(3) was not visible in P3(2)A (at cell A1).[note: 566]

(ii)       The area to the right of tooth #37, especially the bony region, was “more radio opaque” in B36(3) and B36 (4) than in P3(2)A (at cell C5).[note: 567]

(iii)       The triangular shape at the tip of tooth #35 in B36(4) “crosses more into the enamel region” than in P3(2) top radiograph (at cell B1).[note: 568]

318    Having assessed the evidence above, I conclude that both B36(3) and 36(4) were images of P3(2)C.

319    Firstly, a visual inspection of all three images shows that the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures were highly similar across all three images. Given the array of variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam, referred to in paragraph 242(a) above, it would have been difficult to achieve this across three successive shots. There were some instances when the Defence experts purported to highlight what could conceivably be regarded as differences in shape or positioning. For example, Dr Leo Fung suggested that the angle of the tooth #35 appeared more “upright” in P3(2)A. However, on examining the physical exhibits, I did not detect any difference in angulation. As for the dots, lines and other shapes raised by the Defence experts, I am unable to rule out the prospect that these dissimilarities stemmed from reprographic errors during the image capture and printing process.

320    Secondly, the most compelling aspect of the Prosecution’s case as regards this radiograph is the black shard-shaped feature at the crown of tooth #35. A physical examination of P3(2)C shows that this is a physical defect where the surface of the film has peeled off. This is clearly not part of the patient’s anatomy.[note: 569] As such, there is no explicable reason for this feature’s replication across all three images. The Accused tried to offer some explanations for the replication. None of these hold water:

(a)     The Accused suggested that the feature might have been a cavity.[note: 570] This was, with the greatest of respect, nonsense. As alluded to immediately above, the feature was clearly a physical defect on the radiograph film and not part of the anatomical context. Furthermore, a cavity would have been situated on the tooth. Here, the shard-shaped structure extended well beyond the tooth and into the black open space of the oral cavity. As explained by Dr Loh, this makes it impossible for the feature to be a cavity.[note: 571] Finally, as Dr Andrew Tay observed, the feature was huge relative to the size of the teeth.[note: 572] If it had indeed been present on the tooth, whether in the form of a cavity or other dental condition, it must surely have been captured in the Accused’s clinical notes. Yet, there was no record of this in the notes.[note: 573]

(b)     The Accused also suggested that the feature could be due to damage that affected multiple unused radiograph films while they were still stacked together.[note: 574] This explanation contemplated multiple unused radiograph films being stacked together prior to use. Upon such a stack of films being pressed against an external object, more than one film in the stack could sustain a scratch or indentation of the same shape and at the same location on the film. The hypothesis was that if those radiograph films were then taken out and used successively on the same patient, one could conceivably end up with multiple radiographs with the same scratch or indentation juxtaposed at the same location.[note: 575] I reject this explanation, given the probabilities that it entails:

(i)       Firstly, the likelihood of defects such as scratches and indentations occurring in the same shape and size and at the very same spot across multiple radiograph films is extremely small – the Defence expert Dr Leo Fung conceded that the probability was as low as 1%.[note: 576]

(ii)       Secondly, even if we have multiple radiograph films bearing physical defects of the same shape and size and located at the same spot, these films must then be used to capture successive X-rays of the same patient’s teeth. The probability that each successive radiographic image captured by these films could reflect the patient’s anatomical structures with the same shape and positioning would be very small, given the multitude of variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam, explained at paragraph 242(a) above.

(iii)       Finally, even if we have the same physical defect occurring in the same shape, size and location across multiple radiograph films AND these films each capture the same anatomical structures with the same shape and positioning, the physical defect must then be juxtaposed at the very same spot vis-à-vis those anatomical structures. This narrows the probabilities even further.[note: 577] To illustrate, when the radiographer fits the radiograph film on the film holder prior to taking the X-ray, the film need not necessarily be placed in the exact same orientation (with any one edge facing any one direction) each time.[note: 578] The Defence expert Dr Firdaus had thus conceded that even if the physical defect is replicated across multiple radiograph films, it is unlikely that it could be superimposed on the exact same anatomical structure depicted in the radiograph, as was the case here where the shard-shaped feature was at the exact same spot on the crown of tooth #35,[note: 579] in all three images.

Given that the above probabilities are cumulative, the chance of multiple radiographs films capturing the same anatomical features with the same shape and positioning, with a physical defect of the same shape and size juxtaposed at the same location vis-à-vis the anatomical structures, is practically non-existent.

321    I am thus satisfied that both B36(3) and B36(4) were images of P3(2)C. However, this does not dispose of the analysis. To address the allegations in the forgery charges, I must further assess the following:

(a)     In respect of B36(3), whether the tooth #36 socket was made to look more distinct.

(b)     In respect of B36(4), whether white dots were added above the bone line at tooth #36 to depict bone graft material.

(5)    B36(3) & B36(4): Both images had been altered

322    The Prosecution’s case is that B36(3) had been altered to make the tooth #36 socket look more distinct, while B36(4) had been altered to add white dots (depicting bone graft granules) above the bone line at tooth #36.

323    As a preliminary step, I rule out the possibility that the appearance of the photographs was due to ABG having actually been performed at the tooth #36 site. As explained above, when finding the Accused guilty of the cheating charge in respect of Chong Moh Chin, I was satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that ABG had not been performed on her. This then gives rise to the question of how the photographs in B36(3) and B36(4) came to appear as they did.

324    As regards the socket in B36(3), the Prosecution experts were of the view that the shape of this socket looked unnatural. Dr Andrew Tay highlighted that the socket’s roots were significantly smaller than that of the neighbouring teeth, even after taking account of the possibility for natural variations in tooth sizes.[note: 580] He noted that the nature and density of the black space within the socket space meant that the socket was probably added.[note: 581] Dr Loh similarly observed that the roots of the socket were much shorter than the adjacent tooth. He explained that the shortness of the socket could not be explained by the healing process (tooth #36 had been extracted many years prior to Chong Moh Chin’s visit to the Accused on 9 April 2014[note: 582]), given that the darkness and distinct shape of the socket in B36(3) were inconsistent with the appearance of a socket that had years to heal.[note: 583] He thus felt that the socket looked fake.[note: 584]

325    The Defence expert Dr Leo Fung tried to explain that the shape of the socket could have been attributable to genetic malformation of tooth #36, due to a condition called taurodontism. This is where the tooth’s roots are proportionately shorter when compared to the crown.[note: 585] I do not find this explanation to be in any way credible. Firstly, as conceded by Dr Leo Fung, tauorodontism is rare.[note: 586] Secondly, the Defence did not point me to anything in Chong Moh Chin’s patient records showing that taurodontism was documented. If this was an exceptional condition, one would have expected there to be some record of it. Thirdly, Dr Leo Fung’s suggestion of taurodontism was never put to the Prosecution experts when they were giving evidence about the unnatural shape of the socket, notwithstanding Dr Leo Fung having been allowed to sit in court during the cross-examination of Dr Loh and Dr Andrew Tay.[note: 587]

326    Viewing the evidence in totality, I am of the view that the socket in B36(3) was added:

(a)     Firstly, the socket was conspicuously absent in P3(2)C, which was the source radiograph from which B36(3) was derived.

(b)     Secondly, the socket’s appearance strongly suggested that it was not a genuine part of the patient’s anatomy. I agree with the Prosecution experts that the socket looked abnormally short. Unlike in the case of B35(2) (discussed at paragraph 280 above), where the shape of the socket was fine and the only irregularity which the Prosecution could point to was the lack of shading,[note: 588] it is obvious that for B36(3), the very shape of the socket was artificial. Even the Defence expert Dr Firdaus agreed that the socket looked unnatural.[note: 589] As for Dr Leo Fung’s suggestion of taurodontism, this was simply not supported by the evidence.

I thus conclude that B36(3) had been altered by the addition of the short dark socket shape to make the tooth #36 socket appear more distinct.

327    As regards the white dots in B36(4), floating above the bone line at the tooth #36 site, Dr Loh opined that this looked unnatural as he had never seen bone graft granules floating like that.[note: 590] For the reasons set out at paragraph 288 above, I give the Accused the benefit of the doubt on this and accept the possibility that bone graft granules may on occasion be viewed in the radiograph as floating above the bone line, in the wake of an ABG.

328    Notwithstanding this concession by me, the totality of the evidence still points to the conclusion that the white dots were added:

(a)     Firstly, these white dots were conspicuously absent from P3(2)C,[note: 591] which was the source radiograph from which B36(4) was derived.

(b)     Secondly, given my finding that ABG was not performed at the tooth #36 site, I rule out these white dots being actual bone granules.

(c)     Finally, I discount the possibility that these white dots were artefacts randomly arising from reprographic errors. If it had just been a few dots scattered across random locations, I could still give the Accused the benefit of the doubt and refrain from concluding that the dots were added. However, the dots were not at all random. Rather, they comprised multiple discrete dots, all clustered exactly at the site where ABG was supposed to have been performed.

I thus accept the views of the Prosecution experts that the white dots floating above the bone line at the tooth #36 site were added.

329    Collectively, B36(3) and B36(4) were clearly calculated to convey the impression that ABG had been performed at the tooth #36 site, with B36(3) serving as the image of Chong Moh Chin’s mouth before the ABG (where the socket at the tooth #36 site was distinctly present) and B36(4) serving as the image after the ABG (where the socket was conspicuously absent, having been filled with bone graft granules depicted by the white dots floating above the bone line). This conclusion is bolstered by the Accused’s Long Statement, where he stated that B36(3) and B36(4) showed “Bone graft to tooth #36”.[note: 592]

330    I am thus satisfied that B36(3) and B36(4) were images of P3(2)C that had been altered, by:

(a)     addition of the short dark socket shape to B36(3), to make the tooth #36 socket look more distinct; and

(b)     addition of white dots to B36(4), above the bone line at tooth #36.

The three photographs of Neo Kheng Yew’s teeth: B37(1)-(3)

331    To recapitulate, the Accused faced a single cheating charge in respect of Neo Kheng Yew.[note: 593] That charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly submitted a Medisave claim declaring that he had performed ABG (at the tooth #46 site) and FBR (at the tooth #17 area) on Neo Kheng Yew, when both these procedures had not been performed. Following from this, the Prosecution’s case on the forgery charges in respect of Neo Kheng Yew is that the Accused forged three photographs, B37(1)-(3), to deceive MoH auditors into thinking that ABG and FBR (which were the subject of the cheating charge) had been performed on Neo Kheng Yew, when they had not.

332    In respect of the ABG procedure, the Prosecution’s case is as follows:

(a)      B37(1) was an image of P3(3)B that had been altered to depict a distinct socket at the tooth #46 site.

DAC 922436/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B37(1) by making the tooth socket appear more distinct.

(b)      B37(2) was also an image of P3(3)B and had been:

(i)       used to depict the absence of the socket at the tooth #46 site, thereby portraying this as the aftermath of an ABG (with the socket now filled with graft material); and

(ii)        altered to depict white dots above the bone line at tooth #46, thereby portraying this as graft material used in the ABG.

DAC 922437/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B37(2) by adding the white dots.

333    The table below reproduces the images of P3(3)B (with a grid overlaid for ease of navigation), B37(1) and B37(2):

334    In respect of the FBR procedure, the Prosecution’s case is as follows:

(a)      B37(3) was altered to depict a white dot at tooth #17, thereby portraying this as a foreign body in need of removal.

DAC 922435/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering B37(3) by adding the white dot.

(b)      B37(4) was used to depict the absence of the white dot at tooth #17, thereby portraying this as the aftermath of the FBR, where the foreign body was now removed.

Unlike in the forgery charges above, the source radiograph which these two photographs allegedly captured was not retrieved.

335    The table below reproduces the images of B37(3) (with a grid overlaid for ease of navigation) and B37(4):

(1)   B37(1) & B37(2): Both were images of P3(3)B

336    The first issue is whether the photographs B37(1) and B37(2) were images of P3(3)B. The Prosecution experts were of the view that they were.

337    In terms of shape and positioning of the anatomical structures, Dr Andrew Tay opined that B37(1) and B37(2) were similar.[note: 594] In particular, he felt that it was not possible to reproduce the shape of the filling at tooth #47 in successive radiographs, with such similarity as seen in the three images.[note: 595]

338    The Prosecution experts also canvassed how physical defects on the surface of P3(3)B had been transposed to B37(1) and B37(2):

(a)     Firstly, they referred to a vertical white scratch at the left edge of tooth #45 (corresponding to the left side of cell B5) in P3(3)B. According to Dr Andrew Tay, this scratch served as a “unique identifier” that had been reproduced exactly in both B37(1) and B37(2).[note: 596] Likewise, Dr Loh observed that this scratch was on the surface of the radiograph film P3(3)B and had been replicated in B37(1) and B37(2), at the exact same location.[note: 597] Dr Loh also opined that such a scratch would not be reproduced across multiple images in this fashion.[note: 598]

(b)     Secondly, Dr Loh observed that the embossed dot on the surface of P3(3)B[note: 599] (at the bottom half of cell A1) was juxtaposed over the same anatomical structure in all three images, at the exact same location.[note: 600]

339    Consequently, both Dr Andrew Tay[note: 601] and Dr Loh[note: 602] concluded that both B37(1) and B37(2) were derived from P3(3)B.

340    The Defence experts canvassed the prospect that B37(1) and B37(2) were not derived from the same source radiograph but had instead captured two separate radiographs, with P3(3)B being yet another radiograph −meaning that there were three different radiographs involved. While the three images may have looked similar, the Defence experts pointed to an array of dissimilarities in features and appearance, to support the Accused’s claim that these images arose from three separate shots of the patient’s mouth. These dissimilarities, as catalogued in the Defence submissions,[note: 603] are listed below.

341    Dr Leo Fung highlighted the differences between P3(3)B on the one hand, and B37(1) and B37(2) on the other:

(a)     The dots and patches extending to tooth #37 in P3(3)B (occupying cells A1, A2, B1, B2 and C2) were not visible in B37(1) and B37(2).[note: 604]

(b)     The area of radio opacity beneath the edentulous section of the bone line in P3(3)B (occupying cells C3, C4, D3 and D4) was “very homogenous”, while the corresponding location in B37(1) and B37(2) displayed “different densities and shades of grey”.[note: 605]

342    Dr Leo Fung also highlighted the differences when B37(1) and B37(2) were compared with each other:

(a)     The circular white structure at the root of tooth #44 in B37(1) (corresponding to the right portions of cell C6) was of “different density and shape” when compared with that in B37(2).[note: 606]

(b)     The pulp chamber of tooth #45 in B37(1) (corresponding to cell B5) appeared “sharper” than in B37(2), where it appeared “rounder”.[note: 607]

343    As for Dr Alfred Lau, he highlighted the differences when B37(1) and B37(2) were compared with each other:

(a)     The “bone marrow pattern” in the area below the socket between teeth #44 and #45 (corresponding to cells D3 and D4) looked different, as between B37(1) and B37(2).[note: 608]

(b)     The “pulpal shape” of tooth #47 (corresponding to cell B2) looked different, as between in B37(1) and B37(2).[note: 609]

(c)     The white dot on tooth #47 in B37(1) (corresponding to cell B2) did not appear in B37(2).[note: 610]

344    Dr Firdaus, on his part, highlighted the differences between P3(3)B on the one hand, and B37(1) and B37(2) on the other:

(a)     There was a “significantly different mix” of radiolucent and radio opaque marks at the top right corner in B37(1) and B37(2), when compared with P3(3)B (The Defence submissions appear to be wrong in highlighting this feature as being at the image’s top “right” corner. According to the Transcripts, when Dr Firdaus referred to these marks, he was referencing the top left corner of the image, at cells A1, B1 and C1[note: 611]).

(b)     There was a “significant” black line at the restorative margin of tooth #47 in P3(3)B (at cell A2) that was not in B37(1).[note: 612]

(c)     There was a ‘H’-shaped radiolucent line in B37(1) that was more “well-defined” as compared to P3(3)B (at the bottom right corner of cell C2).[note: 613]

(d)     The radiopaque vertical line at the crestal bone to the right of tooth #44 in B37(1) was not visible in P3(3)B (Again, the Defence submissions appear to be wrong. The crestal bone to the right of tooth #44 lay at the extreme right edge of the image − Dr Firdaus did not make any mention of a radiopaque line at this location being present in B37(1) and absent in P3(3)B)

(e)     There was a black line to the right of tooth #47 in B37(2) that was “more well-defined” as compared to P3(3)B (at cell C2).[note: 614]

(f)     The bony ridge to the left of tooth #45 was “defined and pointed” in B37(2), while the corresponding area in P3(3)B (at the bottom right corner of cell B4) appeared “more blunt”.[note: 615]

345    Having assessed the evidence above, I conclude that both B37(1) and 37(2) were images of P3(3)B.

346    Preliminarily, a visual examination of all three images validates Dr Andrew Tay’s observation that the shape and angulation of the anatomical structures were the same across all three images. As regards the dots, lines and other shapes highlighted by the Defence experts, I agree with the Prosecution that these are largely minor dissimilarities which could have arisen from reprographic errors during the process of capturing and printing the image.

347    The most compelling aspect of the Prosecution’s case as regards P3(3)B pertains to the physical features on the surface of the radiograph film, which were transposed to B37(1) and B37(2), ie, the vertical white scratch at left edge of tooth #45 and the black embossed dot at the top left corner of the image. Given that these were not part of the patient’s anatomy but were physical features unique to a specific radiograph film, there was simply no reason for these features to be replicated in the same shape and at the same location across three successive radiographs. The fact that they were transposed with such stunning similarity demanded a credible explanation, for which the Defence offered none. In his examination-in-chief, the Accused suggested that the vertical white line could have been the tip of a metal file that had broken off and lodged itself in the gum, or a metal band wrapped around the tooth.[note: 616] However, the Defence expert Dr Leo Fung confirmed that this could not be an object within the anatomical context, such as a broken file or metal band, as a physical examination of P3(3)B showed that the vertical white line corresponded to a scratch on the film of P3(3)B.[note: 617]

348    I am thus satisfied that both B37(1) and B37(2) were images of P3(3)B. However, that does not end the matter as I must also assess the following:

(a)     In respect of B37(1), whether the tooth #46 socket was made to look more distinct.

(b)     In respect of B37(2), whether white dots were added above the bone line at tooth #46 to depict bone graft material.

(2)    B37(1) & B37(2): Both images had been altered

349    The Prosecution contends that B37(1) had been altered to make the tooth socket at tooth #46 look more distinct, while B37(2) had been altered to add white dots (depicting bone graft granules) above the bone line at tooth #46.

350    First and foremost, I exclude the possibility that the images arose from ABG having actually been performed at the tooth #46 site. As explained above, in finding the Accused guilty of the cheating charge in respect of Neo Kheng Yew, I was satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that the Accused did not perform ABG on him, on 9 April 2014. This then leads to the question as to why the photographs in B37(1) and B37(2) appeared as they did.

351    As regards the tooth #46 socket in B37(1), the feature at issue is the shorter, darker socket that appears to be overlaid above a longer, lighter socket. Both sockets start off at the bone line at the tooth #46 site and extend downwards, except that the two roots of the lighter socket, being longer, extend further down, to below the tips of the two roots of the shorter, darker socket.[note: 618] If one next looks at B37(2), the shorter, darker socket is gone (albeit the longer, lighter socket is still visible in B37(2) extending down from the bone line at the tooth #46 site) −the disappearance of the shorter darker socket thus appears to convey the impression that the socket in B37(4) was now filled with bone graft material.

352    The Prosecution experts commented that the shorter darker socket in B37(1) looked unnatural. This was purportedly a radiograph that had been taken on 9 April 2014, which was the day that tooth #46 was extracted (see paragraph 62 above). This meant that the radiograph was meant to depict a freshly extracted socket. Dr Andrew Tay pointed out if the tooth had indeed been extracted on the day that the radiograph had been taken, the socket’s roots would be of the same size as the neighbouring teeth. Yet, the socket was much smaller and shorter than that of the neighbouring molar roots.[note: 619] As for Dr Loh, he took a similar view, saying that if this had been a freshly extracted socket, the length of the socket would be the same as that of the adjacent teeth, and the lamina dura would look more distinct.[note: 620]

353    The Defence expert, Dr Firdaus, also agreed that the shape of the socket in B37(1) did not make sense. He was asked if the socket looked natural, with a shorter, darker socket overlaid on what appeared to be a lighter, longer socket. Initially, he responded that this was consistent with three-dimensional capture of the bone healing process, with the bone growing inwards toward the socket’s centre. He opined that in such a situation, it was not unusual to see what appeared to be overlapping sockets.[note: 621] Following from this, he was confronted with the fact that B37(1) was taken on the same date (ie, on 9 April 2014) as the radiograph P3(3)B (which did not have the shorter, darker socket overlaid) and he was then asked again whether his hypothesis (about the shorter darker socket being indicative of healing) still held.[note: 622] After comparing both images, he agreed that the appearance of the shorter, darker socket, overlaid against the longer, lighter socket in B37(1), did not make sense.[note: 623]

354    Given the expert evidence, I agree that the shorter, darker socket at tooth #46 was added to B37(1):

(a)     Firstly, the socket was conspicuously absent in P3(3)B, despite this being the source radiograph from which B37(1) was derived.

(b)     Secondly, the socket’s appearance strongly suggested that it was not a genuine feature of the patient’s anatomy. The Prosecution experts, and even the Defence expert Dr Firdaus, all agreed that the socket did not look natural. I agree, given how the socket was clearly shorter than any of the other adjacent roots. Unlike in the case of B36(3) (see paragraph 325 above), there was no suggestion of taurodontism here.

This leads me to conclude that B37(1) had been altered, by the short dark socket shape being added to make the tooth #46 socket appear more distinct.

355    As regards the white dots above the bone line at tooth #46 in B37(2), the Prosecution experts opined that they also looked unnatural. Dr Andrew Tay said that the image did not depict what a bone graft looks like.[note: 624] Similarly, Dr Loh pointed to how the alleged bone granules were floating in the air and said that this was inconsistent with what is seen after a bone graft, where the granules are packed down into a heap without any space in between.[note: 625] For the reasons set out at paragraph 288 above, I am not prepared to give the Accused the benefit of the doubt on this and accept that bone graft granules may on occasion appear in the radiograph as floating above the bone line, following an ABG.

356    Notwithstanding this concession, I am still of the view that the evidence is strongly suggestive of the white dots having been added:

(a)     Firstly, the white dots were conspicuously absent in P3(3)B,[note: 626] despite this being the source radiograph from which B37(2) was derived.

(b)     Secondly, giving my finding that ABG was not performed at the tooth #46 site, I rule out that the prospect of these white dots being actual bone granules. To be sure, Neo Kheng Yew did not recall undergoing any bone graft (and not just ABG).

(c)     Finally, I discount the possibility of these white dots being artefacts generated by reprographic error. If it had been the case of a few dots sprinkled at random locations, I could still give the Accused the benefit of the doubt and refrain from concluding that the dots were added. However, the dots were anything but random. There were multiple discrete white dots, all clustered strategically at the very spot where the ABG was supposed to have been performed.

I thus conclude that the white dots above the bone line at #46 were added.

357    Viewed collectively, both images were clearly meant to convey the impression that ABG had been performed at the tooth #46 site, with B37(1) serving as the image of Neo Kheng Yew’s teeth before the ABG (where the socket at the tooth #46 site was distinctly present) and B37(2) serving as the image after the ABG (where the socket was conspicuously absent, having been filled with bone graft granules depicted by the white dots floating above the bone line). This conclusion is strengthened by the Accused’s Long Statement, where he stated that B37(1) and B37(2) showed “Bone graft at tooth #46”.[note: 627]

358    I am thus satisfied that B37(1) and B37(2) were images of P3(2)C that had been altered by:

(a)     addition of the shorter, darker socket shape to B37(1), to make the tooth #46 socket look more distinct; and

(b)     addition of white dots to B37(2), above the bone line at tooth #46.

(3)    B37(3) & B37(4): Both captured the same radiograph

359    I next assess whether the photograph B37(3) was an image of the same radiograph captured by B37(4). As explained at paragraph 235 above, the source radiograph(s) for both these photographs could not be found.

360    The Prosecution experts were of the view that both photographs were images of the same radiograph.

361    Dr Loh observed that the shape of the teeth restoration was the same in both B37(3) and B37(4), remarking that it was difficult to achieve that kind of similarity for such three-dimensional structures.[note: 628] Dr Loh also paid specific attention to the implant’s screw threads. He explained that dentists may conduct an exercise where they take successive radiographs of an implant over a period of time. The objective is to compare these radiographs to see if the bone level has shifted vis-à-vis the implant’s screw threads, over the period concerned. This exercise, which requires paying very close attention to the screw thread’s pattern, allows the dentist to tell if the bone level has receded. To enable a like-for-like comparison of the radiographs taken at different points in time, the radiographs must all be taken from as similar an angle as possible, given that variations in angle can distort the appearance of the bone height vis-à-vis the screw threads. Dr Loh explained that in this exercise, “one of the biggest problem[s]” is standardising the angle at which the radiographs are shot.[note: 629] Given the notorious difficulty of capturing implant threads at the same angle over successive radiographs, Dr Loh found the similarity with which the screw threads in both B37(3) and B37(4) had been captured to be extraordinary.[note: 630] Dr Loh thus opined that B37(3) and B37(4) were derived from the same radiograph.

362    Dr Andrew Tay also opined that both B37(3) and B37(4) appeared identical, in terms of the shape and orientation of the implants, with the only difference being the white dot purporting to represent the foreign body.[note: 631]

363    The Defence experts canvassed the prospect that B37(3) and B37(4) were not derived from the same source radiograph but had instead captured two separate radiographs. While both images may have looked similar, the Defence experts pointed to variations in features and appearance to support the claim that both photographs captured two separate radiographs. These dissimilarities, as catalogued in the Defence submissions,[note: 632] are listed below.

(a)     Dr Alfred Lau highlighted the differences when B37(3) and B37(4) were compared with each other:

(i)       There was a small white dot to the left of tooth #17 (corresponding to the top right corner of cell D1) (to the left of the white patch which the Prosecution alleged was added to denote the foreign body) in B37(3) that was not visible in B37(4).[note: 633]

(ii)       There was a small white dot to the right of tooth #17 in B37(3) (corresponding to the top right corner of cell C3) that was not visible in B37(4).[note: 634]

(iii)       The “bone marrow pattern” at the distal area of tooth #17 (corresponding to cell B1) looked different, as between B37(3) and B37(4).[note: 635]

(b)     Likewise, Dr Firdaus highlighted the differences when B37(3) and B37(4) were compared with each other:

(i)       The distal area of tooth #17 in B37(3) (at cells B1 and C1) had a “different mix” of radiopacity and radiolucency, when compared with B37(4).[note: 636]

(ii)       The small white dot to the right of tooth #17 in B37(3) (corresponding to the top right corner of cell C3) was not visible in B37(4).[note: 637]

(iii)       The track of the implant at tooth #16 appeared “sharper” in B37(3) (corresponding to cells C5 and D5) as compared to B37(4).[note: 638]

(iv)       The small white dot to the right of the implant at tooth #16 in B37(3) (corresponding to the boundary dividing cells C6 and D6) was not visible in B37(4).[note: 639]

364    Having assessed the evidence above, I am satisfied that B37(3) and 37(4) were images of the same radiograph.

365    Firstly, looking carefully at both photographs, I agree with Dr Loh’s observation that overall, the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures in both images are the same. In particular, the shape of the restoration in both teeth looked the same in both B37(3) and B37(4). In both images, it looked as if a single diagonal line has cut through the restorations on both teeth (starting from cell E2 and moving diagonally up the right to cell D5) −that line looked the same in both images.

366    I also agree with Dr Loh’s observations about the screw threads. Dr Loh testified that it would be extremely difficult for the implant’s screw threads to look the same in successive radiographs. Intuitively, I can see why this is so. As the Prosecution experts noted, given the multiple variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam, it is difficult to take successive radiographs of a three-dimensional object so that it looks the same across the different radiographs. This difficulty, if it exists for objects with regular outlines, must surely be compounded in the case of implant screws, where the threads would manifest themselves as numerous ridges and troughs. I can thus accept Dr Loh’s explanation that it is difficult to shoot successive radiographs of the implant screw so that the threads look the same across different shots.

367    This then brings me to the images in B37(3) and B37(4). The Defence contends that the quality of the photographs in B37(3) and B37(4) was so lacking that the Prosecution experts could not make out any distinct features.[note: 640] I disagree. An examination of both photographs allows one to clearly discern the screw threads, especially those on the left edge of the right tooth. While Dr Firdaus claimed that the threads appeared sharper in B37(3) than B37(4), I could not detect any difference when examining both photographs. Instead, like Dr Loh, I could clearly see that the threads on both images looked the same. It must be stressed that this is not a case where the Accused was engaging in the exercise that Dr Loh canvassed at paragraph 361 above, ie, taking multiple radiographs of an implant’s screw thread to form a time series, to assess if the bone level has receded vis-à-vis the threads. There was no suggestion that the radiographs purportedly captured by B37(3) and B37(4) were deliberately taken to achieve as similar an angle as possible. Rather, the radiographs which both photographs purported to capture were supposedly shot on the same day (ie, 9 April 2014) and were simply meant to show Neo Kheng Yew’s mouth before and after the FBR. I agree with Dr Loh that it is extraordinary for photographs taken under such routine clinical settings to show such remarkable similarity in the screw threads.

368    As for the dissimilarities in dots and patterns highlighted by the Defence experts, these appear very minor to me. I am unable to rule out the prospect of them arising from reprographic errors during the process of capturing and printing the image.

369    I thus conclude that B37(3) and B37(4) were images of the same radiograph, even if that radiograph could not be found. Having done so, I move on to consider if the white dot (at tooth #17) was indeed added to B37(3).

(4)    B37(3): White dot was added

370    At the outset, I rule out the possibility that the white dot at B37(3) was actually a foreign body which the Accused removed. As explained above, when finding the Accused guilty of the cheating charge in respect of Neo Kheng Yew, I was satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that FBR had not been performed at the tooth #17 area. The question thus arises as to how the white dot came to appear in B37(3).

371    The Prosecution experts were of the view that the white dot was added. Dr Loh said that the white dot at B37(3) did not appear to be something within the patient’s jaw.[note: 641] Dr Andrew Tay similarly questioned how a foreign body could possibly have been forced into the gum at that location.[note: 642] He said that a person with such a foreign body at that spot would complain of pain or discomfort.[note: 643] Yet, Neo Kheng Yew testified that the only issue he had with his mouth was the decay at tooth #46[note: 644] and he did not complain to the Accused about any problem other than that.[note: 645] The Accused similarly did not highlight to Neo Kheng Yew about a foreign body in his mouth,[note: 646] notwithstanding the radiographic image at B37(3) showing such a prominent white object next to tooth #17.

372    I agree with the views expressed by the Prosecution experts. The white dot was located next to tooth #17, ie, at the very tooth where the FBR was alleged to have taken place. It was also conspicuously absent from B37(4), which I found to have been an image of the same source radiograph. Given that both photographs were tendered to the MoH auditors to show that FBR had taken place at the tooth #17 area, they were clearly meant to portray Neo Kheng Yew’s mouth ‘before’ and ‘after’ the FBR. This is reinforced by the Accused’s Long Statement, where he stated that the photographs B37(3) and B37(4) showed “Removal of foreign body at tooth 17”.[note: 647]

373    I am thus satisfied that B37(3) was an image of the same radiograph captured by B37(4) and had been altered by the addition of the white dot at the site where the FBR was purportedly performed (at tooth #17).

No trace of what Accused claimed to be the source radiographs

374    The practice of the Accused’s clinic was to store patients’ radiographs in Ziplock sachets that were stapled to the patient’s patient card. As explained at paragraph 235 above, during the raid, the police seized the patient cards of various patients, which had Ziplock sachets (containing radiographs) stapled to them. These included the patient cards for Catherine Chia, Chong Moh Chin and Neo Kheng Yew, to which were attached the following radiographs:

(a)     P3(1)A, which I found to be the source radiograph for B35(1) and B35(2);

(b)     P3(2)A, which I found to be the source radiograph for B36(1) and B36(2);

(c)     P3(2)(C), which I found to be the source radiograph for B36(3) and B36(4); and

(d)     P3(3)B, which I found to be the source radiograph for B37(1) and B37(2).

375    The Accused could have shown that the photographs in the forgery charge were not forgeries, simply by producing the original radiographs which he claimed that these photographs captured. This would have resoundingly demonstrated that the photographs were not derived from what the Prosecution alleged to be the source radiographs and, more importantly, that the alleged alterations at the heart of the forgery charges were genuine features that could be seen on the radiograph film. Yet, despite the Accused’s clinic being in possession of so many radiographs at the time of the raid, all systematically stored in small Ziplock sachets stapled to the patient cards, the Accused could not produce any of the original radiographs which he claimed were captured by the photographs in the forgery charges. These original radiographs were neither stapled to the patient cards,[note: 648] nor found anywhere else. That the original radiographs could simply disappear ran counter to the Accused’s position that safekeeping of the radiographs was an important concern to him. He testified that he used to submit original radiographs for MoH audits but had switched to submitting photographs of the radiographs instead, because it would be quite a “headache” if the radiographs ever got misplaced.[note: 649]

376    The disappearance of all the (purported) original radiographs was as coincidental as it was convenient. This state of affairs cried out for an explanation. The Accused was in fact given that chance to explain, in his Long Statement. However, his responses were nothing short of bland:

(a)     When asked for the whereabouts of the three original radiographs of Catherine Chia, purportedly captured by B35(1)-(3), he replied that they may have “fallen off”, whether “on the clinic table” or “at the bottom of the drawer”.[note: 650] When asked how all these radiographs could go missing when Catherine Chia’s other radiographs were still attached to her patient card, he said that he did not know, re-iterating that the radiographs may have “fallen from the patient notes”.[note: 651]

(b)     When asked for the whereabouts of the four original radiographs of Chong Moh Chin, purportedly captured by B36(1)-(4), he replied that he did not know, surmising that they may have “dropped out”.[note: 652] When asked how all these radiographs could go missing, he replied that they may have “fallen off”.[note: 653]

(c)     When asked for the whereabouts of the four original radiographs of Neo Kheng Yew, purportedly captured by B37(1)-(4), he replied that they were attached to the patient card but may have been “misplaced in the clinic” or “dropped to the bottom of the cabinet.”[note: 654] When queried as to how all these radiographs could go missing, when all the other radiographs were still attached to Neo Kheng Yew’s patient card, he re-iterated that the radiographs could have “fallen off”, been “misplaced” or have “fallen from the patient notes”.[note: 655]

377    Even if the radiographs had (as claimed by the Accused) “fallen off” or “dropped out”, whether into a cabinet or drawer, or onto the clinic table, it is quite another thing for them to vanish into thin air thereafter, to the point that none of them can now be found. The Accused’s inability to produce these original radiographs is thus highly telling, making it difficult to avoid taking a dim view of his claim that the photographs in the forgery charges captured original radiographs that were distinct from the alleged source radiographs. The only logical inference is that the original radiographs could not be found, not because they dropped into a cabinet or drawer, but because they were tucked away in the recesses of the Accused’s imagination.

The photograph of Juliann Rick’s teeth

378    To recapitulate, the Accused faced a single cheating charge in respect of Juliann Rick.[note: 656] That charge alleged that the Accused dishonestly submitted a Medisave claim declaring that he had performed FBR (at the tooth #26 area) and ABG (at the tooth #36 site) on Juliann Rick, when both these procedures had not been performed. Following from this, the Prosecution’s case on the forgery charge is that the Accused forged the photograph that was captured in P4, to deceive MoH auditors into thinking that the FBR (which was the subject of the cheating charge) had been performed on Juliann Rick, when it had not.

379    The Prosecution’s case is that the photograph captured in P4 had been altered to depict a white dot at tooth #26, to portray the foreign body which the Accused claimed to have removed. DAC 922438/2018 thus charged the Accused with dishonestly altering the photograph by adding the white dot.

380    As explained above, the source radiograph which the photograph purported to capture was not recovered. Even the photograph itself, which had allegedly been altered by the addition of the white dot, was not found.[note: 657] All that was produced before the court was P4, being a photocopy of the photograph. The photocopied image of the allegedly forged photograph, as captured by P4, is reproduced below:

381    The Defence contends[note: 658] that the evidence in respect of the allegedly forged photograph in P4 was “woefully deficient”. I must agree. The Prosecution submits[note: 659] that the Accused added the white dot to depict the foreign body which was removed by the Accused. This, argues the Prosecution, was consistent with Julian Rick’s evidence that she did not discuss about, nor undergo, any FBR procedure. With respect, this argument confuses the evidence required to establish that the FBR was never performed, with that required to establish that the photograph (submitted to MoH to prove that the FBR was performed) was a forgery. Any evidence proving the former would not necessarily be probative of the latter.

382    In fact, there was a complete dearth of forensic evidence to establish the forgery charge. This was not just a case of the source radiograph being absent. The photograph which captured that radiograph, and which had allegedly been altered, could also not be found. All the Prosecution had was a second hand copy of that photograph, in the form of the photocopied image in P4. Understandably, the Defence capitalised on the fact that the Prosecution was unable to embark upon the cross-image comparisons that had been made in respect of the photographs that were the subject of the forgery charges above.[note: 660]

383    It would have been useful if the experts had offered some forensic opinion on the authenticity of the photograph. However, Dr Andrew Tay did not appear to have commented very much on whether the image in P4 was forged. As for Dr Loh, he could not even tell what the white dot was, surmising that it could either be intrinsic within the jaw or extrinsic.[note: 661] In short, there was nothing from the Prosecution experts to satisfy me that the white dot was added. In all fairness to these experts, it would have been difficult for them to commit to a view, given that they did not even have the actual photograph on hand.

384    I am also unable to rule out that the white dot might have been nothing more than an artefact captured when Ker Lai Sim photocopied the photograph (to produce P4), as opposed to a feature captured in the photograph’s image. The photocopying process would have introduced yet a further layer of reprographic errors. The Prosecution has based much of its case on the prospect of reprographic errors occurring, using this to explain away minor differences between what they contend to be identical images. This renders it difficult for the Prosecution to simply dismiss out of hand the prospect that reprographic errors could also have been responsible for the white dot, which is rather tiny after all. Without the actual photograph, I will never know.

385    Given the dearth of evidence in support of this charge, I am not satisfied that the white dot on the photograph captured by P4 was added. I thus acquit the Accused of the forgery charge in DAC 922438/2018.

Exhibits D16, D17 and D18

386    As alluded to above, the Prosecution experts’ methodology for ascertaining if different images capture the same radiograph focused on the striking similarities in shape and positioning of the anatomical structures. I have explained why this methodology is both logical and coherent. Given the variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam (see paragraph 242(a) above), it would be unusual for such similarities to occur in successive radiographs, particularly in a routine clinical setting where radiographs serve the function of merely capturing the patient’s teeth before and after a procedure.

387    To refute this view, the Accused adduced the following three pairs of radiographs, marked as exhibits D16, D17 and D18, to show that it is possible to take successive radiographs that are nearly indistinguishable:[note: 662]

(a)     D16 was a pair of radiographs taken by the Accused of Dr Leo Fung’s teeth, which the Defence claimed were taken 15 minutes apart.[note: 663]

(b)     D17 was a pair of radiographs taken by Dr Leo Fung of a volunteer’s teeth, which the Defence claimed were taken five minutes apart.[note: 664]

(c)     D18 was a pair of radiographs taken by the Accused of a volunteer’s teeth, which the Defence claimed were taken 18 minutes apart.[note: 665]

388    I have reproduced the images of the three pairs of radiographs below. One sees that the images in each pair look very similar to each other, despite each pair having been taken with an interval of five or more minutes in between:

389    Before commenting on these three pairs of radiographs, it is necessary to set out the background to how they came into being. The Defence embarked on the exercise of creating these radiographs only midway through the trial, after Dr Loh had been released from the stand, and only on the third day of Dr Andrew Tay’s cross-examination. When the Defence served the notice under s 231 of the Criminal Procedure Code 2010 (2020 Rev Ed) (“CPC”) on the Prosecution to adduce these three pairs of radiographs, the Prosecution strenuously objected, raising the following points:

(a)     Given the provenance and purpose of these radiographs, they could very easily have been created and adduced much earlier.

(b)     Dr Loh testified extensively about how the similarities displayed by the photographs in the forgery charges led inexorably to the conclusion that they were reproduced from the alleged source radiographs. Yet, the Defence had waited until Dr Loh was released from the stand and no longer available to testify, before applying to adduce these radiographs.

The Prosecution thus argued that it was prejudiced by the Defence’s drip-feeding of evidence.

390    Notwithstanding these protests, the Defence offered no explanation for why the three pairs of radiographs were being tendered so late in the day, save to say that the Prosecution still had one other expert left on the stand, ie, Andrew Tay, who could comment on the radiographs. The Prosecution countered that the testimonies of both their experts was not fungible −the three pairs of radiographs thus ought to have been put to Dr Loh for his views.[note: 666] After hearing arguments from both sides, I allowed the Defence to adduce D16, D17 and D18, while giving the Prosecution liberty to recall Dr Loh if it saw fit.

391    Having carefully examined D16, D17 and D18, I conclude that they do not advance the Defence’s case to any tangible degree.

392    Firstly, the three pairs of radiographs were taken in a non-clinical setting. These were not shots of actual patients’ teeth before and after real-life procedures. Rather, they were taken within an engineered environment, with the specific objective of demonstrating to the court that successive radiographs can look the same. Neither IO Beverly nor the Prosecution experts were present when these radiographs were taken. In fact, no representative of the Prosecution was around during the shooting of these radiographs. The Defence also did not call the volunteer, whose mouth was the subject of D17 and D18, to testify about the instructions given to him during the shooting of the radiographs and how the shoot was done. The Prosecution thus suggested to the Accused in cross-examination that these radiographs were taken with the specific goal of showing the reproducibility of successive radiographs. He did not deny this:[note: 667]

Q:    And as proofs of technique, these radiographs were taken for the express purpose of making them as similar as possible, correct?

A    Uh, I aimed in the same area, yah.

The Accused also conceded that this exercise was not something that would have been done under normal clinical settings.[note: 668]

393    Given the circumstances under which the radiographs were taken, I agree with the Prosecution that the radiographs were “carefully designed experiments” [note: 669] which had no bearing on how radiographs are actually taken under routine clinical settings. This conclusion is buttressed by the fact that a perusal of the radiographs that were taken under routine clinical settings, found in P3, shows that none of the radiographs therein (particularly when comparing those shot at the same visit by the patient) displayed the same level of similarity as that seen in D16, D17 and D18. It was put to the Accused that no pair of radiographs, whether in P3 or in any of his other patient cards for that matter, displayed this level of similarity. The Accused did not deny this.[note: 670] Even the Defence expert Dr Firdaus agreed that the radiographs in P3 were more reflective of radiographs captured in routine clinical settings, while D16 to D18 were not something ordinarily seen in routine procedures.[note: 671]

394    The Defence suggests that even in routine procedures, dentists do attempt to reproduce the exact same angle of capture when shooting successive radiographs. The Defence highlights[note: 672] that Dr Loh, “admitted that when he takes radiographs of implants, he tries as much as possible to get similar and standardised radiographs”. In couching Dr Loh’s evidence in this fashion, the Defence relies on the section of Dr Loh’s testimony where he explained how successive radiographs of an implant may be taken over a period, to see if the bone level has receded vis-à-vis the implant threads. I alluded to this at paragraph 361 above. However, that exercise of taking a time series of radiographs to check for receding bone levels over time has no relevance to any of the photographs in the forgery charges, where the underlying radiographs were all purportedly taken on the same day, interposed only by the dental procedure which the radiographs purportedly sought to depict.

395    Secondly, the three pairs of radiographs in D16, D17 and D18 were not the only radiographs taken in the exercise. According to the Defence, between three to five shots were taken to generate each of the three pairs:[note: 673]

(a)     To generate the radiographs in D16, five shots were taken.[note: 674]

(b)     To generate the radiographs in D17, three shots were taken.[note: 675]

(c)     To generate the radiographs in D18, four shots were taken.[note: 676]

Clearly, as within each of the three sets of radiographs above, only the pair that most resembled each other had been selected for the court’s perusal. The Defence did not see fit to tender the remaining radiographs in each of the three sets, nor explain what variability in appearance those other radiographs displayed. A court could not be faulted for drawing the inference that if those radiographs had been tendered, they would not have shown the same degree of similarity as the pair of radiographs which had ultimately been cherry-picked from each of the three sets.

396    More importantly, this exercise showed that even in a non-clinical setting that had been engineered to produce similar-looking radiographs, the Defence still had to take multiple radiographs of the same site (up to five in the case of D16), before arriving at a pair of images where the degree of similarity was sufficiently satisfactory to the Defence. This only serves to bolster the inference that in routine clinical settings, where the focus is on the execution of surgical procedures involving real life patients (rather than on taking similar-looking radiographs), cases of radiographs with such striking similarity would be nothing short of rare.

397    I thus place very little weight on the radiographs in D16, D17 and D18.

398    I should also add that the radiographs in D16 to D18 only purported to show how the anatomical structures in the patient’s mouth may be reproduced across two radiographs in similar fashion. They do not explain how, as in this case, scratches and other defects on the radiograph film, or uniquely shaped artefacts captured in the imaging process that were clearly not part of the patient’s anatomy, could be reproduced with remarkable similarity (in terms of size, shape, and positioning) across multiple radiographs.

Objectivity of the experts in opining on the forgery issue

399    Given that the conclusions above rest heavily on the expert testimonies, it is necessary for me at this juncture to address parties’ submissions on whether the experts had been objective in their analyses of the forgery issue. The Defence contends that both Prosecution experts, Dr Andrew Tay and Dr Loh, lacked objectivity. The Prosecution, for its part, levels various criticisms of its own at the testimonies of the Defence experts.

400    My conclusions on these submissions are summarized as follows:

(a)     Neither Dr Andrew Tay nor Dr Loh lacked objectivity. I accept their opinions about the compelling inferences to be drawn from the striking similarities in key features between the photographs in the forgery charges and the alleged source radiographs.

(b)     I harbour doubts about Dr Leo Fung’s objectivity and do not find him to be a reliable expert witness.

(c)     While I have no reason to doubt the integrity or objectivity of Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus, I find their expert evidence to be of little help, in large part because of the manner in which their terms of reference had been structured.

401    I elaborate on my reasoning below.

Dr Andrew Tay

402    The Defence contends that Dr Andrew Tay was not an independent expert, given that he was involved in the investigations conducted pursuant to MoH’s audit that ultimately led to charges being brought against the Accused. The Defence contends that Dr Andrew Tay suffered from confirmation bias and had a “vested interest” that the court upholds the conclusions of the audit exercise.[note: 677] The Defence alleges that this led to Dr Andrew Tay falling into the trap of becoming an advocate for the Prosecution’s cause[note: 678] and was, effectively, an accuser who had already formed a view against the Accused.[note: 679]

403    As a preliminary observation, the issue of whether Dr Andrew Tay’s involvement in the audit created a pre-existing bias was not something raised to him during cross-examination. In fact, his prior involvement in the audit did not even appear to be a live issue until after closing submissions were filed.

404    In any case, I find the Defence’s allegations of bias to ring hollow. The Defence is unable to point me to any authority imposing a general bar against experts who were consulted during the investigations stage from being called by the investigating party as an expert witness at trial. The Defence submits:[note: 680]

… an individual who was involved in investigations into a matter should not subsequently be called as an expert witness to give an opinion on matters of his or her own expertise. Where this is done, there arises the tendency for the said individual to make use of factual information obtained in the course of the investigations as a basis for his / her expert opinion, thereby blurring the distinction between an expert and a factual witness.

405    In support of this submission, the Defence cites the case of The Dream Star [2018] 4 SLR 473 (“The Dream Star”). However, that case reveals no such proposition, as contended for by the Defence. The Dream Star involved a collision between the plaintiff’s vessel and another ship. The plaintiff had then appointed the Master of the plaintiff’s ship to investigate the collision. During his investigations, the Master interviewed the crew of the plaintiff’s ship, who gave their accounts of the collision. At the trial of the in rem action brought by the plaintiff, the Master was called by the plaintiff as an expert witness. In proffering his expert testimony, the Master referred to the factual evidence which he had gleaned while investigating the collision. This included the accounts relayed to him by the crew of the plaintiff’s ship, which the Master then used as the factual basis for his expert views. This was notwithstanding that the crew members had already recanted some aspects of their factual accounts, both in their affidavits of evidence-in-chief and in their oral testimonies at trial. It was against this backdrop that Belinda Ang J (as she then was) held (at [32]-[34]):

32    … an expert who was involved in the investigation of a marine casualty is best deployed as a witness of fact to testify on matters relating to the investigations, and this approach keeps the investigator’s role separate from the person who is an expert witness giving opinion on matters of his or her expertise …

33    … If the master mariner who investigated the marine casualty is called to testify in his capacity as an investigator, he is, as I have stated, treated as a witness of fact. In this case, [the plaintiff’s and defendant’s experts] were called to testify as expert witnesses, and their respective duty is to assist the court on matters within his expertise irrespective of who instructed or called them to testify as the expert: O 40A r 2 of the Rules of Court (Cap 322, R 5, 2014 Rev Ed).

34    In his capacity as an expert witness, [the plaintiff’s expert] was tasked to express his opinion on what has been embodied in the written evidence of the crew or adduced in the oral testimony of the crew at trial. It was thus patently wrong of him to refer to what the crew told him during an interview that was conducted … as though it was factual evidence that could be introduced in court through his testimony as an expert witness. By way of illustration, [the plaintiff’s expert] insisted that the [plaintiff’s vessel] had sounded five short blasts on her whistle because that was what the bridge team of [the plaintiff’s vessel] had told him previously, even though he was reminded by [defence counsel] that the evidence of the bridge team’s AEICs and oral testimony in court was that only one loud blast was sounded. In introducing factual evidence which was not found in the written or oral evidence of the bridge team, [the plaintiff’s expert] blurred his two separate roles, and inappropriately made use of hearsay information as a factual basis for an expert opinion …

[emphasis added]

406    One thus sees that the factual matrix in The Dream Star is specific, with no bearing on the present facts. Dr Andrew Tay was never involved as an investigator in this case. He merely gave his expert opinion on the photographs obtained during the audit and this had in turn triggered the investigations, which were conducted by the police and not by him. There is nothing in The Dream Star to support the Defence assertion that an expert in Dr Andrew Tay’s position cannot continue acting for the Prosecution as an expert at trial and relaying to the court the same opinion which he had relayed to MoH’s auditors. In fact, the court in The Dream Star held (at [33]) to the contrary:

Oftentimes, the person who investigated the casualty is subsequently called as an expert witness as there are time and cost savings to be enjoyed by the party concerned. Generally, there is no bar to such a person’s appointment as an expert witness save that the party should disclose his expert’s earlier role as investigator. [emphasis added]

407    Despite raising The Dream Star as an authority for the claim that Dr Andrew Tay should not be regarded as an impartial witness, the Defence simultaneously tries to distinguish this authority by contending pointing out that The Dream Star involved civil proceedings, where time and cost considerations may necessitate an expert involved in the investigation stage being called as an expert witness at trial. The Defence argues that such considerations are not at play in the present case, where the Prosecution did not reap any cost saving from calling Dr Andrew Tay.[note: 681] This is a rather muddled argument. The Defence appears to be suggesting that experts involved in the investigation stage must be treated as biased unless it can be shown that calling them as experts results in cost savings. However, it is difficult to see how the saving of costs renders an expert any less partial if he is partial to begin with.

408    The Defence also argues that it was not enough for Dr Andrew Tay to simply have disclosed his role in the audit (which he did). The Defence contends that either Dr Andrew Tay or the Prosecution ought to have:

made an honest admission to the court and state on record that there was a potential conflict of interest in calling him as an expert witness. [emphasis added]

The Defence argues that the failure to do this meant that effectively, no disclosure of Dr Andrew Tay’s potential conflict of interest was made. [note: 682] Again, I find this submission difficult to follow. The Prosecution had already disclosed the fact of Dr Andrew Tay’s involvement in the audit. What the Defence appears to be demanding for is that the Prosecution goes further and explicitly concedes, for the record, that Dr Andrew Tay was in a position of potential conflict because of his involvement with the audit. The Defence has not explained the basis for this demand. Once the fact of Dr Andrew Tay’s involvement in the audit had been fully disclosed, it must surely have been open to the Prosecution to contend that this prior engagement was not sufficient to give rise to any potential conflict of interest, just as it was open to the Defence to contend that it was.

409    Secondly, the Defence claims that Dr Andrew Tay had been “pugnacious and stubborn in responses for the sake of it”.[note: 683] The following are some examples which the Defence cites:

(a)     In exploring if a patient could be unaware that a bone harvest was being carried out, Dr Andrew Tay was asked if the trauma suffered at a harvest site would be lower in cases where only a small amount of bone is harvested. Dr Andrew Tay had replied “Any bone graft is traumatic”. The Defence complains that this response was ‘glib’.[note: 684]

(b)     To show that a patient may be unaware of a drill being used, the Defence suggested to Dr Andrew Tay that the patient may not hear the drill if it is run at a lower speed. Dr Andrew Tay responded that he did not know of any dentist who would run his instrument at a lower speed just to hide the sound. The Defence argues[note: 685] that Dr Andrew Tay, by failing to simply agree or disagree, showed a penchant for attacking the question’s premise without answering it.

(c)     When Dr Andrew Tay was asked if he had come across patients with differing degrees of sensitivity and pain tolerance, he replied that it was “hard to quantify”. The Defence queries why Dr Andrew Tay had to give qualified answers to what were in effect “straightforward, uncontroversial” questions.[note: 686]

(d)     When Dr Andrew Tay was asked whether patients tend to forget successful treatments and remember complications and failures, he replied “Generally, yes”. Again, the Defence complains that Dr Andrew Tay should have just given an unqualified ‘yes’.[note: 687]

410    A reader running through this list of objections would not be blamed for viewing them as bordering on the petty. An expert commenting on an area of science is entitled to preface his responses with the necessary qualifiers, particularly if an absolute answer in the positive or negative risks giving an incomplete picture. This does not, in and of itself, make the expert pugnacious, stubborn or glib, as alleged by the Defence.

411    In summary, I do not think that Dr Andrew Tay’s involvement in the audit gave rise to any presumption of bias. Furthermore, his testimony did not betray the lack of objectivity which the Defence seeks to attach to it.

Dr Loh

412    The Defence also attack Dr Loh’s credibility as an expert witness, saying that he was “afflicted with partiality” and adopted the “unrelenting view” that the photographs placed before him were identical.[note: 688]

413    In advancing this argument, the Defence highlights the following portion of Dr Loh’s cross-examination, where he dismissed Defence Counsel’s question as frivolous. Specifically, the Defence was asking Dr Loh about the shape of the tooth #37 root in P3(2)C, highlighting how the outline of the root there was much clearer as compared to that in photographs B36(3) and 36(4), which were blurrier. The Defence was seeking to use this difference to suggest that B36(3) and B36(4) must have captured different radiographs. Dr Loh disagreed, saying that the images were from the same source.[note: 689] When the Defence pressed this point, saying that the blurriness in B36(3) and B36(4) suggested that they were photographs of radiographs that were less clear than P3(2)C,[note: 690] Dr Loh responded as follows:[note: 691]

the purple tree in the forest is there, the elephant in the room is there, the unique signature is there, it’s the same photograph. You know, Sir, you---you are taking me through so much frivolous thing. I---I don’t know- … how to take this--- …. But … the point is that you are throwing things at me that are so random and so frivolous. I already told you that the purple tree in the forest is there, the signature is there, the elephant in the room is there, but you’re still throwing frivolous things at me. That’s what I’m trying to tell you. …. Your … your client is in no position to interpret radiograph like that. This kind of quality to the detail that you’re talking about. You’re talking about bone marrow spaces, trabeculae pattern. For that kind of interpretation, you need very good quality radiograph. You are showing me 2 blur---you, yourself, also said blur pictures, and you’re talking about trabeculae pattern, bone marrow pattern. You get what I’m saying? It’s so frivolous and---and so nonsensical, seriously.

[emphasis added]

The Defence raises this exchange as an instance where Dr Loh refused to give heed to the differences highlighted by the Defence, brushing them away as “frivolous” or “nonsensical” and going so far as to characterise the Defence’s questions as not carefully considered.688

414    To understand what led to this riposte by Dr Loh, the backdrop to the exchange needs to be set out for context. As explained above, the Defence’s strategy at trial was to point to numerous instances where features and appearances looked different as between the ‘before’ photograph and the ‘after’ photograph, as well as between these photographs on the one hand, and the alleged source radiograph on the other. The Defence sought to rely on these differences to suggest that the photographs captured separate radiographs that were different from the alleged source radiograph. Dr Loh’s response to this strategy, as was Dr Andrew Tay’s, was that the differences raised by the Defence could be explained away by the occurrence of reprographic errors during capture or development of the photographs. In Dr Loh’s view, what was more compelling was (to use Dr Loh’s words) the “elephant in the room” or the “purple tree in the forest”. These were the anatomical structures that had been reproduced with such striking similarity (in terms of shape and positioning) that they could not be explained, as well as those features that were clearly not part of the anatomical context (eg, physical defects on the radiograph film) that had inexplicably been replicated across multiple images. To get Dr Loh to capitulate on his position, the Defence’s approach to cross-examination often went along the following lines:

(a)     Highlight the differences which the Defence perceived to exist as between the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs, before eliciting a response from Dr Loh as to each of those differences.
