(b)     Highlight the differences which the Defence perceived to exist as between the ‘before’ and ‘after’ photographs on the one hand, and the alleged source radiograph on the other, before eliciting a response from Dr Loh as to each difference.

In going through (b), the Defence would on occasion traverse the exact same feature that had already been canvassed in (a). An instance of this is seen in how the Defence tried to suggest to Dr Loh that the bite plate in B35(1) appeared closer in perspective than the bite plate in B35(2).[note: 692] Dr Loh explained that this could have been due to differences in magnification during the process of photographing the radiograph.[note: 693] The next day, Defence Counsel returned to this feature again, this time suggesting to Dr Loh that the bite plate in B35(2) appeared closer than the bite plate in P3(1)A.[note: 694] Again, Dr Loh had to repeat his explanation.[note: 695]

415    This manner of questioning, while seemingly methodical, meant that Dr Loh had to keep reiterating his response that the focus ought to be on those striking similarities that could not be explained away, as opposed to the multitude of small differences which could be explained by the operation of reprographic errors. It was against this backdrop of having to keep repeating the same explanation, over the course of three days of cross-examination,[note: 696] that Dr Loh on occasion grew impatient and made comments about the cross-examination questions being frivolous. The following comment from Dr Loh summed up his perspective:[note: 697]

… in fairness to your client, I’m interested in truth as well. When I pointed out to you similari---similarities, I’m talking about a big, big elephant in the room that nobody can---can deny, right? And I point out to you 2 or 3 items. That is about it which nobody can deny. I can also do like you, radiograph A and B, you see this little black thing here? It’s same here, there’s a little black thing---there’s a little grey thing, there’s a little grey thing. I can go on like that for 10 days, 100 days, the same thing, alright? What I point out to you in terms of similarities, you are not denying, right, in terms of the elephant in the room. But what you are pointing out to me are so frivolous. You say “yes”, I say “no”, how---I mean where do we end from here?

416    To move things along, I had asked the Defence to consider if it could, when posing cross-examination questions, bunch those similar features within the same photograph into a single question, thereby reducing repetition.[note: 698] Defence Counsel had, to his credit, agreed and this resulted in the subsequent questions moving at a slightly faster pace. On his part, Dr Loh also appeared to recognise that his responses under cross-examination could have been better tempered as he had, upon finally being released from the witness stand, taken it upon himself to apologise to Defence Counsel for any offense that might have been caused.[note: 699]

417    While it is one thing to say that Dr Loh could have shown a little more tolerance under the grind of what may have seemed like endlessly repetitious cross-examination questions, it is quite another to unthinkingly attribute any manifestations of impatience to bias. The court bears the onus of scrutinizing the expert’s opinion to see if it has indeed been tainted by lack of objectivity. In engaging in that scrutiny, I find Dr Loh’s reasoning (about focusing on the striking similarities in key features, rather than on the multitude of minor differences) to resonate with logic and good sense, particularly given the multiple variables impacting on the angulation of the X-ray beam and the inexplicability of non-anatomical features (such as scratches and indentations on the radiograph film) being replicated across different radiographs. Dr Loh’s irritability on the stand did not betray any lack of objectivity that would vitiate his reasoning on this critical point.

418    To further attack Dr Loh’s objectivity,[note: 700] the Defence refers to a portion of the Transcripts where Dr Loh seemingly told Defence Counsel how to phrase the cross-examination question:[note: 701]

So, what I’m saying is that before you ask me that question, shouldn’t you respectfully asking this, should you not have checked the print first- ... before you ask that---… question? I’m just--- saying that the questions don’t seem to be considered carefully before they are posed to me.

At first blush, this might appear like a somewhat impetuous retort from the witness stand. However, the Defence’s submission fails to lay the context to Dr Loh’s response. The Defence was trying to establish that the photographs B37(3) and B37(4) were different, on account of differences in clarity with which the implant threads had been captured in the image. It was the Defence’s case that B37(3) captured the threads more sharply than B37(4). This difference was raised to advance the Defence’s theory that both photographs came from different source radiographs. In raising this difference, Defence Counsel had directed Dr Loh’s attention not to the actual photographs B37(3) and B37(4), but to A4-sized printouts of the scanned images of B37(3) and B37(4).[note: 702] Dr Loh had initially agreed that the image of B37(3) was more focused than the image of B37(4).[note: 703] However, when he subsequently looked at the actual exhibits, ie, the two photographs themselves, he realised that the image of the threads in the photograph B37(4) was clear and not less defined than in B37(3) after all.[note: 704] It was against this backdrop that Dr Loh complained that the Defence Counsel should have first checked the photographs (being the actual exhibits) before posing the question, rather than misdirecting Dr Loh’s attention to differences in image quality between the A4-sized printouts. While these printouts (being A4-sized) were larger and thus easier to read that the actual photographs (which were rather tiny −B37(3) and B37(4) each spanned only about 5cm in length), they were still merely reproductions of the real thing.

419    In my view, Dr Loh’s consternation on this point was not unfounded. In asking Dr Loh to comment on the differences between B36(3) and B36(4), the Defence ought to have focused his attention on the exhibits themselves, rather than on second-hand copies of these exhibits, particularly when the prevalence of reprographic errors was such a major issue at trial.

420    Ultimately, I have not accepted Dr Loh’s testimony in its entirety. As explained at paragraph 288 above, I did not feel sufficiently assured (given the conflicting expert views) in accepting his opinion that bone graft granules in the aftermath of an ABG can never appear as floating dots in a radiograph. However, the choice of whether to accept an expert’s testimony is not a binary one −the court is entitled to accept some parts of an expert’s evidence while not accepting others: Armstrong v Quest at [92]. I thus accept Dr Loh’s testimony about the compelling inferences to be drawn from the striking similarities between the photographs in the forgery charges and the alleged source radiographs. In my view, Dr Loh’s testimony did not betray any lack of objectivity that would have merited rejection of his opinions.

Dr Leo Fung

421    If I have any doubts about the objectivity of the expert testimonies at all, it is in relation to that of the Defence expert Dr Leo Fung.

422    For all intents and purposes, Dr Leo Fung was an employee of the Accused. [note: 705] He held a conditional registration as a dentist in Singapore and, as such, was unable to practice in his own clinic. He could only practice as an employee of a clinic, under the supervision of two registered dentists who would submit reports about his performance to the Singapore Dental Council every six months. The continuation of Dr Leo Fung’s conditional registration would depend on his supervising dentists providing favourable reports.[note: 706] Pursuant to this, Dr Leo Fung worked at the Accused’s clinic,[note: 707] where both his supervising dentists were also employed.[note: 708] The clinic was wholly owned by the Accused,[note: 709] who was its sole owner and sole director.[note: 710] In that capacity, the Accused was the person-in-charge at the clinic[note: 711] and had the final executive say in the clinic’s matters.[note: 712] Against that backdrop, the Prosecution asks that Dr Leo Fung’s testimony be viewed with circumspection.[note: 713]

423    As evidence of Dr Leo Fung’s lack of objectivity, the Prosecution contends that he had strayed beyond the remit of what an expert is to do, by overtly advocating for the Accused.[note: 714] Specifically, Dr Leo Fung had testified as follows:[note: 715]

Your Honour, can I make a comment on X-rays? Okay, um, because I’ve had an opportunity to really review some of these X-rays that I think are going to be presented, but the--- there’s---there’s a few---there’s---there’s a---a lot of problems of grave concern to me in terms of the X-rays that are being used right now in Court. And …in my years of experience, when you have images that are of … poor photographic quality, ones that are different sized, … and also, images that are very poor quality for diagnosing, uh, diseases or any issues, um, we start to have a---some grave concerns about that. So, three things are, size of the images, second is the---the---the diagnostic quality of the X-rays, and the third is the quality of the photocopying of the images. So, to put it in perspective, uh, if I were to take these X-rays and do a presentation in front of my colleagues of a thousand people, I think a lot of people will be laughing at me, okay. And then if I bring that to a second level, and I take these radiographs, and I want to use it as a qualifying exam and write an exam or send these to my colleagues, I will most likely fail drastically. And now, if I take it up to a higher level and I’m using this in a Court of Law and it’s going to determine the freedom of an individual, I would--- the bar has to be set very high. So, this is something that I need to convey to you, because that is something that---I mean, as---as somebody who’s trying to be objective in looking at this, you know, would raise his point to you. So, I just want to let you know that I’m looking at these X-rays with a caveat, if I’m using the term in proper context.

[emphasis added]

424    I agree with the Prosecution that Dr Leo Fung had strayed beyond his remit as an expert, whose primary duty is owed to the court. I am reminded of the caution sounded in Ho Mei Xia Hannah v PP [2019] 5 SLR 978 (at [50]):

I agreed, further, that Dr Lee’s “recommendation” that the court look upon the appellant’s case with “great compassion” went beyond his remit as an expert. This follows from the Court of Appeal’s holding in Chia Kee Chen at [5] that experts are duty-bound to be neutral and independent, and to assist the court rather than to advocate for a cause in a partisan manner, regardless of how sincerely the expert may sympathise with the cause of his client. The seeking of “compassion” goes beyond propounding and pressing home the medical opinion he sought to persuade the court to accept … . It was immaterial that Dr Lee’s recommendation for compassion related in part to the “origin [and] effects of her mental disorder”.

In like vein, Dr Leo Fung had advocated the Accused’s cause, by stating that if the photographs were used in a court of law, “the bar has to be set very high”, on account of the Accused’s liberty being at stake.

425    The Defence explains that Dr Leo Fung was not advocating for the Accused but merely “expressing what standard of proof is expected of him”.[note: 716] This explanation is unpersuasive. An expert is to give his opinion based on the facts. The requisite evidential threshold under the criminal standard of proof, as well as the question of whether the expert’s evidence suffices to cross that threshold, are matters that lie entirely within the sphere of responsibility of the court and not the expert. There is no reason for the expert to overtly state that the bar must be set very high, on account of the freedom of an individual, unless this is an admonition directed at the court.

426    There were also instances where Dr Leo Fung’s testimony bordered on the outlandish. For example, the Prosecution’s case in respect of B36(3) and B36(4) is that both photographs captured the radiograph P3(2)C, given that the shard-shaped indentation at P3(2)C was replicated in both photographs. In examination-in-chief, Dr Leo Fung tried to explain the replication by canvassing the possibility that multiple radiographs can sustain damage at the same spot.[note: 717] When I sought clarifications on how this could happen, Dr Leo Fung explained that the unused radiograph films could be stacked and placed in a drawer where they then get damaged, adding that “the percentage is very low, but it does happen”.[note: 718] When I asked him how to state how low the percentage would be, he said 1%, but repeated that “it does happen”.[note: 719] This point was then pursued by the Prosecution in cross-examination, where it was put to Dr Leo Fung that the 1% probability would have to be further compounded by the probability of the same defect being juxtaposed at the exact same location, vis-à-vis the other anatomical structures, in three separate radiographs. This meant that the resulting probability would be even lower, to which Dr Leo Fung agreed.[note: 720]

427    While I have no issues with an expert comprehensively laying out the different scientific explanations for the court’s consideration, it is quite another matter when the expert tries to explain away undisputed facts by canvassing possibilities which have close to zero chance of materialising. It would be nothing short of naïve to construe such explanations as being motivated by a desire to assist the court. In proffering the possibility of the same defect being replicated across multiple radiographs, despite knowing that the likelihood of such replication was virtually fanciful, Dr Leo Fung must have realised that his explanation served no purpose other than to cloud the waters.

428    Dr Leo Fung even tried to suggest that with local anaesthesia, the sense of proprioception is lost, despite this being at odds with the evidence (including that of the Accused). He eventually recanted this (see paragraph 178 above).

429    For these reasons, I view the Prosecution’s concerns about Dr Leo Fung’s partiality as well founded. I do not find him to be an objective expert.

Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus

430    As regards the two remaining Defence experts, Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus, I similarly find their expert opinions to be unhelpful. However, this is not because they personally exhibited any form of bias −I could see no basis to impugn their objectivity. Rather, it is because the Defence had fashioned the terms of reference for both these experts in a manner that shoe-horned their opinions to point in only direction. I explain this below.

431    As regards Dr Alfred Lau, his terms of reference did not require him to opine on the similarities that the photographs bore to the alleged source radiographs, notwithstanding that these similarities formed the lynchpin on which the forgery charges rested. As such, Dr Alfred Lau did not embark on a comparison of the similarities.[note: 721] Rather, his terms of reference required him to only focus on the differences between the images and explain them,[note: 722] with the result that he embarked on an exercise of spotting as many differences as possible.[note: 723] Further, in highlighting these differences, Dr Alfred Lau proceeded on the assumption that the photographs were faithful reproductions of the radiographs which they purported to capture,[note: 724] despite authenticity being at the very heart of the forgery charges. As such, there were multiple instances where the differences in features highlighted by Dr Alfred Lau (to show that the images were derived from different sources) ironically included the very embellishment which the forgery charge alleged to have been added by the Accused.[note: 725]

432    As for Dr Firdaus, he was engaged by the Defence to provide an opinion without being apprised of the precise scientific technical point that was in dispute at the trial.[note: 726] He was not even instructed about the precise areas within the photographs that were alleged to be forged.[note: 727] He was also not made aware of the conclusions arrived at by the Prosecution experts, nor the reasons underlying those conclusions,[note: 728] notwithstanding Dr Firdaus’ view that the opinions expressed by the Prosecution experts would have been relevant to his opinion and would have been helped him decide whether the photographs in question were forgeries.[note: 729] As a result, Dr Firdaus’ analysis did not focus on the unique features that had been replicated across the relevant images, which the Prosecution now relies upon to establish the forgery charges.[note: 730]

433    The terms on which Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus had been engaged cohered with the Defence’s strategy, which was to highlight every dissimilar dot, line and shape, as well as every variation in contrast and brightness, to bolster the case that the images concerned came from different sources. That strategy had on occasion been pursued indiscriminately. By way of context, the photographs which were the subject of the forgery charges were all quite small −B35(1)-(3), B36(1)-(4) and B37(1)-(4) all spanned only about 5cm in length. To facilitate visualisation, parties had thus reproduced the images of the photographs, enlarged them and printed the enlarged images on A4-sized paper. However, in the case of B36(3), the process of reproducing the photograph’s image inadvertently led to the appearance of a white dot (under tooth #35) in the soft copy image that was not on the physical photograph. Correspondingly, the A4-sized printout of the image of B36(4) also bore that white dot:

To show that the photographs B36(3) and B36(4) were derived from different source radiographs, the Defence raised a slew of differences in features between B36(3) and B36(4). One of the features that was repeatedly raised to the court, which the Defence put forth as an example of a feature appearing in B36(3) but not B36(4), was the white dot.

434    When cross-examining Dr Loh, Defence Counsel had referred to the A4-sized printout of B36(3) and pointed to the white dot as “another point of dissimilarity”. At that juncture, I had paused the cross-examination to look at the actual photograph. That was when I saw that the white dot, while on the A4-sized printout of the image of B36(3), was not on the photograph itself. I highlighted this to Defence Counsel who, after examining the actual photograph, agreed that the white dot was absent in B36(3). Defence Counsel also conceded that the white dot had shown up on the A4-sized printout because of reprographic error:[note: 731]

Q

Okay, in B36, page 3, below the tooth 35, there is a white speck which is absent from B36,--- … page 4. … This is the contrasting between B36, page 3 and B36, page 4 below the tooth 35. There is a white speck in B36, page 3 which is absent from B36, page 4.

A

Absent?

Q

It’s another point of dissimilarity.

Court:

Hang on a minute. Let me take B36(3). … The actual B36(3) photo. Can you show me where the white speck is?

DC:

Your Honour, is posing the question to [the witness]?

Court:

To you.

DC:

To me? Oh, okay.

Court:

That is B36(3). … There is no white dot based on my observation.

DC:

I--- …I will--- … pass, Your Honour. …

Court:

because it looks to me--- … like in preparing.

Foo:

This could be well a---well be a genuine reprographic error.

[emphasis added]



Following this, the Defence abandoned its line of questioning on the white dot.

435    Subsequently, when the Defence was cross-examining the next Prosecution expert, Dr Andrew Tay on B36(3), Defence Counsel again tried to pose questions on the white dot, notwithstanding my having previously disabused the Defence of the misconception that the white dot was there:[note: 732]

Q

… what is the difference in your view between the white spot here and---and the white spot in B36, page 4?

A

That’s quite easy.

DPP:

Your Honour, may I make an observation? …

 

[Witness was asked to step outside the courtroom]

DPP

… Your Honour will recall that my learned friend was asking Dr. Tay about white speck at the bottom left-hand corner of page 36(3)--- … which is … --- absent in (4).

Court:

That’s right.

DPP:

My learned friend asked the same questions of Dr. Loh at which point, my notes say at least that you referred to the originals and ultimately, the question was withdrawn. So, I wonder if my learned friend is taking a different tack with Dr. Tay. And if he is, then why?

DC:

Now, Your Honour, the---the question speak for itself, Dr. Tay is a very learned and erudite person. If he requests to look at the original of the image of the radiograph as in B36, page 4 or the original radiograph of any other thing, I certainly have no objections.

Court:

Was it not established during the questioning of Dr. Loh that the white spot was absent from the original photograph in B36(3)?

DC:

Forgive me, Your Honour, I---I can’t really recall, I---I s---I stand guided. I---I will go along with Your Honour’s recollection.

Court

This is not a case where---well if he wants to ask for the photograph, he can very well ask for it. And if he asks for it and he had taken a look, he will see that the white speck is absent. I don’t think that’s how the fact-finding process should be done, I mean, if we’ve already established that it’s absent and that is the truth, we have to go by the truth. …

DC:

Understand, Your Honour. May I just confirm this point with my co-Counsel? …

 

…

 

Most grateful, Your Honour. I think all parties are in consensus that is missing from the original image of the radiograph as---is represented in B36 page 3, I will withdraw that question and I will go on to my next issue. …

[Witness returns to the court]

Q

Thank you very much, Dr. Tay, for the imposition of asking you to leave the Court whilst we engage in a discussion. Just to update Dr. Tay, all parties examined the actual original image of the radiograph as shown is B36(3) and we are of the consensus that the white speck that have I earlier asked you about underneath P35 tooth is actually a print error on my copy of B36 page 3, so I’ll withdraw that question and move on to the next proposition.

[emphasis added]



436    After this second correction, one would have thought that the misperception about the white dot was finally put to rest. Yet, when the Defence was called, Dr Leo Fung still listed this white dot as one of the differences:[note: 733]

Court:

So, going back to B36A page 3 annotation B, what do you wish to tell--- … Q this Court?

A

on page 3 of B36, uh, there’s a white dot on the photo print.

Witness:

Oh, Your Honour, may I look at that? Just to confirm that because---

Court:

Because again,--- … I don’t see it. Give me a minute.

Witness:

Okay.

Court:

I’ll just pass this to you.

Witness:

So, I stand corrected again, Your Honour, it’s not on that photo print.

[emphasis added]



One thus notes that this would have been the third time that the Defence’s attention was brought to the white dot not being there.

437    Despite the multiple corrections, when the Defence called Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus to testify, both these experts continued to list the white dot as one of the differences supporting the contention that both B36(3) and B36(4) were derived from different source. This observations was elicited during the examinations-in-chief of both Dr Alfred Lau[note: 734] (who surmised that the white dot might be a foreign body) and Dr Firdaus.[note: 735] Clearly, both experts were still basing their opinions on the images of B36(3) and B36(4) printed on A4-sized paper (which would have contained reprographic errors arising from capturing or printing of the images) rather than B36(3) and B36(4) themselves.

438    The shoddiness with which the Defence had instructed Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus was thus perplexing.[note: 736] It is objectionable enough that a party, in failing to properly take stock of the evidence adduced, leads the court on a wild goose chase. But that objectionability is taken to a whole new level when expert witnesses such as Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus are deployed to bark up a particular tree, after the party calling those experts has been shown (and has accepted), three times, that the tree is wrong. Even in their closing submissions, the Defence continued to portray this white dot as a point of difference between B36(3) and B36(4).[note: 737] This episode is a classic manifestation of how Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus had been engaged on terms that offered little assistance to the court in getting at the truth and, as in this case, lent them to giving opinions grounded on plainly false premises.

439    As an aside, the incident surrounding the white dot also serves as a real-life example of how differences in features and appearance can and do arise when images are reproduced. Paying no heed to the prospect of such reprographic errors carries the very real risk of every minor discrepancy taking a life of its own, spawning fruitless lines of inquiry.

440    Ultimately, when Dr Alfred Lau and Dr Firdaus were asked point blank whether they were able to support the Defence’s contention that the photographs were not forged, they candidly admitted that they were not. Specifically:

(a)     Dr Alfred Lau admitted that he had not formed any conclusion as to whether any of the photographs in the forgery charges were real or fake.[note: 738] When asked if he thought that the photographs were forged, his answer was noncommittal: “It was in my mind, it could be, it could be not.”[note: 739] In fact, Dr Alfred Lau stated that if what was needed was an opinion on whether the photographs came from the same radiograph, he was “not the expert to tell you that”.[note: 740] He was thus able to say if the photographs were forged, as he was not an expert on pictures.[note: 741]

(b)     As for Dr Firdaus, he stated that he was unable to express an opinion on whether the photographs in the forgery charges were derived from the alleged source radiographs,[note: 742] as his method of spotting the differences between the images was not suitable for determining if the photographs were derived from the radiographs in question.[note: 743]

441    Both experts also did not debunk the Prosecution experts’ methodology of focusing on the striking similarities in the shape and positioning of anatomical structures and on the replication of non-anatomical features such as physical defects on the radiograph film and artefacts.

Was it the Accused who forged the photographs?

442    To recapitulate, I am satisfied that the following seven photographs were forged, in the manner set out in the respective forgery charges: (a) B35(1); (b) B36(1); (b) B36(3); (c) B36(4); (d) B37(1); (e) B37(2) and (g) B37(3).

443    The next main issue to be addressed is whether it was it was the Accused (as opposed to someone else) who forged these seven photographs. The Defence argues that the Prosecution failed to show exactly how the forgeries were committed, and by what means,[note: 744] as no evidence was adduced to show how the Accused went about altering the photographs.[note: 745]

444    It is true that there was no evidence showing exactly how the Accused forged the photographs (eg, how the cutting and pasting was done), although I would expect it to be rare that direct evidence would be available in cases such as this. However, there was clear evidence, in the form of admissions within the Accused’s Long Statements, that it was he who prepared the forged photographs. The first Long Statement (B38) and second Long Statement (B39) were, respectively, recorded on the day of the raid (8 July 2015) and the day after the raid (9 July 2015). The Accused’s answers in both Long Statements were clear that it was he who prepared the photographs in the forgery charges:

(a)     In respect of B35(1)-(3), the Accused was asked who prepared the three photographs and he replied :”I prepared it”.[note: 746] When asked who labelled them with the patient’s name, tooth number and procedure date, he replied “I labelled them”.[note: 747] The Accused even described how he used Microsoft photo editor to label the photographs:[note: 748]

I used Windows photo editor. I opened the photo of the radiograph first, then I inserted text. I typed in the name, tooth number and date of procedure. And then I saved and printed them out on photo paper.

When asked when the three photographs were prepared, he said “I cannot remember when I made the photo prints” and “I should have made it after 14 April 2014”.[note: 749]

(b)     In respect of B36(1)-(4), the Accused was also asked about the four photographs, to which he replied: “I prepared them”[note: 750] and “I took them”.[note: 751] As to when they were taken, he said “nearer to the audit”.[note: 752] He likewise described how he used Microsoft photo editor to label of the photographs:[note: 753]

I used Windows photo editor. I opened the photo of the radiograph first, then I inserted text. I typed in the name, tooth number and date of procedure.

The Accused further explained how he saved the images, printed them out and cropped them:[note: 754]

Q 145

What do you do after inserting text?

A:

I saved the image back to the computer or back to the SD card. I then printed it out.

…

Q 148

How do you print out the photos of the radiograph after you insert the text?

A:

I will print it using the inkjet printers at the clinics or at home. I will print them on photo paper and then cut them out into the smaller squares.



(c)     In respect of B37(1)-(4), the Accused mentioned that it was his nurses who took the photographs.[note: 755] However, when asked who prepared these photographs, his response was “I prepared them”.[note: 756] He also said :”I labelled them”,[note: 757] again describing how he used Microsoft photo editor to do the labelling:[note: 758]

I labelled the photos of the analogue radiographs by inserting text to it using Microsoft photo editor. Then I print them out on photo paper and cut them.

445    The Accused nevertheless raises the following defences:

(a)     While not disputing the voluntariness of his Long Statements, the Accused contends that the relevant answers therein were phrased in too ambiguous a manner to be construed as an admission that he, and not his staff, prepared the photographs in the forgery charges.

(b)     The Defence witness, Ng Jin Jie, Kenn (DW6) (“JJ Ng”), affirmatively testified that it was he (and not the Accused) who prepared the photographs in the forgery charges.

(c)     The Defence witness, Loo Hwee Hoon (DW4), who was employed at the Accused’s clinic as practice manager during the relevant period, gave evidence about the clinic’s operations which, by the Defence’s calculations, showed that there was no window of opportunity for the Accused to embellish the soft copies of the images.

446    Having considered these defences, I conclude that:

(a)     The Accused’s Long Statements were unequivocal in laying responsibility for preparing the forged photographs squarely on the Accused.

(b)     JJ Ng’s testimony was a fabrication.

(c)     Loo Hwee Hoon’s testimony did not negate the position clearly reflected in the Accused’s Long Statements, ie, that it was the Accused who prepared the forged photographs.

I set out my reasons below.

Accuracy of the Accused’s Long Statements

447    The Defence does not dispute the voluntariness of the Accused’s Long Statements. However, it challenges their accuracy, particularly those portions where the Accused used the pronoun ‘I’ (eg, “I prepared” the photographs or “I labelled” them). The Defence contends that the Accused, in using this pronoun, intended to refer not just to himself but to his nurses and administrative or counter staff.[note: 759] This, argues the Defence, coheres with the operational reality, where the Accused had to focus on clinical work and had no time for administrative tasks such as preparing photographs, which were left to staff.[note: 760]

448    The Defence explains that the language in the Long Statements may have been imprecise, given how tired the Accused was at the time of their recording. Specifically, B38 was recorded on the day of the raid, ie, on 8 July 2015, while B39 was recorded on the day after the raid, ie, 9 July 2015. To show how exhausted the Accused was, the Defence highlights the following:

(a)     The police raided the Accused’s home on the morning of 8 July 2015 at 7am in the morning.[note: 761] The Accused only had about four to five hours of sleep,[note: 762] having gone to be at about 2 to 3am that morning.[note: 763] By the time recording of B38 commenced at 11.15am, he was feeling quite sleepy.[note: 764] He even reflected this in his answer to question 3 in B38, where he said that he was “quite sleepy”. Although the recording of B38 concluded at 7.52pm, the Defence’s case is that the Accused was given a cell only at 3 to 4am. Even then, he had to sleep on the cell floor, without any blanket.

(b)     As such, when the recording of B39 commenced at 10.30am on 9 July 2014, the Accused was even sleepier than before.[note: 765] He similarly reflected this in his answer to question 119 in B39, saying that he was “very sleepy” as he “slept very little last night”. The Accused claimed that by the time the recording of B39 ended, he was feeling “totally deflated” and “very exhausted”.[note: 766]

449    The Accused thus explained that as he was tired, his Long Statements may have contained lapses in detail.[note: 767] In his state of fatigue, he had used the word “I” because he found it a “mouthful to mention all the possible staffs at the moment”.[note: 768] He “wanted to finish up the statements and complete the interview” and he would “just answer” as he could not think very clearly.[note: 769]

450    I reject the Accused’s claim that he was exhausted to the point of not paying attention to the details in his Long Statements. Firstly, his Long Statements contained many of the Accused’s handwritten corrections to the typed words. To name some examples:

(a)     In B38, the Accused was asked at Question 3 whether he was feeling well enough to give the statement. The Accused’s typed answer recited “I am a little sleepy”. Subsequently, he struck out the word “little” and replaced it with the word “quite”.

(b)     In B39, the Accused was asked at Questions 154 and 158 why the photographs all bore the same angulation and tilt. His typed answers to both questions stated that “the patient must have sit at the same position when the two radiographs were taken”. Subsequently, he struck out the word “same” and replaced it with the word “similar”.

Evidently, the Accused was not too tired to ensure the accuracy of his replies.

451    As regards the Accused’s claim that it was too much of a “mouthful” to specifically mention the nurses handling the administrative tasks, this did not accord with his responses in the Long Statements, which included portions where the Accused added very specific details on his staff’s scope of responsibility. For example, Question 131 in B39 and the Accused’s answer thereto were typed out as follows:

Q 131:

Besides you, is there anyone else in the clinic that take photos of the analogue radiographs?

A:

I would instruct my nurses to take the photos for me.



The Accused subsequently amended his typed answer to include the following handwritten note:

Only the nurses do this currently. Usually Maria, Julie or Anita will do it.

452    Clearly, the Accused was very specific in conveying what his staff did or did not do, to the point of making handwritten corrections to his typed answers to spell out individual names. The Accused did not appear in any way deterred from listing the “mouthful” of names.

453    As regards the Accused’s claim that he had intended to refer to his staff when he used the word “I”, this ran counter to many portions of his Long Statements where he referred to the tasks performed by his staff and, in doing so, did not use the word “I” to refer to them. In fact, there were many instances where the Accused adroitly toggled between using the pronoun “I” and making specific references to his staff, switching from one to the other as and when the context changed. An example is seen in the following exchange in B38:

Q 86:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-002-005. Who prepared these radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’, ‘2’, ‘3’ and ‘4’?

A:

I prepared them.

Q 87:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-002-007 to 009. Who recorded, on this letter of certification, the procedures performed on Chong Moh Chin on 9 April 2014?

A:

Mdm Loo.

Q 88:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-002-007 to 009. Who signed on this letter of certification?

A:

I signed it.

Q 89:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-002-013. Who signed as the witness on this Medisave authorisation form?

A:

One of the nurses.

Q 90:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-002-011 to 012. Who submitted this ‘Universal Claim Form’ via the Medisave system to make Medisave claims?

A:

I submitted it.

[emphasis added]



The same attention to detail is seen in B39:

Q 163:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-003-005 . Who prepared these radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’, ‘2’, ‘3’ and ‘4’?

A:

I prepared them.

Q 164:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-003-007 to 009. Who recorded, on this letter of certification, the procedures performed on Neo Kheng Yew on 9 April 2014?

A:

Mdm Loo. She wrote out the letter of certification based on the Medisave claim that had been submitted by me.

Q 165:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-003-007 to 009. Who signed on this letter of certification?

A:

I signed it.

Q 166:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-003-013. Who signed as the witness on this Medisave authorisation form?

A:

One of the nurse.

Q 167:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-003 - 011 to 012. Who submitted this ‘Universal Claim Form’ via the Medisave system to make Medisave claims?

A:

I submitted it.

…

Q 203:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-001-005. Who prepared these radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’, ‘2’ and ‘3’?

A:

I prepared it.

Q 204:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-001-007 to 009 and SWH-001-010. Who recorded, on this letter of certification, the procedures performed on Chia Ching Choo Catherine on 14 April 2014?

A:

Mdm Loo.

Q 205:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-001-007 to 009 and SWH-001-010. Who signed on this letter of certification?

A:

I signed it.

Q 206:

I refer you to exhibit SWH-001-013. Who signed as the witness on this Medisave authorisation form?

A:

One of the nurses.

[emphasis added]



454    Clearly, the Accused was deliberate in his use of pronouns. His claim that he had used the word ‘I’ loosely just did not cohere with the flow of his Long Statements.

455    Furthermore, the suggestion that the task of preparing and printing the photographs were performed by the staff and not the Accused flies in the face of his very explicit answers in B39, to the effect that he performed some of the tasks at home:

Q 135:

What do you use to view the photos of the analogue radiographs inside the SD card?

A:

I use either the 2 laptops desktop and 1 laptop Hougang, or my desktop at home to view the photos.

…

Q 146:

Which computer did you use insert the text to the photos of the radiograph?

A:

Either the 2 laptops at Punggol or 1 desktop and 1 laptop Hougang, or my desktop at home.

…

Q 148

How do you print out the photos of the radiograph after you insert the text?

A:

I will print it using the inkjet printers at the clinics or at home. I will print them on photo paper and then cut them out into the smaller squares.

[emphasis added]



Clearly, for those tasks performed at the Accused’s home, these would have been performed by the Accused himself and not his staff, there being no suggestion of staff going to the Accused’s home to prepare the photographs.

456    The Defence also attacks the reliability of the Long Statements by highlighting how IO Beverly failed to comprehensively specify the subject matter of the investigations, prior to commencing the statement recording exercise.[note: 770] Specifically, the preamble to the Long Statements failed to contain keywords such as “MOH”, “Medisave”, “bone grafts” or “foreign body removal”, which the Defence argues would have given the Accused better context to the investigations. The Defence also takes issue with how IO Beverly failed to explicitly mention that she was investigating allegations of forgery,[note: 771] saying that this omission was compounded by the fact that the Accused was not shown colour copies of the photographs in the forgery charges, when the Long Statements were being recorded.[note: 772]

457    However, the Defence fails to articulate the prejudice which flowed from the alleged lack of specificity in the preamble to the Long Statements. There is none that I can see. The questions in the Long Statements quizzed the Accused extensively about why the photographs in the forgery charges looked the same. That must have given him an idea that their authenticity was in in issue, even if the word “forgery” was not explicitly stated. His responses categorically refuted any suggestion that the photographs might have been derived from the same source image, by highlighting differences between the photographs, or at least explaining the similarities. The Accused did this in respect of all the photographs that were the subject of the forgery charges. I set out below the relevant responses from the Accused in his Long Statement.

(a)     In respect of B35(1) and B35(2):

Q 229:

I refer you to SWH-001-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’ and ‘2’ show the same section?

A:

I don’t think they show the same section. I think ‘1’ is more towards the bottom right side.

Q 230:

I refer you to SWH-001-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘l’ and ‘2’ show the same angulation and tilt?

A:

I think are not the same. Tilt wise, I think the tooth 37 in ‘l’ is more upright.

[emphasis added]



(b)     In respect of B36(1) and (2):

Q 153:

I refer you to SWH-002-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’ and ‘2’ show the same section?

A:

I don’t think they show the same section. I think ‘1’ is closer to the left while lower than ‘2’.

Q 154:

I refer you to SWH-002-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’ and ‘2’ show the same angulation and tilt?

A:

The cone must have been positioned at the same height and the patient must have sit at the same position when the two radiographs were taken. [the Accused subsequently amended the reference to “the same position” by striking out “the same” and replacing it with “similar”]

[emphasis added]



(c)     In respect of B36(3) & (4):

Q 157:

I refer you to SWH-002-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘3’ and ‘4’ show the same section?

A:

I think the left bottom corner of ‘3’ and ‘4’ looks different.

Q 158:

I refer you to SWH-002-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘3’ and ‘4’ show the same angulation and tilt?

A:

Because it is the same patient’s jaw. The cone must have been positioned at the same height and the patient must have sit at the same position when the two radiographs were taken. [the Accused subsequently amended the reference to “the same position” by striking out “the same” and replacing it with “similar”]

[emphasis added]



(d)     In respect of B37(1) and B37(2):

Q 192:

I refer you to SWH-003-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’ and ‘2’ show the same section?

A:

I don’t think they show the same section. ‘2’ is a bit more towards the left, the back of the teeth. ‘1’ is more towards the right.

Q 193:

If you were given the same patient, the same equipment and setup of your x-ray room, will you be able to reproduce a set of radiographs that show the exact same section as how you did for ‘1’ and ‘2’?

A:

Yes, I think it is possible for me to do so.

Q 194:

I refer you to SWH-003-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’ and ‘2’ show the same angulation and tilt?

A:

I don’t think they are the same. I think that ‘1’ is more slanted to the right.

[emphasis added]



(e)     In respect of B37(3) and B37(4):

Q 197:

I refer you to SWH-003-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘3’ and ‘4’ show the same section?

A:

I think they are not the same, I think ‘4’’ is more rotated downwards to the right.

Q 198:

I refer you to SWH-003-005. Explain why the radiograph photo prints labelled ‘3’ and ‘4’ show the same angulation and tilt?

A:

I think they are not the same. I think ‘4’ covers more towards the right side. [The Accused then added the line “Anyway, the photocopies are not very clear”]

[emphasis added]



458    Clearly, the Accused’s attention was drawn to the similarities between the photographs in the forgery charges. As seen from the last answer quoted above, he had even remarked about the photocopies of the photographs shown to him not being very clear. Yet, this did not stop him from disagreeing with the suggestion that the photographs were the same, as well as explaining the reasons for his position.

JJ Ng’s testimony

459    At the very end of the trial, the Defence served a notice on the Prosecution under s 231 CPC to call yet another witness, JJ Ng.

460    JJ Ng claimed that he was employed by the Accused for a short spell in 2014 (ie, the year when the MoH audit took place). He testified that he was likely the person who prepared the photographs that were the subject of the forgery charges. Specifically, he testified that while he could not be 100% sure:

(a)     B35(1)-(3) were “likely” to have been printed by him;[note: 773]

(b)     B36(1)-(4) were “very likely” to have been done by him;[note: 774] and

(c)     B37(1)-(4)[note: 775] were “very similar” to what he did.

JJ Ng explained the basis for his surmise, by pointing to the label inserted at the top of these photographs (containing the patient’s name, tooth number and date of procedure) and observing that these were in a font that was “almost identical” to what he used, although he could not be 100% sure.[note: 776] He also testified that for the task of preparing such photographs, the Accused told him that he had only employed JJ Ng and no one else.[note: 777] This strengthened JJ Ng’s conjecture that he was the one who prepared the photographs in the forgery charges.

461    The Defence thus submits that JJ Ng’s evidence has cast doubts on the Prosecution’s case that it was the Accused who prepared the photographs in the forgery charges. In doing so, the Defence asserts[note: 778] that JJ Ng was a “forthright” witness who candidly admitted to not being 100% sure that the photographs were prepared by him, venturing only to say that they were “very likely” to have been prepared by him. The Defence thus describes[note: 779] JJ Ng’s testimony as:

… strongly demonstrative of an honest witness who gave an unvarnished account of what he recalled. He did not embellish the facts for the purposes of enhancing the quality of his testimony.

By way of preliminary observation, it would be plain to even the most naïve observers that JJ Ng’s claim, to the effect that he was likely or very likely to have been the one who prepared the photographs, would (if accepted) have sufficed to muddy the link between the Accused and the provenance of the photographs. There was no need for JJ Ng to say that he was “100% sure” for his testimony to achieve that result. The fact that JJ Ng stopped short of saying that he was “100% sure”, attesting only that he was “very likely”, did not in my opinion add to the perception of his credibility.

462    Before assessing JJ Ng’s testimony proper, it is necessary to first set the backdrop to how JJ Ng came to work for the Accused:

(a)     Sometime in 2014, JJ Ng was working in various jobs, including as a mover and painter. In the hope of securing permanent employment, he posted his resume on the internet. This led to the Accused’s clinic calling him down.[note: 780]

(b)     JJ Ng turned up at the Punggol Field branch of the Accused’s clinic,[note: 781] where he filled out a form with his personal particulars, educational qualifications and work experience.[note: 782] Thereafter, JJ Ng was assigned to man the counter and answer phone calls,[note: 783] for which he would be paid $8-10 an hour.[note: 784]

(c)     After about three hours on the job, JJ Ng decided to quit as he felt ill-suited to his role manning the counter.[note: 785] The senior staff at the clinic relayed JJ Ng’s resignation to the Accused,[note: 786] who emerged from his clinic to speak to JJ Ng. The Accused looked at the personal particulars form that JJ Ng filled out earlier that day (which included his educational qualifications) and remarked to JJ Ng: “it’s such a waste, you know computer”.[note: 787] In making this comment, the Accused appeared to be referencing JJ Ng’s ‘O’ level examination results, which included a module on office administration with a Microsoft certificate[note: 788] −a qualification obtained more than 10 years before that.[note: 789]

(d)     The Accused thus asked JJ Ng if he was interested to do freelance work which JJ Ng could undertake at his own time.[note: 790] The Accused explained that the freelance job involved JJ Ng being given electronic copies of photographs, plus a document containing the patients’ particulars. JJ Ng was then supposed to:[note: 791]

(i)       check the electronic copies of the photographs against the patient’s particulars in the document;

(ii)       electronically edit the soft copies of the photographs by overlaying a label above the photographic image and inserting the patient’s particulars into the label; and

(iii)       print the edited images on photo paper, cut the printed photographs down to size and insert the same into small Ziplock sachets.

The Accused spent about half an hour explaining the job to JJ Ng,[note: 792] who agreed to take the job.

(e)     JJ Ng was then given an envelope containing an SD card, which in turn stored JPEG image files of patient radiographs, as well as Ziplock sachets for storing the printed photographs.[note: 793] He was also given a copy of exhibit B4, being the email from Ker Lai Sim informing the Accused’s clinic about the audit (referred to paragraph 231 above).[note: 794] B4 contained a two-page annex listing, inter alia, the names of the patients and the procedures they underwent.

(f)     JJ Ng then went about his task by opening the JPEG files and editing the images by inserting labels containing the patient’s name, the date of the procedure and the number of the tooth on which the procedure was performed. He then printed the edited image on photo paper, snipped the printed photographs down to size and inserted them into the Ziplock sachets.[note: 795]

(g)     Through the course of this freelance role, JJ Ng turned up at the Punggol Field branch for work for a total of about five times to collect and return the photographs[note: 796] (meaning that he went to the clinic another four more times after his first day of work). He also visited the Hougang branch four times.[note: 797] In total, JJ Ng prepared four sets of photographs: two from the clinic’s Punggol Field branch and two from the clinic’s Hougang branch.[note: 798]

463    During the entire span of his engagement with the Accused’s clinic in 2014, JJ Ng managed to speak to the Accused face-to-face only once.[note: 799]

464    In terms of remuneration, JJ Ng was paid $800 for each set of photographs that he prepared. Considering that each set of photographs contained about 10 or more patients, with three to four photographs per patient, there were about 40 photographs per set.[note: 800] This excluded those image files for which JJ Ng was unable to find the requisite details from the document containing the patient’s particulars – he would ignore those image files as it was not his job to search for the correct particulars.[note: 801] JJ Ng would take about two to three minutes to label each photograph, meaning that an entire set (of 40 photographs) could take about three to four hours. At $800 for the entire set, JJ Ng was thus effectively paid $200 per hour for this freelance job.[note: 802] This was a significant jump in the rate of remuneration −by about 20 times −from the hourly rate of $8-10 offered by the Accused’s clinic for JJ Ng’s previous stint manning the counter784 (from which he had resigned only after three hours).

465    During cross-examination, the Prosecution put to JJ Ng that his testimony, including his account of how he came to work for the Accused, was a lie.[note: 803] Now, this might have come across as a somewhat strongly worded put, especially when directed in open court. However, having scrutinized the evidence of JJ Ng, I find it difficult to fault the Prosecution for this.

466    Firstly, JJ Ng’s account of how he came to work for the Accused was nothing short of astonishing. According to JJ Ng, when he went to the Accused’s clinic for the first time, he quit only after three hours on the job. This would have given any would-be employer cause for pause. However, the Accused’s reaction was extraordinary. He went out of his way to persuade JJ Ng to take another job at the clinic. Not just any job, but one which carried a much heavier responsibility, ie, preparing documents with grave regulatory implications to the Accused personally, at a rate of remuneration that was 20 times that of the counter job which JJ Ng had just abruptly walked away from. There was no explanation for why the Accused was so eager to hire JJ Ng, given the latter’s lacklustre performance just three hours into the job. The Accused had even taken half an hour of his time to explain to JJ Ng what the new job entailed. I pause to note that this is also out of sync with the Accused’s prior testimony that he typically had a packed schedule of patients requiring him to work long hours, to the point that he left administrative tasks to his staff.[note: 804] More so in 2014, which the Accused recounted to be a particularly stressful year.[note: 805] The manner in which the Accused went out of his way to employ JJ Ng (to prepare the photographs) is even more baffling when one considers that this was the first time that both men met.

467    Secondly, JJ Ng’s evidence on his alleged role in preparing the photographs bore gaping cracks on several fronts:

(a)     JJ Ng surmised that the photographs forming the subject of the forgery charges were (to use his words) “very likely” to have been prepared by him. He justified his guess by pointing to how the size and spacing of the font used to label these photographs (to reflect the patient’s name, tooth number and date of procedure), as well as the cut of the photographs, were “almost identical to what I do”.[note: 806] This explanation is dubious. A visual inspection of the photographs shows that the font on the labels look entirely generic. JJ Ng did not explain what was so distinctive about the font as to allow him to conclude that the photographs were “almost identical to” the four sets of photographs that he had prepared for the Accused’s clinic, some eight years ago.

(b)     Furthermore, JJ Ng failed to properly demonstrate how he managed to glean the information necessary for populating the labels which he inserted into the photographs. To recapitulate, the label contained the patient’s name, the date of the procedure performed on the patient and the number of the tooth on which the procedure was performed. JJ Ng had initially claimed that he had used the list in B4 to glean the relevant details.[note: 807] However, this made no sense as the list of patients in B4 did not even reflect the tooth number.

As regards the gap in (b), JJ Ng was confronted with this and challenged to point to the section in B4 which allowed him to discern the relevant tooth number.[note: 808] He deflected this challenge by saying that the JPEG files did not just capture the image of the radiograph but also the image of handwritten notes containing the necessary details, at the side of the radiograph.[note: 809] Needless to say, this was a highly material detail that JJ Ng entirely omitted during his examination-in-chief, when he only attested[note: 810] to how he had used the particulars in B4 to insert the relevant information into the label. His account of handwritten notes being captured in the JPEG files was clearly an afterthought, hatched under the heat of cross-examination to plug a gaping hole in his story. In any event, the notion of the radiographs being photographed alongside such handwritten notes went against the Accused’s testimony about how photographs of radiographs were prepared. According to the Accused, the radiograph would be put against a light box and a digital camera would then be used to capture an image of the radiograph.[note: 811] This exact same procedure was described by Loo Hwee Hoon, who was the Practice Manager at the Accused’s clinic at the relevant time.[note: 812] Neither of them made any mention of putting handwritten notes alongside the radiograph on the lightbox, when capturing the photograph.

468    These gaps in JJ Ng’s account of how he went about preparing the photographs makes it extremely difficult to accept that he was the one who inserted the labels with the patient’s name, procedure date and tooth number.

469    Thirdly, it is obvious that JJ Ng’s very late introduction as a material factual witness was an afterthought. The Accused’s Long Statement made no mention of JJ Ng, nor, for that matter, did the Accused’s oral testimony in court. The very first time the court was apprised of JJ Ng’s impending appearance was towards the end of cross-examination of what was supposed to have been the final Defence witness, Dr Firdaus. At that point, Lead Defence Counsel Mr Foo foreshadowed that he did not have instructions to close his case and intimated that he was discharging himself.[note: 813] Even at that juncture, the Defence did not specifically name JJ Ng. It was only on the next day, after completion of Dr Firdaus’ re-examination, that the court was given JJ Ng’s name.[note: 814] The Prosecution objected, saying that it had been taken by “unfair surprise” by the late calling of JJ Ng as a witness.[note: 815] I asked the Defence to explain why JJ Ng was being called so late in the day. Mr Daniel Atticus Xu replied, surprisingly, that he could not give me an answer and suggested that I check with the new lead counsel coming on board to replace Mr Foo.[note: 816] When I pressed Mr Xu on this, he said that JJ Ng was being called at the eleventh-hour because the Accused met JJ Ng only recently, by way of a chance encounter.[note: 817]

470    When JJ Ng eventually took the stand, he gave his account of how that chance encounter with the Accused unfolded. It was, in short, a tale that beggared belief. JJ Ng testified that he had fortuitously met the Accused on 8 July 2022 at the vicinity of Cuppage Road,[note: 818] after not having seen the Accused for eight years.[note: 819] He saw the Accused from afar and called out to him.[note: 820] At that point, the Accused had a mask (it being the COVID season) covering his chin.[note: 821] Upon being called by JJ Ng, the Accused looked at him and tried to recall who he was. This prompted JJ Ng to introduce himself as “Kenn”, from the Punggol Field branch of the Accused’s clinic. This triggered the Accused’s recollection of who JJ Ng was.[note: 822] JJ Ng had then asked the Accused how he was, to which the Accused replied that he was not good.[note: 823] The Accused then opened up to JJ Ng about his problems with MoH and his involvement in a “lawsuit” (meaning the present criminal trial).[note: 824] The Accused also elaborated to JJ Ng that the “lawsuit” pertained to incidents that happened in 2014. This prompted JJ Ng to remind the Accused that he had worked for the Accused in that very window of time, in 2014.[note: 825] JJ Ng also offered to help the Accused.[note: 826] The Accused nevertheless rejected the offer of assistance.[note: 827] However, a few days later, the Accused initiated another meeting with JJ Ng, this time at the Botanic Gardens. At that latter meeting, JJ Ng reminded the Accused about how JJ Ng had been engaged to label the photographs that were sent for the audit. JJ Ng then asked the Accused to check with his lawyers to see if there was anything that JJ Ng could do to help.[note: 828] This eventually led to JJ Ng taking the stand.

471    The above account of the serendipitous meeting between the Accused and JJ Ng is farfetched, on multiple counts:

(a)     JJ Ng testified that when he worked for the Accused, he only had occasion to speak to the Accused face-to-face once (see paragraph 463 above). The interaction was thus sparse, to say the least. Considering that the purported Cuppage Road encounter took place some eight years819 after that sparse interaction, any limited impression that JJ Ng might have had of the Accused must have been diluted by the lapse of time. I agree with the Prosecution’s submission that, by the time of the Cuppage Road encounter, the relational link between both men would have grown so remote as to approximate that between strangers[note: 829] (not to say that it was even close to start with). Furthermore, the Accused’s chin was covered with a mask during the Cuppage Road encounter,821 meaning that JJ Ng was not even able to see the Accused’s entire face. Notwithstanding the collective operation of all these factors, JJ Ng was amazingly able to recognise the Accused from a distance.

(b)     Despite their past dealings being both limited in scope and remote in time, the Accused still readily confided in JJ Ng on what must have been a very personal affair – his criminal charges. The Accused told JJ Ng that he was “not good” and spoke about his “lawsuit”. This very candid disclosure allowed the focus of the conversation to pivot, with the year of the alleged offences (ie, 2014) being brought to the fore, thereby triggering JJ Ng to point out that this was the period of his brief stint working for the Accused.

(c)     Despite JJ Ng’s magnanimity at the Cuppage Road encounter in offering to help the Accused, the latter rejected the offer. It was unclear why the Accused turned JJ Ng away. The Cuppage Road encounter took place on 8 July 2022, by which point, all the witnesses in the trial had completed their testimonies, save for the Defence expert Dr Firdaus. The full shape of the case that the Accused had to meet must have been patently clear by then. Yet, no explanation was proffered as to why the Accused turned JJ Ng down at the Cuppage Road encounter, only to reach out to him subsequently to orchestrate the Botanic Gardens meeting.

Over and above the individual considerations above, the sheer coincidence inherent in JJ Ng’s account would not be lost on the reader. It was JJ Ng’s evidence that he was employed by the clinic for only a very limited window of time, in the year 2014, during which he had turned up at each of the clinic’s two branches for only four or five occasions (to collect the photographs) and spoke to the Accused face-to-face only once. Yet, this extremely narrow window coincided with the very incident at the centre of the forgery charges, ie, the MoH audit. JJ Ng had then lost contact with the Accused for eight whole years thereafter, only to suddenly bump into the Accused just as the Defence was closing its case.

472    I thus have no hesitation in rejecting JJ Ng’s account of the chance encounter at Cuppage Road. This then leaves the Defence with no satisfactory explanation as to why JJ Ng was neither mentioned in the Accused’s Long Statements nor raised in the Accused’s oral testimony, having been brought in as a witness only at the 59th minute of the eleventh hour. My conclusion above, that JJ Ng was called as an afterthought, thus remains unmoved. This conclusion, coupled with my observations as to:

(a)     the incredible circumstances by which JJ Ng purportedly came to be engaged by the Accused to prepare the photographs in the forgery charges; and

(b)     the gaping holes in JJ Ng’s account as regards how he managed to glean the patient particulars that were used to label the photographs,

leaves me without a doubt that JJ Ng’s testimony was an outright fabrication.

Loo Hwee Hoon’s evidence

473    Loo Hwee Hoon was employed as a practice manager at the Accused’s clinic from April 2011 to October 2017[note: 830] – this thus covered the period in 2014 when the photographs in the forgery charges were tendered to MoH for the audit. Her role as practice manager included taking care of the clinic’s day-to-day operations, as well as managing patients and employees.[note: 831]

474    Loo Hwee Hoon testified that she had not seen the Accused taking photographs of radiographs or retrieving the soft copy images to print them out.[note: 832] She also testified that any staff on the payroll may get delegated to perform these tasks in an MoH audit.[note: 833] The Defence relies on this to argue that the Accused had no window of opportunity to manipulate the photographs.[note: 834] Specifically, the Defence contends that:

(a)     Based on Loo Hwee Hoon’s experience of not ever having seen the Accused retrieving the photographs and printing them, this meant that it could only be the staff who extracted the JPEG files from the digital camera and sent these to JJ Ng.

(b)     JJ Ng would then edit the soft copies of the images in the JPEG files (by adding the labels), before printing them out and sending the printed photographs back to the clinic.

(c)     Once the photographs were returned to the clinic, they would already be in printed form, meaning that the Accused could no longer use photo editing software to embellish the images.[note: 835]

475    This argument is unconvincing. Firstly, it hinges on JJ Ng’s account (of how he prepared the photographs) being true. As explained above, I found his testimony to be a fabrication. It is also difficult for me to ignore how Loo Hwee Hoon, throughout her entire testimony, had not for once even mentioned the existence of JJ Ng, let alone his involvement in the clinic’s operations.

476    Secondly, while Loo Hwee Hoon may have said that she had not personally seen the Accused taking photographs of radiographs or retrieving the images from the camera, it is a quantum leap to say that the Accused had “no window of opportunity” to do so. Loo Hwee Hoon clearly qualified her testimony by saying that she was not involved in the entire process:

Q    And what would you do with the picture thus taken by the camera?

A    Um, they remain in the camera, as what I understand, and use for the audit’s, um, data collection. Um, but, um, I’m not involved in the whole process of it.

[emphasis added]

Loo Hwee Hoon’s qualifier was fitting, given the Accused’s statement that he would sometimes label and print the photographs in his own home −see paragraph 455 above. Clearly, Loo Hwee Hoon would not be there at the Accused’s home to witness him do this.

477    When she was asked, point blank, if the Accused did take photographs of the radiographs and print them out, she made it clear that her negative reply was premised on an assumption:[note: 836]

Q    Okay. Now, specifically now, have you ever seen Dr. Sng retrieved radiographs place him on light boxes, take photographs of them, and then print them out for the purposes of submission to MOH request for audit.

A    I’ve not seen him done so in the clinic of course.

Q    But do you know whether he does do so? Sorry, he did do so, it was in the past. Do you know whether he did do so?

A    If I’ve not seen it, I ca---I would assume it’s a no, yah.

[emphasis added]

478    As such, Loo Hwee Hoon’s testimony does nothing to shake the clear admission in the Long Statements that it was the Accused who prepared the photographs that were the subject of the forgery charges.

Was it the Accused who submitted the photographs to MoH?

479    Having decided that it was the Accused who prepared the photographs in the forgery charges, the next issue is whether it was also he who sent these photographs to MoH for the audit.

480    In his Long Statement (B38), the Accused categorically admitted that he was the one who issued the instructions for submission of the documents to MoH for audit:

Q 78:

Who prepared the documents submitted to MOH for the audit?

A:

I will check the patient cards for the procedures that they are auditing, and then take out the relevant X-rays that are needed. Mdm Loo will consolidate these documents and bundle them and send to MOH.

Q 79:

Who gave instructions to this person to prepare the documents to be submitted to MOH for the audit?

A:

I will.

…

Q 82:

Who were involved in the preparation of the documents submitted to MOH for the audit?

A:

Me and Mdm Loo and Joey.

Q 83:

What were their roles?

A:

I will check the patient cards for the procedures that they are auditing, and then take out the relevant X-rays that are needed. Mdm Loo will consolidate these documents and bundle them and send to MOH .

[emphasis added]



481    The Defence nevertheless seeks to raise doubts by highlighting two possibilities −that the photographs in the forgery charges, which had been seized from the Accused’s residence during the raid, were either:

(a)      never submitted to MoH for the audit; or

(b)     submitted to MoH, but without the Accused’s approval.

I find both suggestions to be unsupported by the evidence, for the reasons below.

Suggestion that the photographs were never submitted to MoH

482    During the cross-examination of IO Beverly, Defence Counsel suggested that the photographs in the forgery charges, which had been seized from the Accused during the raid, were never submitted to MoH:[note: 837]

Q:

… I’m constrained to put to you that the originals of the patient’s operations report which carries with them the photoprints in a transparent ziplock bag at the upper right-hand corner of each page, that is to say, to wit B35, 36, and 37, were prepared by the accused for internal approval by his clinic and not submitted and that’s why they were seized from his house.

DPP:

… I would be grateful if my learned friend could explain what he means by “internal approval by his clinic”.

DC:

That---that would be---that would be downstream when the accused give his Evidence-in-Chief. So, maybe I can change my put to the witness by saying that these were drafts which were never submitted by Dr. Sng to MOH.



483    I reject the suggestion that the photographs were meant for “internal approval” and thus never submitted to MoH for the audit. Firstly, the Defence never explained what it meant by the term “internal approval”. In the extract from IO Beverly’s cross-examination above, Defence Counsel indicated that the Accused would explain in his evidence-in-chief what “internal approval” meant. However, no such explanation was given during the Accused’s evidence-in-chief. The Prosecution had to pursue this in cross-examination, by asking the Accused what Defence Counsel meant by saying that the photographs were meant for “internal approval”, to which the Accused replied that “I think the statement is a bit off” and that he could not recall Defence Counsel’s statement.[note: 838] The Accused then clarified that what was conveyed simply meant that the documents were “drafts” that were never submitted.[note: 839]

484    However, the notion that the photographs in the forgery charges (seized from the Accused’s residence) were never submitted to MoH was debunked by Ker Lai Sim, who testified that she made colour photocopies of the photographs and operation reports submitted by the Accused’s clinic to MoH for the audit. As explained at paragraph 233 above, Ker Lai Sim had created the following exhibits from the documents submitted by the Accused’s clinic:

(a)     P6A, being a colour photocopy of Catherine Chia’s operation report and three photographs of her teeth;

(b)     P7A, being a colour photocopy of Chong Moh Chin’s operation report and four photographs of her teeth; and

(c)     P8A, being a colour photocopy of Neo Kheng Yew’s operation report and four photographs of his teeth.

485    More importantly, during her testimony in court, Ker Lai Sim scrutinized the photographs in B35(1)-(2), B36(1)-(4) and B37(1)-(4), which had been seized from the Accused’s residence, and confirmed that:

(a)     B35(1)-(3) were the three photographs copied by her in P6A.[note: 840]

(b)     B36(1)-(4) were the four photographs copied by her in P7A.[note: 841]

(c)     B37(1)-(4) were the four photographs copied by her in P8A.[note: 842]

After making these copies, she had returned the photographs and operation reports to the Accused’s clinic, under the cover letter exhibited at exhibit P10. The Prosecution’s case is that these photographs were then seized by the police from the Accused’s residence, during the raid.

486    Ker Lai Sim’s evidence is thus clear. The photographs in the forgery charges, seized from the Accused’s residence, were one and the same as those submitted to MoH for the audit, which Ker Lai Sim had copied before returning to the Accused’s clinic. Her testimony on this was unchallenged during cross-examination, where all the Defence did was to refer to P10 and get Ker Lai Sim to confirm that MoH, in returning the documents to the Accused’s clinic, did not explicitly list the contents of what was being returned.[note: 843] No suggestion was made to her about MoH mistakenly returning photographs other than those submitted by the Accused’s clinic for the audit.

487    I should add that Ker Lai Sim’s evidence can also be corroborated by a visual comparison of the images in P6A, P7A and P8A with the photographs in B35(1)-(3), B36(1)-(4) and B37(1)-(4), which shows that the former clearly captured the latter.

Suggestion that the photographs were submitted to MoH without Accused’s approval

488    At one point in the trial, the Accused also canvassed the possibility of his staff submitting the photographs to MoH for the audit without his approval. He suggested that his administrative staff might have mistakenly submitted the photographs to MoH even before he had a chance to sort them out.[note: 844]

489    In support of this suggestion, the Accused points out that when the photographs were seized from his residence, the police found multiple photographs for each patient stored in a single Ziplock sachet.[note: 845] Specifically:

(a)     In respect of Catherine Chia, the three photographs B35(1)-(3) were stored in a single Ziplock sachet and stapled to the supporting documents.[note: 846]

(b)     In respect of Chong Moh Chin, the four photographs B36(1)-(4) were stored in a single Ziplock sachet and stapled to the supporting documents.[note: 847]

(c)     In respect of Neo Kheng Yew, the four photographs B37(1)-(4) were stored in a single Ziplock sachet and stapled to the supporting documents.[note: 848]

The Accused claimed that this state in which the photographs were found was inconsistent with his practice when submitting documents for audit, which was to store each photograph in a separate Ziplock sachet.[note: 849] The Accused suggested that if the photographs had been submitted to MoH with multiple photographs stored in a single Ziplock sachet, they were likely submitted by his staff to MoH before he had a chance to sort them out.[note: 850]

490    In support of this suggestion, the Accused tendered two sets of documents, admitted as exhibits D21 and D22. These were documents that his clinic submitted to MoH, for an audit of procedures performed in 2011. Unlike in the present case, what was submitted in D21 and D22 to MoH for audit were not just photographs of radiographs −they were the original radiographs. The Accused pointed to how, in both D21 and D22, each radiograph was enclosed in a separate Ziplock sachet.[note: 851] This cohered with his practice of putting individual photographs into separate Ziplock sachets. This also showed that the state in which the photographs in the forgery charges were found at the point of seizure, where multiple photographs were collectively stored in a single Ziplock sachet, was not something the Accused would have done.

491    I fail to see the relevance of exhibits D21 and D22. Back in 2011, when these two exhibits were submitted to MoH for audit, the Accused had a different practice for such submissions. Specifically, he would submit the original radiograph, as was done with D21 and D22. This practice subsequently evolved and, by the time of the 2014 audit, he was submitting photographs of the radiographs, as was the case with the photographs that are the subject of the forgery charges.[note: 852] The superseded practice of submitting original radiographs to MoH for audit, well as the associated practice of enclosing each radiograph in a separate Ziplock sachet within the submission, thus has no relevance to the present case (where the submission to MoH followed the updated practice of submitting photographs, and not original radiographs). The Defence did not adduce any evidence of more recent audits where photographs (rather than original radiographs) were submitted for audit. Nor did the Defence call any clinic staff to testify how photographs of radiographs would be enclosed when submitted to MoH for audit.

492    In any case, the suggestion that the clinic staff could simply send documents to MoH for audit without the Accused’s approval runs counter to the evidence of Loo Hwee Hoon, who testified repeatedly that all documents submitted to MoH have to go to the Accused for approval:[note: 853]

Q:    But the point that I’m trying to make is that ultimately, the documents would go to Dr. Sng before they are submitted to MOH for audit.

A    The---hmm, no, yes.

Q    So therefore, you would agree with me that whenever documents are submitted to MOH by your practice, Dr. Sng has to approved them before they are---they are given to---to MOH?

A    I would agree that he has to look at it, yah, approved them before we submit.

…

Q    … So, what you are saying is that as far as you know, the documents are given to Dr. Sng before submission to MOH?

A    Yes. I agree.

Q    But---but you are not able to say whether he looks at them or not?

A    I agree.

…

Q    Because the general process in the practice was that before documents are submitted pursuant to an audit, they had to go to Dr. Sng?

A     Agree.

[emphasis added]

493    Loo Hwee Hoon’s evidence thus corroborated the admission in the Accused’s Long Statement that submissions to MoH for audit were cleared through him. The Accused’s claim that the photographs in the forgery charges were submitted to MoH without his approval is thus not borne out by the evidence.

The “chain of custody” argument
