494    At a broader level, the Defence also argues that the Prosecution failed to prove the “chain of custody” in respect of the photographs.[note: 854] Specifically, the Defence argues that the Prosecution failed to show that the photographs returned by MoH to the Accused’s clinic after the audit were the same as the photographs seized from the Accused’s residence.[note: 855]

495    As a preliminary observation, this submission was premised on a misunderstanding of the chain of custody concept. The authorities which the Defence cites in support of its submission[note: 856] all focus on proper custody of the exhibits after seizure by the law enforcement agency. It is trite that once exhibits enter the agency’s custody, it is incumbent on the agency to ensure that the handling of the exhibits, from point of seizure to the point of adduction in court, is properly documented. This provides assurance that the integrity of the exhibits has not been compromised. There is therefore no chain of custody issue here, as the Defence has not raised any concerns pertaining to post-seizure management of the photographs in the forgery charges.

496    Rather, the submission focuses on what happened to the photographs after MoH returned them to the Accused’s clinic (under the cover letter B10, dated 25 September 2014) and before the police seized them from his residence during the raid (on 8 July 2015). The Defence stresses[note: 857] how close to 10 months elapsed within this window. Presumably, the concern here is that during this window of time, the photographs may have been tampered with or swapped, thereby breaking the “chain of custody”.

497    This argument is without merit. The police found the photographs at the Accused’s residence and tendered them to court, where they were admitted as B35(1)-(3), B36(1)-(4) and B37(1)-(4). As explained at paragraph 485 above, it was Ker Lai Sim’s evidence that these very photographs were the photographs that MoH received (and consequently captured in the photocopies admitted as P6A, P7A and P8A). This suffices to establish the link between the photographs submitted to MoH for the audit, and the photographs seized from the Accused’s residence and thereafter tendered in court. It is of course open to the Accused to try and break this link, perhaps by adducing evidence showing that something untoward may have happened to the photographs during those 10 months, either while they were at the clinic (after having been returned from MoH) or after they made their way to the Accused’s residence (before the seizure). It is also obvious that given the venues at issue, if there had indeed been any potential for tampering, the Accused was in the best position to tender evidence on that, eg, by calling the clinic staff to explain what happened to the photographs after they were returned to the clinic by MoH, or adducing evidence to show what might have happened to the photographs after the Accused brought them home. However, no such evidence was adduced. In fact, the Accused did not raise any suggestion at trial about post-audit tampering of the photographs, choosing to highlight this as a possibility only in submissions at the close of trial.

498    As such, Ker Lai Sim’s evidence, to the effect that the photographs that MoH received from the Accused’s clinic were the same as those tendered in court, remains unshaken.

Conclusion on the Forgery Charges

499    Section 468 of the Penal Code reads:

Whoever commits forgery, intending that the document or electronic record forged shall be used for the purpose of cheating, shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 10 years, and shall also be liable to fine.

There are thus two broad requirements for this offence.

(a)     Firstly, there must be a forgery. The term “forgery” has been defined by s 463 of the Penal Code to include, inter alia, the making of a false document to support any claim:

Whoever makes any false document or electronic record or part of a document or an electronic record with intent to cause damage or injury to the public or to any person, or to support any claim or title, or to cause any person to part with property, or to enter into any express or implied contract, or with intent to commit fraud or that fraud may be committed, commits forgery.

[emphasis added]

The term “false document” is in turn defined by s 464(1)(b) of the Penal Code to include a document that has been dishonestly altered:

A person is said to make a false document or false electronic record —

…

(b)    who without lawful authority, dishonestly or fraudulently, by cancellation or otherwise, alters a document or an electronic record in any material part thereof, after it has been made, executed or affixed with an electronic signature …

[emphasis added]

(b)     Secondly, there must have been an intention to use the forged document for the purpose of cheating. The term “cheating” is in turn defined by s 415 of the Penal Code:

Whoever, by deceiving any person, whether or not such deception was the sole or main inducement, fraudulently or dishonestly induces the person so deceived to deliver any property to any person, or to consent that any person shall retain any property, or intentionally induces the person so deceived to do or omit to do anything which he would not do or omit to do if he were not so deceived, and which act or omission causes or is likely to cause damage or harm to any person in body, mind, reputation or property, is said to “cheat”.

[emphasis added]

500    Applying these legal requirements to the facts, I am satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that the Accused is guilty of the following seven forgery charges. As explained above, I find that the photographs in these charges had been altered, in the manner described below:

(a)      DAC 922428/2018: B35(1) was an image of the radiograph P3(1)A, which had been altered by the addition of a white dot at tooth #33.

(b)      DAC 922431/2018: B36(1) was an image of the radiograph P3(2)A, which had been altered by the addition of a white dot at tooth #16.

(c)      DAC 922433/2018: B36(3) was an image of the radiograph P3(2)C, which had altered by the tooth socket at tooth #36 being made to look more distinct.

(d)      DAC 922434/2018: B36(4) was also an image of the radiograph P3(2)C, which had been altered by the addition of white dots above the bone line at tooth #36.

(e)      DAC 922436/2018: B37(1) was an image of the radiograph P3(3)B, which had been altered by the tooth socket at tooth #46 being made to look more distinct.

(f)      DAC 922437/2018: B37(2) was also an image of the radiograph P3(3)B, which had been altered by the addition of white dots above the bone line at tooth #46.

(g)      DAC 922435/2018: B37(3) was an image of the same radiograph captured by B37(4), which had been altered by the addition of a white dot at tooth #17.

501    In finding that these photographs were images of the source radiographs above, I place significant weight on the striking similarities which the photographs bore to the alleged source radiograph, in terms of:

(a)     the shape and positioning of the anatomical structures, and/or

(b)     the replication of features on the radiograph that were clearly not part of the anatomical context (eg, scratches or indentations on the radiograph’s film, or artefacts captured in the radiographic image).

In contrast, the multitude of dissimilarities in features (such as dots, lines, and other shapes) and differences in appearance (in terms of brightness, definition and texture), highlighted by the Defence, were not inconsistent with variations arising from reprographic error during capture or printing of the image.

502    As regards the alterations made to the images, I find that they were deliberately made. These alterations were strategically placed to give the impression that the procedures subjected to the audit had been performed when, as per my findings in the cheating charges above, they had not been performed.

503    I am also satisfied, based on the evidence (including the Accused’s Long Statements), that it was the Accused who prepared the seven photographs at paragraph 500 above. It was thus the Accused who altered these photographs in the manner set out in the forgery charges. The defence that the photographs were prepared by JJ Ng was, without a doubt, a fabrication.

504    Given the nature of the alterations to the photographs, the Accused must have known that they were calculated to give the impression that the audited procedures were performed, when he never performed them. This much is clear from the following replies in his Long Statement B39:

Q 149:

Why did you have to make these 4 radiograph photo prints labelled ‘1’, ‘2’, ‘3’ and ‘4’?

A:

MOH requires us to submit the radiographs with patient name, and date of procedure for audit purposes. The radiograph is supposed to show and support the procedure that I had submitted in my Medisave claim.

Q 150:

What happens if you do not produce such radiographs to MOH?

A:

MOH will reject the claim if I don’t produce pre-operation and post-operation radiographs to support the claim that I had submitted. I have to show a set of two of pre-operation and post-operation for all procedures. … So I have to prepare such radiographs to show the procedures that I submitted in my claims. If the claim is rejected, MOH will ask me for a refund of the Medisave monies that had disbursed to the clinic. I have to either cancel the claim and return the whole sum disbursed, or amend the claim to return the rejected procedure/ portion.

[emphasis added]



Consequently, I infer that the Accused acted dishonestly in altering the seven photographs in paragraph 500 above.

505    These conclusions thus establish the first requirement for the offence under s 468 of the Penal Code, ie, that there was a “forgery”, as defined by s 463 of the Penal Code. The forgery was constituted by the making of “false documents” to support the claim that the audited procedures had been performed. In this case, the seven photographs listed in paragraph 500 above were “false documents”, within the meaning of s 464(1)(b) of the Penal Code, as they had been dishonestly altered by the Accused.

506    I am also satisfied that it was the Accused who sent the photographs to MoH. As he did so knowing that the photographs were forgeries, it could be inferred that he sent the photographs with the intention of deceiving the MoH auditors into thinking that the audited procedures were performed. This deception, if successful, would allow the Accused to keep the sums he had received from the false Medisave claims. This means that the second requirement for the offence under s 468 of the Penal Code has been satisfied. The forgeries (ie, the dishonest alterations to the photographs) were committed for the purpose of “cheating”, as that term is defined by s 415 of the Penal Code. The “cheating” here was the deception of the MoH auditors into thinking that the audited procedures had been performed, thereby inducing them to consent to the Accused retaining the proceeds from the false Medisave claims.

507    I thus convict the Accused of the seven forgery charges listed in paragraph 500 above.

508    I also acquit the Accused of the remaining four forgery charges, for the reasons below:

(a)      DAC 922429/2018: While I am satisfied that B35(2) was an image P3A(1), I am not sufficiently satisfied that the image had been altered to make the tooth socket look more distinct.

(b)      DAC 922430/2018: As for B35(3), I am not sufficiently satisfied that this was an image of P3(1)C, nor am I convinced that the white dots in B35(3) were added.

(c)      DAC 922432/2018: While I am satisfied that B36(2) was an image of P3(2)(A), there is insufficient evidence to satisfy me that the date inserted in B36(2) was false.

(d)      DAC 922438/2018: There is a complete dearth of evidence to show the white dot was added to the photograph reproduced in P4.

Sentence

509    I will now hear the parties on the appropriate sentences for the cheating and forgery charges on which the Accused has been convicted.
